# product
- Satelle lets a human-authorized client, script, or AI agent start, inspect, steer, stop, and recover durable native Computer Use sessions on operator-controlled remote desktops through stable CLI, JSON, event, HTTP, WebSocket, and MCP contracts @spec @mvp
- Satelle's primary Operator is the person or organization that owns or administers the controlled Host and authorizes Host Bindings, provider credentials, desktop access, unsafe execution policy, and state-changing maintenance @spec @mvp
- Satelle's primary Client is a human-operated CLI, script, AI agent, or MCP consumer acting only within authority explicitly granted by the Operator @spec @mvp
- Satelle is a self-hosted control plane, not a hosted relay, generic remote desktop viewer, or replacement Computer Use runtime @spec @mvp
- Satelle differentiates through agent-oriented structured contracts, user-controlled deployment, durable session control, and auditable safety behavior @spec @mvp
- Satelle keeps authoritative Host, Session, Turn, and diagnostic state on Operator-controlled machines unless the Operator explicitly exports an artifact @spec @mvp
- Satelle's primary successful-use journey configures and trusts one Host, completes satelle setup --verify, runs one attached Turn to completion and captures its reusable Session identifier, reconnects a fresh Client, reads current status, starts one detached steer Turn on the same Session, stops that active Turn, and confirms the stopped state through status @spec @mvp
- Satelle public MVP acceptance requires the primary successful-use journey and recovery after client reconnect to pass end to end on every declared MVP Computer Use Host Platform @spec @mvp @release-gate @verification
- Satelle public MVP acceptance requires the same public Session, error, and event contracts across SSH-tunneled and direct transports @spec @mvp @release-gate @verification

# domain
- a Satelle Bridge is a self-hosted control plane that orchestrates native Computer Use through a compatible upstream agent runtime instead of implementing screenshot and input automation itself @spec @mvp
- Open Computer Use is reference material for Satelle native Computer Use protocol shape, readiness checks, and failure modes, not a Satelle runtime adapter, backend dependency, or remote-host requirement @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Operator is the human or organization that owns the controlled Host and grants authority to Satelle Clients @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Client is a human-operated CLI, script, AI agent, or MCP consumer that invokes Satelle within Operator-granted authority @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Controller is the machine and OS user running the Satelle CLI or MCP Server @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Controller Platform is an operating system on which the local CLI, MCP Server, and remote-management workflows are supported @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Computer Use Host Platform is an operating system on which Satelle supports native Computer Use execution @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Host is one Host Daemon identity owned by one daemon OS account @spec @mvp
- an MVP Satelle Host owns exactly one explicitly authorized Desktop Binding @spec @mvp
- a later broker-capable Satelle Host may own multiple explicitly authorized Desktop Bindings @spec @later
- a Satelle Host Identity is a stable random identifier generated and stored by one Host Daemon installation @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Host Alias is a stable logical name used by projects, profiles, commands, and public output to select a Satelle Host @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Host Binding is the user-level mapping from a Host Alias to a concrete transport endpoint, authentication descriptor, Desktop Binding, Host-owned provider configuration, and optional expected Host Identity before first trust @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Host Daemon is a remote-machine service that owns Host checks, Codex app-server lifecycle, capability probes, authoritative state, and Satelle Client connections @spec @mvp
- a Satelle API Principal is one authenticated Client token identity with explicit permission scopes @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Session is a durable Satelle-owned control record mapped internally to one Satelle Host and one upstream Codex thread @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Turn is one run or steer execution attempt that belongs to exactly one Satelle Session @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Goal is optional lifecycle metadata attached to a Session or upstream thread and does not replace Turn control @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Execution Policy is the Host-enforced combination of approval, sandbox, timeout, provider, model, desktop, and experimental-feature choices for one Turn @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Control Lease is the Host Daemon-owned exclusive right to operate one Host Identity and Desktop Binding through native Computer Use @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Maintenance Lease is the Host Daemon-owned exclusive right to mutate daemon, runtime, service, or storage state for one Host @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Bootstrap Lock is a user-scoped remote filesystem lock acquired through authenticated SSH bootstrap or by a reachable Host Daemon already holding the same operation's Maintenance Lease before remote daemon files can be replaced @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Idempotency Record binds one API Principal, operation, idempotency key, request digest, and durable outcome @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Readiness Result is a timestamped capability result whose validity is bounded by its cache key, expiry, and invalidation conditions @spec @mvp
- Satelle YOLO Mode is an explicit unsafe execution mode that asks Codex to bypass Codex-controlled approvals and sandboxing where the compatible Codex control plane supports those settings @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Provider Probe Surface is an ephemeral local UI served by the Host Daemon to verify that a selected model and provider can observe and act through native Computer Use @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Event is a stable JSON lifecycle record emitted by attached run and steer commands or Host Daemon event streams @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Setup Action Ledger is the Host Daemon-owned record of setup, repair, update, migration, and other specified maintenance action plans, status changes, partial failures, and recovery metadata for a controlled Host @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Setup Component is a named onboarding responsibility that setup can plan, report, and selectively target without changing the default setup contract @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Trusted Profile is a user-level profile explicitly allowed by the local OS user to supply noninteractive mutation consent for configured command families and Host Aliases @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Mutation Command Family is a stable consent scope grouping one mutating command workflow independently from exact CLI subcommand spelling @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Doctor Finding is a diagnostic result with a scope, severity, fixability, readiness impact, summary, evidence, and optional recovery command @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Doctor Probe is an individual diagnostic check with a stable probe id, scope, dependencies, resource locks, timeout, and cache policy @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Doctor Event is a diagnostic-stream record with its own versioned schema and is distinct from a lifecycle Satelle Event @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Log Entry is a normalized redacted Host Daemon-owned diagnostic record with timestamp, source, severity, Host, optional Session id, message, structured fields, and redaction metadata @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Log Cursor is an opaque durable position used to resume normalized log delivery without acting as a Satelle Event replay cursor @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Operator Log File is a rotating plain-text mirror of redacted Satelle Log Entries for local inspection on the remote Host, not an authoritative store @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Diagnostic Bundle is a redacted local archive for support and debugging that can include selected Host Daemon metadata, Doctor Findings, setup ledger summaries, recent Satelle Log Entries, and export metadata @spec @later
- a Satelle Raw Diagnostic Export is a user-requested local diagnostic artifact that may include data excluded from normal Satelle diagnostics while preserving explicit consent, redaction, retention, and audit boundaries @spec @later
- a Satelle Desktop Snapshot Export is a user-requested local artifact that captures the current visible desktop for one selected Host Identity and Desktop Binding at invocation time and never represents historical Session imagery @spec @later
- a Satelle Recording Mode is an explicitly consented prospective Turn capture of selected screenshots, desktop video, transcripts, or replayable events under finite retention and Host policy @spec @later
- a Satelle Config Include is an explicit reference from one Satelle TOML configuration file to another Satelle TOML configuration file loaded as part of the same user-level or project-level configuration source @spec @later
- a Satelle Executable Credential Helper is a Host-Resolved Secret Source that runs a user-configured executable on the machine resolving provider authentication and returns secret material through the Satelle credential-helper protocol @spec @later
- a Satelle Queued Turn Request is a Host Daemon-owned pending run or steer request waiting to start because the selected Control Lease is occupied @spec @later
- a Satelle Platform-Native Log Sink is an OS-owned logging destination such as journald, Windows Event Log, or macOS unified logging that receives mirrored redacted Satelle Log Entries without becoming a Satelle-owned store @spec @later
- a Satelle Path Set is the runtime-resolved collection of config, cache, local state, operator log, SQLite store, and recording artifact paths for one OS user on one machine @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Desktop Binding is one configured remote OS user account whose compatible visible desktop sessions a Host Daemon is authorized to observe and control @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Desktop Session is one active visible GUI session for a Desktop Binding that native Computer Use can observe and control @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Desktop Session Preference is a Host-level selector that narrows one Desktop Binding to one compatible Desktop Session without changing the bound OS user @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector is an advanced OS-specific selector copied from a Host Daemon session listing for one Computer Use Host Platform @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Multi-User Broker permits an authorized API Principal to select among multiple Desktop Bindings owned by one Host Identity at request time while preserving per-user authorization, isolation, and audit boundaries @spec @later
- a Satelle Secret Source is a typed reference to secret material stored outside Satelle config files, such as an operating-system credential store item, environment variable, file path, or remote-Host-owned provider auth store @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Host-Resolved Secret Source is a Secret Source descriptor containing only a non-secret lookup reference and resolved by the target Host Daemon on the machine running the selected provider binding @spec @mvp
- a Satelle File Secret Source is a Secret Source whose value is a path to a file containing secret material on the machine resolving that provider authentication binding @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Provider Binding maps requested model and provider intent to a concrete upstream model, provider endpoint, and Host-Resolved Secret Source @spec @mvp
- a Satelle MCP Server is a local stdio JSON-RPC bridge exposing selected Satelle control surfaces as tools for AI Clients @spec @mvp
- a Satelle AI Client Install Target is a supported AI client configuration destination that can be updated to call Satelle through MCP @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Agent Skill Bundle is a versioned set of Satelle-owned SKILL.md guides for AI agents setting up, using, and recovering Satelle @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Automation Workflow is a user-requested batch, watch, notify, or REPL flow that coordinates Satelle commands without changing underlying authority and safety rules @spec @later
- a Satelle Command History Entry is a local redacted record of one Satelle command invocation, outcome, duration, target, and stable command family @spec @mvp

# brand
- Satelle is the canonical product name for the remote computer-use bridge @implemented @mvp
- satelle is the canonical local CLI executable name @implemented @mvp
- Satelle name selection accepts the known online availability caveat that satelle has an existing AI-agent-adjacent GitHub repository collision and still treats Satelle as the chosen MVP product identity @spec @mvp
- Satelle's brand metaphor is satellite-adjacent remote presence, command uplink, telemetry downlink, and visible remote operation rather than generic remote desktop administration @implemented @mvp
- Satelle's Beacon Coral palette is the selected MVP brand palette rather than a placeholder palette @implemented @mvp
- Satelle's primary brand color is Beacon Coral #FF5E5B / oklch(0.693 0.197 24.774) @implemented @mvp
- Satelle's default dark brand surface is Orbit Ink #0F0D17 / oklch(0.167 0.021 293.174) @implemented @mvp
- Satelle's primary light text color is Platinum #D6D8E0 / oklch(0.883 0.011 274.878) @implemented @mvp
- Satelle's secondary accent color is Relay Rose #FF8FB1 / oklch(0.779 0.139 1.409) @implemented @mvp
- Satelle cliclack prompts use Beacon Coral for prompt glyphs, active selections, and primary brand emphasis @spec @mvp
- Satelle cliclack prompts use Relay Rose only for sparse highlights so normal CLI screens do not become one-note pink @spec @mvp
- Satelle cliclack prompts use #A6E22E / oklch(0.841 0.204 127.286) for success states and #FF4D6D / oklch(0.679 0.213 14.719) for error or cancel states @spec @mvp
- Satelle color output respects terminal no-color and dumb-terminal conventions by falling back to plain text without changing command behavior @spec @mvp

# cli

## foundations
- the satelle CLI is implemented in Rust @implemented @mvp
- satelle --version writes exactly satelle <version> followed by one newline to stdout and exits 0 without contacting a Host @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle CLI parsing uses clap derive for commands, subcommands, flags, help text, and future shell completion support @implemented @mvp
- satelle interactive setup uses the Rust cliclack crate for setup intro and outro prompt framing @implemented @mvp

## completions
- satelle exposes shell completion generation for bash, zsh, fish, and PowerShell @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle completions <bash|zsh|fish|powershell> --output-dir <directory> installs the selected shell's canonical completion filename, while omitting the shell with --output-dir detects SHELL and falls back to PowerShell only on Windows; installation creates the output directory, writes the installed path followed by one newline to stdout, does not modify shell profiles, and does not initialize Host, config, or state paths @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle completion installation filesystem failures use the completion-install-failed error code and exit 73 without printing a Rust panic or backtrace @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle completions <bash|zsh|fish|powershell> --output-dir <directory> --update-profile <file> atomically creates or updates the explicit profile file with exactly one shell-specific Satelle-managed activation block, preserves the existing Unix mode and every byte outside that block, remains byte-idempotent on repeated runs, and keeps stdout as the installed completion path followed by one newline @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle completion profile updates reject malformed managed markers, invalid UTF-8, and non-regular profile paths without changing the profile, using completion-profile-update-failed and exit 73 without a Rust panic or backtrace @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle completions <bash|zsh|fish|powershell> writes the selected shell completion script to stdout, exits 0, and does not initialize Host, config, or state paths @spec @contract @mvp @implemented

## profiles-and-output
- satelle supports a global --profile option that applies selected user-level configuration profile overlays rather than only reporting the selected profile name @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle recognizes only the SATELLE_* namespace for Satelle-owned process environment variables and does not preserve pre-Satelle environment compatibility aliases @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP command data output modes are human and json; a command-specific streaming contract may define json as versioned NDJSON instead of one final JSON value @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP uses --format <human|json> as the canonical command data output selector for commands that support machine-readable output @mvp @implemented
- satelle later adds compact-json, toon, and markdown command data formats only after each format has a stable lossless mapping from the command's canonical JSON contract @spec @later
- satelle later tabular inspection commands add csv only when every emitted field has a stable column contract and no nested data would be lost @spec @later
- satelle compact-json output emits one minified JSON value for commands that otherwise emit one pretty JSON value @spec @later
- satelle TOON output is a token-efficient structured command result format and never replaces JSON as the canonical machine-readable contract @spec @later
- satelle later expands the canonical selector to --format <human|json|compact-json|toon|markdown|csv>, while each command advertises only formats with a lossless mapping for that command @spec @later
- satelle keeps --json as an exact convenience alias for --format json @mvp @implemented
- satelle reports a typed output-mode-conflict usage error when --json and --format are both provided @mvp @implemented
- satelle command help lists only the output formats supported by that command @mvp @implemented
- satelle --events json remains an NDJSON event-stream selector and is not an alias for final-result --format json @mvp @implemented
- satelle run and steer report a typed output-mode-conflict usage error when --events json is combined with --json or any explicit --format value @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle doctor reports a typed output-mode-conflict usage error when --events is combined with --json or any explicit --format value @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle run, steer, stop, status, setup, repair, doctor, config check, config explain, self update, host update, paths, and host sessions JSON results include a top-level schema_version @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle run JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.run.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle steer JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.steer.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle stop JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.stop.v1 @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle stop JSON v1 includes outcome, session_id, turn_id, previous_state, current_state, changed, and stopped_at fields; outcome is stopped or already_terminal @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle stop on an already-terminal Turn exits 0 with outcome already_terminal and changed false @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle status JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.status.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle logs initial and followed JSON records each use schema_version satelle.logs.entry.v1 and emit exactly one record per line without a top-level wrapper @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle setup JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.setup.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle repair JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.repair.v1 @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle doctor JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.doctor.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle config check JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.config.check.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle config explain JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.config.explain.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle self update JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.self.update.v1 @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle host update JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.host.update.v1 @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle paths JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.paths.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle host sessions JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.host.sessions.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle JSON error v1 uses schema_version satelle.error.v1 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle does not remove fields, change field meanings, or rename enum tokens within one result schema_version @spec @contract @mvp
- breaking machine-readable result changes require a new schema_version @spec @contract @mvp

## automation
- satelle later exposes an interactive REPL for repeated run, steer, status, logs, doctor, and config inspection against one selected context @spec @later
- satelle repl is the exact Automation Workflow command and requires an interactive terminal @spec @later
- satelle later REPL export writes a redacted local transcript of commands, structured outputs, and stable session identifiers without including raw prompts unless the user explicitly requests prompt inclusion @spec @later
- satelle later exposes batch automation for running multiple Satelle operations with bounded concurrency, rate limits, per-item outcomes, and a final aggregate summary @spec @later
- satelle batch --input <path|-> is the exact batch command and reads one satelle.batch.request.v1 JSON object per input line from a file or standard input @spec @contract @later
- satelle batch emits one satelle.batch.result.v1 JSON record per input item followed by one satelle.batch.summary.v1 record, preserving input order for result records even when execution completes out of order @spec @contract @later
- satelle batch defaults to 4 concurrent items, accepts --concurrency values from 1 through 16, and never exceeds the selected Host's admission and API rate limits @spec @later
- satelle batch automation never bypasses host-busy, setup consent, YOLO, Trusted Profile, provider auth, or native Computer Use readiness rules that would apply to each individual command @spec @later
- satelle later exposes watch automation for polling or streaming session, log, doctor, or host state changes and emitting changed records only when requested @spec @later
- satelle watch <sessions|logs|doctor|host> is the exact watch command and emits versioned NDJSON change records until interrupted or its reconnect budget is exhausted @spec @contract @later
- satelle later exposes notify automation for sending selected Satelle state changes to a configured webhook with change-only delivery, bounded retries, and redacted payloads @spec @later
- satelle notify --watch <sessions|logs|doctor|host> --webhook <notifier-alias> is the exact notify command @spec @later
- webhook notifier aliases are defined only in user-level configuration, resolve an HTTPS endpoint plus optional Secret Source authentication on the Controller, and cannot be defined or redirected by project configuration @spec @later
- satelle notify --dry-run emits the redacted versioned webhook payloads without making network requests @spec @later

## distribution
- satelle is distributed as one satelle executable per target, and builds for native Computer Use Host targets contain both Controller commands and Host Daemon mode @spec @mvp
- satelle publishes npm-registry packages as a first-class installation path for npm, pnpm, and bun users @spec @mvp
- satelle publishes the npm-registry package with scope microck and package name satelle as the canonical package identity for the JavaScript launcher and platform-specific native optionalDependencies @spec @mvp
- satelle publishes satelle as an unscoped npm-registry convenience package for shorter install commands @spec @mvp
- satelle unscoped npm-registry package depends on the exact same-version npm package with scope microck and package name satelle and forwards its satelle executable instead of duplicating native optionalDependencies or binary selection logic @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle release validation fails when scoped and unscoped npm-registry package versions, executable behavior, README install guidance, or provenance metadata diverge @spec @mvp
- satelle npm-registry distribution exposes a satelle executable command that launches the Rust native binary instead of reimplementing the CLI in JavaScript @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle npm-registry distribution uses a thin JavaScript launcher or installer layer only for package-manager integration @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle npm, pnpm, and bun installation docs use the same scoped and unscoped npm-registry package identities across package managers instead of separate package identities per package manager @spec @mvp
- satelle installation documentation lists npm, pnpm, and bun npm-registry installs before non-npm methods because npm-registry distribution is the recommended local CLI install path @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP first-party non-npm local install methods are a Unix shell installer, a Windows PowerShell installer, a Homebrew tap, a Scoop bucket, and direct GitHub release archive downloads @spec @mvp
- satelle Unix shell installer supports curl and wget entrypoints that pipe a canonical HTTPS installer script into sh @spec @mvp
- satelle Windows PowerShell installer supports an Invoke-RestMethod entrypoint that pipes a canonical HTTPS installer script into PowerShell @spec @mvp
- satelle install scripts support explicit version selection instead of only installing the latest release @spec @mvp
- satelle install scripts fetch native binaries only from the versioned GitHub release artifact set, require an exact SHA-256 entry for the selected archive in SHA256SUMS, and fail closed before installation when the entry is absent, malformed, or mismatched @spec @release-gate @verification @mvp
- satelle install scripts install to a user-writable bin directory by default and do not require root, administrator, or system-wide installation for ordinary use @spec @mvp
- satelle install scripts do not modify shell profiles, PATH, or PowerShell profiles unless the user explicitly opts in with a flag or interactive consent @spec @mvp
- satelle Homebrew distribution uses a first-party tap in MVP instead of making Homebrew core acceptance a release blocker @spec @mvp
- satelle Scoop distribution uses a first-party Scoop bucket in MVP instead of making Scoop Main acceptance a release blocker @spec @mvp
- satelle package-manager installs through npm, Homebrew, or Scoop rely on the package manager's own upgrade and uninstall flow instead of Satelle self-updating those installations @spec @mvp
- satelle install scripts and direct archive install guidance create or document a local installation receipt that records install_method, binary_path, version, target, artifact_digest, and installed_at metadata @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle self update for binaries installed by the Satelle install scripts or direct GitHub release archive flow when the installation receipt identifies Satelle as the binary owner @spec @mvp
- satelle self update is disabled for npm, pnpm, bun, Homebrew, Scoop, and other package-manager-owned installations @spec @mvp
- satelle self update reports a typed self-update-managed-install error for package-manager-owned installations and includes the detected install method plus the recommended package-manager upgrade command @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports --dry-run to report the current version, latest compatible version, install owner, target artifact, and planned replacement without modifying files @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports --version <version> for explicit version updates using the same versioned GitHub release artifact set as install scripts @spec @mvp
- satelle self update verifies release integrity metadata before replacing the current binary @spec @mvp
- satelle self update never runs automatically during ordinary run, steer, setup, repair, host update, or doctor commands @implemented @mvp
- satelle self update refuses to cross downgrade or prerelease boundaries unless the user explicitly requests a specific version and the release artifact passes integrity checks @spec @mvp
- satelle self update never mutates configured remote hosts as an implicit side effect of replacing the local CLI binary @spec @mvp
- satelle self update after a successful local binary replacement in an interactive terminal offers to check and update configured remote hosts to the updated local CLI version @spec @mvp
- satelle self update does not show the configured-remote update offer when --no-input is set, stdin is not a TTY, JSON output mode is active, or --dry-run is active @spec @mvp
- satelle self update noninteractive success output includes the follow-up host update command for configured remotes when remote Host Daemon versions may need alignment @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports --update-remotes as an explicit request to run the configured-remote Host Daemon update flow after the local update succeeds @spec @mvp
- satelle self update interactive configured-remote update offer preselects only the current command target host when one is resolved, otherwise the configured default host when exactly one resolves unambiguously @spec @mvp
- satelle self update interactive configured-remote update offer lists other configured remote hosts as unselected choices that the user may opt into before the remote update plan is built @spec @mvp
- satelle self update --update-remotes without an explicit host selector targets the same current or default host selection used by the interactive offer instead of every configured remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports repeatable --host <alias> with --update-remotes for explicitly selected configured remote hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports --all-remotes with --update-remotes as the explicit request to check and update every configured remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle self update reports a typed no-remote-host-selected error when --update-remotes cannot resolve a current or default host and no --host or --all-remotes selector is provided in noninteractive mode @spec @mvp
- satelle self update re-executes the updated local binary before running any accepted or flag-requested configured-remote Host Daemon update flow @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow selects Satelle Host Daemon updates by default and does not select standalone Codex runtime updates unless the user explicitly requests additional host update components @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow uses host update planning, consent, action ledger, partial-failure, and post-update readiness rules instead of bypassing remote mutation controls @spec @mvp
- satelle self update remote-update failure output states that the local CLI update succeeded, identifies each failed remote host, describes what remote state was preserved or changed, and gives the recovery command @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow builds per-host update plans for all selected remote hosts before applying any remote mutation @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote --dry-run treats per-host update plans as preview diagnostics and does not persist or emit a reusable apply plan @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote JSON dry-run output includes reusable_plan false so automation does not treat the preview as an apply artifact @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow re-probes selected remote hosts and rebuilds per-host update plans for every non-dry-run invocation even when a dry-run command was run earlier @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow may apply the in-memory plan shown immediately before final confirmation within the same CLI process without repeating the full dry-run command @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow revalidates selected host identity, current Host Daemon version, selected component set, target artifact digest, and restart impact before mutating each remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow attempts every selected remote host that has a valid update plan after the combined plan passes consent instead of failing fast on the first host failure @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow uses bounded concurrency for per-host planning and per-host update application instead of serial-only execution or unbounded parallelism @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow defaults to a maximum of 4 concurrent remote hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle self update supports --concurrency <n> with --update-remotes to set the maximum number of remote hosts processed at once @spec @mvp
- satelle self update --concurrency 1 with --update-remotes forces serial remote host processing @spec @mvp
- satelle self update MVP accepts --concurrency values from 1 through 16 and reports a typed concurrency-limit-exceeded usage error for larger values @implemented @mvp
- satelle self update reports a typed concurrency-without-remote-update usage error when --concurrency is provided without --update-remotes @implemented @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow keeps human progress grouped by remote host and does not interleave raw per-host logs in normal output @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow records each selected remote host outcome as succeeded, unchanged, skipped, or failed @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow treats unreachable hosts and host planning failures as per-host failed or skipped outcomes instead of blocking planning for every other selected host @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow exits 0 only when every selected remote host succeeds, is unchanged, or is explicitly skipped by user selection before mutation @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow exits with the remote execution failure class and typed remote-update-partial-failure error when at least one selected remote host fails after local update succeeds @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow does not roll back successful remote host updates when another selected remote host fails @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow human summary groups remote hosts by succeeded, unchanged, skipped, and failed, and prints recovery commands for failed hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote --quiet prints no human output when every selected remote host is unchanged or skipped and no error occurs @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote --quiet prints one concise human changed summary when at least one selected remote host changes and no error occurs @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote --quiet still prints failure summaries and recovery commands when any selected remote host fails @spec @mvp
- satelle self update configured-remote update flow JSON summary includes status, changed, local_update, remote_hosts, aggregate_counts, failed_hosts, and recovery_commands fields @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP official package repository submissions are prioritized by user demand, repository acceptance fit, maintainer ownership, release automation compatibility, update latency, uninstall semantics, and support burden rather than pursued as a bulk checklist @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP first official package repository candidates are WinGet and Scoop Main because their manifest models can reference versioned Windows release artifacts and checksums that Satelle already publishes @spec @later
- satelle keeps the first-party Scoop bucket as the canonical Scoop installation path until a Scoop Main manifest is accepted and release automation proves Scoop Main updates do not lag normal Satelle releases @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP Homebrew core submission is attempted only when Satelle can provide a source-build formula that passes Homebrew-supported macOS CI, disables Satelle self-update for Homebrew installs, and satisfies Homebrew stability and notability expectations @spec @later
- satelle keeps the first-party Homebrew tap as the canonical Homebrew installation path until Homebrew core accepts Satelle and core updates prove reliable across releases @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP Chocolatey submission is considered after WinGet and Scoop Main only when Chocolatey moderation, validator requirements, checksum rules, install scripts, uninstall behavior, and maintainer response expectations are documented @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP AUR, Debian package repository, RPM package repository, Nixpkgs, and MacPorts submissions are considered only after clear user demand or committed ecosystem maintainer ownership justifies their source-build policy, review, maintenance, and release-lag obligations @spec @later
- satelle MVP does not publish .deb, .rpm, AUR, WinGet, Chocolatey, Nixpkgs, MacPorts, Homebrew core, or Scoop Main packages as release blockers @spec @mvp
- satelle npm-registry distribution uses version-matched platform-specific native binary packages for supported local CLI platforms instead of bundling every OS and architecture binary into the top-level package @spec @mvp
- satelle top-level npm-registry package declares version-matched platform-specific native binary packages as optionalDependencies instead of downloading the local native binary during ordinary package installation @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle npm-registry distribution does not require postinstall network access to fetch the local native binary during ordinary package installation @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle platform-specific native npm packages declare npm ecosystem platform constraints such as os, cpu, and libc where supported by the target package manager @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP supports Linux, macOS, and Windows as Controller Platforms independently from the narrower Computer Use Host Platform matrix @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP supports macOS and Windows as native Computer Use Host Platforms because official Codex Computer Use is available there @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support Linux as a native Computer Use Host Platform until an official provider Computer Use runtime supports Linux @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes linux-arm64-gnu mapped to Rust target aarch64-unknown-linux-gnu @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes linux-x64-gnu mapped to Rust target x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes darwin-arm64 mapped to Rust target aarch64-apple-darwin @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes darwin-x64 mapped to Rust target x86_64-apple-darwin @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes win32-arm64-msvc mapped to Rust target aarch64-pc-windows-msvc @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP Controller target matrix includes win32-x64-msvc mapped to Rust target x86_64-pc-windows-msvc @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle release validation treats Controller artifacts and native Computer Use Host acceptance as separate matrices @spec @mvp
- the single satelle executable contains Controller commands on every Controller target and Host Daemon mode on every native Computer Use Host target @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not publish native packages for 32-bit platforms, mobile OS targets, BSD targets, AIX, illumos, PowerPC, RISC-V, s390x, loong64, or ARMv7 targets @spec @mvp
- satelle unsupported npm local platform reports a typed unsupported-local-platform error instead of trying a best-effort binary download @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle release validation fails when any MVP Controller target matrix entry is missing from the top-level npm optionalDependencies, release artifacts, or integrity metadata @spec @mvp
- satelle JavaScript launcher resolves the installed matching platform-specific native package at runtime and executes its native satelle binary @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle JavaScript launcher reports a typed native-binary-package-missing error when the matching platform-specific native package is absent @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle native-binary-package-missing error output tells users to reinstall without omitting optional dependencies or use the direct native binary installation path @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle JavaScript launcher does not silently download a replacement native binary when the matching platform-specific native package is missing @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle JavaScript launcher does not run package-manager repair, reinstall, or mutation commands unless the user invokes an explicit repair command added for that purpose @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle native-binary-package-missing error output includes package-manager-specific reinstall guidance when the launcher can detect npm, pnpm, bun, or another package-manager owner from the installation layout @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle release versions align exactly across scoped and unscoped top-level npm packages, every platform-specific native npm package, the local CLI binary, and every version-matched remote Host binary artifact @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle public release publishing is performed only by a GitHub Actions release workflow in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle local developer machines may build, test, package, and dry-run releases but do not publish npm packages, upload final public GitHub release assets, or mint public release provenance @spec @mvp
- satelle public npm package publishing uses npm trusted publishing with OIDC instead of long-lived npm automation tokens when npm supports trusted publishing for the package @spec @mvp
- satelle public npm package publishing runs on cloud-hosted CI runners capable of generating npm provenance attestations @spec @mvp
- satelle public release workflow generates GitHub artifact attestations for each native binary artifact before publishing the release @spec @mvp
- satelle public release workflow produces checksum and integrity metadata for every native binary artifact before publishing npm packages or GitHub release assets @spec @mvp
- satelle public GitHub release workflow creates or updates a draft release, attaches all release assets and metadata, verifies the release artifact set, and publishes the release only after validation passes @spec @mvp
- satelle first MVP public release does not require npm staged publishing because npm staged publishing requires each package to already exist on the npm registry before it can be staged @spec @mvp
- satelle may publish initial npm package versions through trusted publishing after release validation passes when staged publishing is unavailable for brand-new package identities @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP npm staged publishing is adopted only after all Satelle npm package identities exist, trusted publishing is stable, release automation supports npm CLI 11.15.0 or newer and Node.js 22.14.0 or newer, and maintainers accept the required 2FA approval step @spec @later
- satelle npm staged publishing, when adopted, is used as a human approval gate before npm package versions become installable rather than as a canary rollout, gradual rollout, or replacement for prepublish validation @spec @later
- satelle npm staged publishing, when adopted, uses trusted publisher stage-only permission for CI so CI can run npm stage publish but cannot directly run npm publish for configured packages @spec @later
- satelle npm staged publishing approval checks every staged top-level and platform-specific native npm package for version, artifact digest, package metadata, provenance, and release alignment before any staged package is approved @spec @later
- satelle npm staged publishing approval rejects the entire npm release when any staged Satelle npm package is missing, mismatched, or fails release validation instead of approving a partial platform package set @spec @later
- satelle local CLI can fetch a version-matched target host binary artifact for a different remote OS or architecture from the same release artifact set when SSH bootstrap or host update needs it @spec @mvp
- satelle verifies integrity metadata for fetched native binary artifacts before uploading or executing them on a remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle remote hosts do not need Node.js, npm, pnpm, or bun installed to run the Satelle Host Daemon because the uploaded host component is a self-contained native binary @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not include an explicit package-manager native binary repair command because normal npm-registry installation must succeed through package-manager optionalDependencies rather than a secondary downloader @spec @mvp
- satelle later adds the launcher-only satelle native repair command so a missing native optionalDependency can be repaired without reinstalling the entire Satelle package graph manually @spec @later
- satelle native repair is implemented in the JavaScript launcher because the Rust native binary may be missing when repair is needed @spec @later
- satelle native repair invokes the detected package manager to reinstall the matching platform-specific native package instead of using direct HTTP downloads @spec @later
- satelle native repair verifies the repaired native package version, executable path, platform metadata, and release integrity metadata before reporting success @spec @later
- satelle native repair refuses installs owned by package managers it cannot identify safely and reports the direct native binary install path instead @spec @later

## execution
- satelle optimizes equally for one-shot prompt execution and ongoing session/thread control @spec @mvp
- satelle one-shot prompt execution creates a remote Codex thread, sets the thread goal to the prompt objective when the supported app-server protocol exposes goal methods, starts the first turn, and returns both the outcome and the reusable session identifier @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer accept exactly one prompt source: a positional prompt, the positional value - for standard input, or --prompt-file <path> @spec @contract @mvp
- conflicting prompt sources report a typed prompt-source-conflict usage error @spec @mvp
- satelle run treats a single dash prompt argument as an instruction to read prompt text from standard input @implemented @mvp
- satelle help warns that prompt command arguments may be retained by shell history or visible in local process metadata @spec @mvp
- satelle recommends standard input or prompt files for sensitive prompt input @spec @mvp
- satelle never sends raw prompt text through SSH command arguments, remote process arguments, environment variables, logs, or bootstrap diagnostics @spec @mvp
- satelle run supports image attachments in MVP when the remote Codex app-server protocol supports image or localImage user input @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer use repeatable --image <local-path> as the exact local image attachment option @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle image attachment paths provided to CLI commands are interpreted as local CLI machine paths by default @spec @mvp
- satelle uploads local image attachments to the remote Host Daemon before passing them to Codex as supported image input @spec @mvp
- the authenticated capabilities response advertises maximum attachment count, per-attachment bytes, aggregate attachment bytes, and supported media types @spec @mvp
- attachment upload verifies declared size, actual size, media type, and content digest before Turn start @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon attachment staging uses generated filenames instead of Client-provided path components @spec @mvp
- attachment staging files are private to the daemon OS user @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects path traversal, device files, directories, and unsupported symlinks as attachment inputs @spec @mvp
- attachment staging is deleted after terminal Turn state, rejected Turn admission, cancellation, timeout, or bounded crash-recovery cleanup @spec @mvp
- attachment cleanup failure creates a redacted cleanup diagnostic without exposing attachment content @spec @mvp
- satelle deletes uploaded image attachments from the remote host after the turn by default @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not retain uploaded image attachments after the turn for logs, status, diagnostics, setup ledgers, diagnostic bundles, or recording artifacts @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support remote-host path image attachments because attachment paths are interpreted as local CLI machine paths by default @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP remote-host path image attachments use an explicit --remote-image <path> option rather than overloading ordinary image attachment paths or SSH-style host:path syntax @spec @later
- satelle later --remote-image resolves paths on the selected remote Host and never on the local CLI machine @spec @later
- satelle later --remote-image rejects use when no remote Host resolves unambiguously before path validation @spec @later
- satelle later --remote-image validates remote file existence, readability by the Host Daemon OS user, supported image media type, and size limits before starting the Codex Turn @spec @later
- satelle later --remote-image does not copy the remote image back to the local CLI machine during normal execution @spec @later
- satelle later --remote-image follows the same no-retention default as uploaded local image attachments for logs, status, diagnostics, setup ledgers, diagnostic bundles, and recording artifacts @spec @later
- satelle MVP does not support arbitrary file attachments until file transfer, storage, and remote path semantics are specified @spec @mvp
- satelle run waits by default until the selected remote Turn reaches a terminal status such as completed, blocked, failed, or stopped @spec @mvp
- prompt Turns use a 30 minute default and maximum execution timeout, configurable through timeouts.turn_execution as a human duration string with explicit units and a finite hard maximum of 24 hours @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer accept --timeout <duration> as the exact per-Turn execution-timeout override; the override may shorten but never lengthen the resolved user-level or Host-owned limit and rejects bare integers or values above 24 hours @spec @contract @mvp
- project-level configuration may request a shorter finite Turn timeout but cannot disable or lengthen the user-level or Host-owned Turn timeout limit @spec @mvp
- when a Turn exceeds its effective execution timeout, Satelle requests upstream cancellation and reports a typed turn-timeout failure @spec @mvp
- Satelle commits failed with turn-timeout and releases the Control Lease only after upstream cancellation or another terminal upstream state is confirmed; otherwise the Turn becomes recovery_pending and retains the lease @spec @mvp
- satelle run supports a detach option that returns after starting the turn and prints the reusable session identifier @implemented @mvp
- satelle run streams concise human lifecycle and progress events by default when running attached in an interactive terminal @implemented @mvp
- satelle run does not require a separate watch option for the ordinary attached interactive run path @implemented @mvp
- satelle run suppresses live human event streaming by default when stdout is not a TTY, when JSON final-output mode is active, when quiet mode is active, or when detach mode is active @implemented @mvp
- satelle run writes human lifecycle and progress events to stderr while reserving stdout for the final outcome, session identifier, or machine-readable output contract @implemented @mvp
- satelle run supports an explicit event output option with auto, human, json, and none modes so users and scripts can override automatic event streaming behavior @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer use --events <auto|human|json|none> as the exact event-output flag @implemented @mvp
- satelle --events defaults to auto @implemented @mvp
- satelle does not provide a short alias for --events in MVP because event output mode is a clarity-sensitive output contract @implemented @mvp
- satelle --events auto applies the command's automatic event streaming rules, including TTY detection, JSON final-output suppression, quiet suppression, and detach suppression @implemented @mvp
- satelle --events human forces human event output to stderr for attached run and steer commands even when stdout is not a TTY or JSON final-output mode is active @implemented @mvp
- satelle --events json makes stdout a newline-delimited JSON event stream for attached run and steer commands, with the terminal event carrying the final outcome or typed error details @implemented @mvp
- satelle --events none suppresses event streaming while preserving the command's final output contract @implemented @mvp
- an explicit satelle --events value overrides quiet-mode automatic event suppression except when detach mode is active @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed events-with-detach usage error when --events human or --events json is used with detach mode @implemented @mvp
- satelle JSON event streaming writes one Satelle Event JSON object per line @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event JSON objects contain exactly schema_version, type, source, timestamp, seq, session_id, turn_id, host, state_subject, message, and data @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event state_subject is null for events without committed lifecycle state, a session subject containing kind and session_state_revision, or a turn subject containing kind, session_state_revision, and turn_state_revision @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event timestamps are UTC RFC 3339 strings @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event seq values are monotonically increasing within a single attached event stream @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event seq values are stream-local ordering numbers instead of durable event identifiers @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event source values are stable snake_case enum strings that identify the event producer, such as cli or host_daemon @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event type values are stable snake_case enum strings @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event message values are human-readable convenience text and are not the stable automation contract @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event data values contain event-type-specific structured details for automation @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event v1 records use schema_version satelle.events.v1 @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Event types are limited to preflight, readiness, provider_smoke, turn_started, turn_progress, action_required, turn_completed, turn_blocked, turn_failed, and turn_stopped @implemented @mvp
- satelle Satelle Event terminal types are turn_completed, turn_blocked, turn_failed, and turn_stopped @implemented @mvp
- satelle does not remove fields, change field meanings, or rename enum tokens within one Satelle Event schema_version @spec @mvp
- satelle may add optional Satelle Event fields or event types within one schema_version only when older consumers can ignore them safely @spec @mvp
- satelle breaking Satelle Event wire changes require a new schema_version @spec @mvp
- satelle run JSON final-output mode without JSON event streaming emits one final JSON object instead of newline-delimited event objects @implemented @mvp
- satelle run JSON event streaming emits newline-delimited JSON event objects and includes a terminal event containing the final outcome or typed error details @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer --events json emit exactly one terminal event as the final stdout record and do not emit a separate final-result JSON object after that event @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle detach mode returns immediately with the session identifier and does not attach to the live event stream @implemented @mvp
- satelle JSON output reports effective timeout values as numeric millisecond fields with names ending in _timeout_ms instead of requiring automation to parse human duration strings @implemented @mvp
- satelle run prints a concise non-blocking preflight summary by default before starting execution on a ready host @spec @mvp
- satelle run supports --quiet to suppress the preflight summary for automation @implemented @mvp
- satelle run supports a verbose option that expands preflight output into detailed host, readiness, transport, and provider diagnostics @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer automatically run the native Computer Use readiness smoke test during preflight when no valid matching native readiness cache entry exists, including first use after setup @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer do not require the user to run satelle doctor --scope computer-use --refresh before first prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer do not start the prompt turn until native Computer Use readiness passes through a valid cache entry or a live harmless readiness smoke test @spec @mvp
- satelle native Computer Use readiness checks distinguish pointer click support from click-and-drag support instead of treating a successful click as full pointer readiness @spec @mvp
- satelle readiness and diagnostics treat file-management workflows as a distinct Computer Use capability area rather than assuming general desktop readiness covers file selection, file movement, uploads, downloads, and save dialogs @spec @mvp
- satelle quiet output may suppress native readiness smoke-test progress text but does not skip native readiness smoke tests required for prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer JSON event streaming emits readiness events that distinguish native readiness cache hits, live native readiness smoke tests, passes, failures, and manual-action-required blockers before turn_started @spec @mvp
- satelle native readiness smoke-test failures block prompt execution and include a typed error plus a recommended diagnostic or repair command @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer automatically run the required provider Computer Use smoke test during preflight when experimental provider Computer Use is active and no valid matching provider smoke-test cache entry exists @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer do not start a prompt Turn until a required live provider Computer Use smoke test passes or a valid matching provider smoke-test cache entry exists @spec @mvp
- satelle Provider Probe Surface includes a harmless click-and-drag task before caching provider Computer Use readiness for providers that claim pointer control support @spec @mvp
- satelle quiet output may suppress provider smoke-test progress text but does not skip provider smoke tests required for prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer support --refresh-provider-smoke-test to ignore a matching provider smoke-test cache entry and rerun the provider Computer Use smoke test before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle --refresh-provider-smoke-test does not opt into experimental provider Computer Use by itself; non-OpenAI provider use still requires --experimental-provider-computer-use or user-level configuration opt-in @implemented @mvp
- satelle --refresh-provider-smoke-test has no short alias in MVP because it is a diagnostic validation control rather than a frequent-path flag @implemented @mvp
- satelle help text describes --refresh-provider-smoke-test as a cache refresh, not as a provider capability bypass or experimental provider opt-in @implemented @mvp
- satelle session control reuses the same stored Codex thread identifier for follow-up steering, status inspection, and stopping flows @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer supports image attachments using the same constraints as run @spec @mvp
- satelle steer waits by default until the newly started follow-up turn reaches a terminal status such as completed, blocked, failed, or stopped @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer supports a detach option that returns after starting the follow-up turn and prints the reusable session identifier @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer streams concise human lifecycle and progress events by default when running attached in an interactive terminal @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer suppresses live human event streaming by default when stdout is not a TTY, when JSON final-output mode is active, when quiet mode is active, or when detach mode is active @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer writes human lifecycle and progress events to stderr while reserving stdout for the final outcome, session identifier, or machine-readable output contract @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer supports the same explicit event output modes as run: auto, human, json, and none @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer JSON final-output mode without JSON event streaming emits one final JSON object instead of newline-delimited event objects @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer JSON event streaming emits newline-delimited JSON event objects and includes a terminal event containing the final outcome or typed error details @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer use --experimental-provider-computer-use as the per-command opt-in flag for attempting native Computer Use with a non-OpenAI provider @implemented @mvp
- satelle does not provide a short alias for --experimental-provider-computer-use in MVP because the flag is rare and risk-bearing @implemented @mvp
- satelle help text for --experimental-provider-computer-use states that the mode is experimental, non-OpenAI provider behavior may not work correctly, and a live provider Computer Use smoke test is still required @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer can add a new turn to the same Satelle session and underlying Codex thread after the previous turn or goal completed @implemented @mvp
- satelle steer updates session lifecycle metadata to reflect the new active turn while preserving previous turn history @implemented @mvp
- satelle stop stops the active Turn in a Session by default without stopping the Host Daemon lifecycle @spec @mvp
- satelle stop preserves the Session and records the active Turn as stopped instead of deleting the Session @spec @mvp
- satelle allows later steer commands to continue from a stopped session when the stored Codex thread identifier remains available @implemented @mvp

## setup-and-maintenance
- satelle host lifecycle commands manage Host Daemon start, stop, restart, and service actions separately from session stop @spec @mvp
- satelle setup treats a missing Satelle Host Daemon as a planned remote install action using the invoking local CLI release's matching verified host artifact for the detected remote platform @spec @mvp
- satelle setup treats an older or protocol-incompatible Satelle Host Daemon as a planned remote update action to the invoking local CLI release's matching verified host artifact @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not require a host binary URL or host binary path for ordinary onboarding @spec @mvp
- satelle setup probes the remote operating system, architecture, and supported libc or runtime family before selecting a Satelle Host Daemon artifact @spec @mvp
- satelle setup presents Host Daemon install or update plans with current version, target version, target platform, artifact digest, install path, and restart impact before mutating the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle setup applies Host Daemon install or update actions through the same final confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, --dry-run, action ledger, and partial-failure rules used by other setup mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle setup defaults setup_mode to on_demand when no CLI flag or user-level host setting selects a mode @spec @mvp
- satelle installs or configures a persistent user-level Host Daemon service only when --persistent or user-level setup_mode = persistent selects persistent mode @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not silently install a persistent Host Daemon service; the service install or configuration action is shown in the setup plan and follows the normal confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, and --dry-run rules @spec @mvp
- satelle setup prefers a user-level or login-session service over a privileged system service for native Computer Use hosts because visible desktop control usually belongs to the signed-in user session @spec @mvp
- satelle setup uses a privileged system service only when the requested host mode requires it and the setup plan states the privilege, service account, and desktop-session implications before mutation @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP binds each concrete host alias to one Satelle Desktop Binding instead of selecting a desktop user per run @spec @mvp
- before first trust, a user-level Host Binding may set expected_host_id = null so setup can discover but not silently pre-trust the reachable Host Identity @spec @mvp
- satelle setup defaults the Satelle Desktop Binding to the authenticated bootstrap OS account when that account has a compatible active desktop session @spec @mvp
- satelle setup supports setup-time desktop binding selection through an interactive prompt or user-level host configuration when multiple candidate desktop users are visible @spec @mvp
- satelle setup with --no-input reports a typed desktop-binding-required diagnostic when multiple candidate desktop users are visible and no desktop_user binding is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed desktop-session-unavailable diagnostic when the bound desktop_user does not have a compatible active desktop session for native Computer Use @spec @mvp
- satelle setup automatically selects the bound desktop_user's active Satelle Desktop Session only when exactly one compatible session is visible @spec @mvp
- satelle setup prompts for a Satelle Desktop Session Preference when multiple compatible sessions are visible and stdin is interactive @spec @mvp
- satelle setup with --no-input reports a typed desktop-session-ambiguous diagnostic when multiple compatible sessions are visible and no desktop_session_preference is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer report a typed desktop-session-ambiguous diagnostic instead of picking a session when multiple compatible sessions match the bound desktop_user and no configured preference resolves to exactly one session @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer report a typed desktop-session-preference-unmatched diagnostic when the configured desktop_session_preference does not resolve to one active compatible session @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not default to the physical console session when multiple compatible sessions are visible because that can control the wrong desktop @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP portable desktop_session_preference values are only and console @implemented @mvp
- satelle treats desktop_session_preference = only as selecting a Satelle Desktop Session only when exactly one compatible session is visible @spec @mvp
- satelle treats desktop_session_preference = console as selecting the OS-reported physical console session only when that session belongs to the bound desktop_user and is compatible with native Computer Use @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed desktop-session-console-unavailable diagnostic when desktop_session_preference = console has no matching compatible console session @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP supports Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector configuration as an advanced escape hatch separate from portable desktop_session_preference values @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects host configuration that sets both desktop_session_preference and a Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector for the same concrete host alias @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed desktop-session-selector-conflict diagnostic when both portable and native session selectors are configured for one concrete host alias @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed desktop-session-native-selector-wrong-platform diagnostic when a Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector platform does not match the detected remote operating system @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed desktop-session-native-selector-unmatched diagnostic when a Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector does not resolve to exactly one active compatible session @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon refuses native Computer Use sessions for desktop sessions that do not match its configured Satelle Desktop Binding @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP supports multiple users on one physical machine only through separate per-user Host Daemon installations, Host Identities, Host Aliases, and Desktop Bindings running under their respective OS accounts @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not provide a Satelle Multi-User Broker for one host alias to route across multiple Satelle Desktop Bindings @spec @mvp
- a later Satelle Multi-User Broker fronts one Host Identity and routes an authorized Host Alias and API Principal to one of multiple explicitly authorized Desktop Bindings @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Multi-User Broker requires per-user authorization, separate Desktop Binding identity, session isolation, provider-auth isolation, path-set isolation, log attribution, audit records, and explicit user or session selection before prompt execution @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Multi-User Broker does not allow a daemon running as one OS user to control another OS user's desktop session unless the target operating system and native Computer Use runtime expose a supported secure handoff for that user @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Multi-User Broker treats each bound OS user's Codex authentication, native Computer Use app approvals, OS privacy permissions, provider credentials, and desktop session preferences as separate readiness state @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Multi-User Broker rejects ambiguous runtime user selection with a typed desktop-binding-ambiguous error instead of falling back to the console session or last-used user @spec @later
- satelle project-level configuration cannot select or authorize a different remote desktop OS user for Satelle Multi-User Broker execution @spec @later
- satelle setup supports --on-demand to select on_demand setup mode and report non-persistent service intent in setup output @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup supports --persistent to explicitly request persistent service mode when configuration would otherwise select on_demand @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup supports host configuration key setup_mode with values persistent and on_demand, where CLI flags take precedence over configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --on-demand still uploads or verifies the Host Daemon artifact needed for SSH bootstrap but does not register a persistent service @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed persistent-service-unsupported error without falling back when --persistent explicitly selects an unsupported service mode @spec @mvp
- when an inherited user-level persistent default is unsupported, satelle setup presents an explicitly reported on-demand fallback plan, while explicit --persistent continues to fail without fallback @spec @mvp
- satelle setup JSON output includes setup_mode, service_persistent, service_scope, and fallback_reason fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup can persist Satelle Host Daemon path overrides into remote service configuration when the setup plan installs or configures a persistent Host Daemon service @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not persist path overrides when it only starts an on-demand SSH bootstrap Host Daemon process @spec @mvp
- satelle setup path override flags are --daemon-home <absolute-path>, --daemon-config-file <absolute-path>, --daemon-state-dir <absolute-path>, --daemon-cache-dir <absolute-path>, and --daemon-log-dir <absolute-path> @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup maps --daemon-home to SATELLE_HOME in the planned Satelle-owned service configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle setup maps --daemon-config-file, --daemon-state-dir, --daemon-cache-dir, and --daemon-log-dir to SATELLE_CONFIG_FILE, SATELLE_STATE_DIR, SATELLE_CACHE_DIR, and SATELLE_LOG_DIR in the planned Satelle-owned service configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle setup accepts persistent daemon path override values from user-level host configuration and setup flags, with setup flags taking precedence @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup does not inherit local SATELLE_HOME, SATELLE_CONFIG_FILE, SATELLE_STATE_DIR, SATELLE_CACHE_DIR, or SATELLE_LOG_DIR into daemon service configuration automatically @spec @mvp
- satelle setup validates daemon path override values as absolute paths before presenting a setup plan @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed daemon-path-override-not-absolute usage or configuration error when a daemon path override is relative or tilde-prefixed @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup stores daemon path overrides in a Satelle-owned per-service configuration surface instead of the global operating-system environment @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not configure persistent Linux Host Daemon services in MVP because Linux is not a supported native Computer Use remote host platform @spec @mvp
- satelle setup uses launchd plist EnvironmentVariables for persistent daemon path overrides on macOS hosts that use launchd @spec @mvp
- satelle setup uses Satelle-owned Windows service configuration for persistent daemon path overrides on Windows hosts instead of modifying global machine environment variables @spec @mvp
- satelle setup plan output shows the current resolved Satelle Path Set and the planned resolved Satelle Path Set when persisting or changing daemon path overrides @spec @mvp
- satelle setup creates or verifies configured remote daemon path override directories before restarting a persistent Host Daemon service @spec @mvp
- satelle setup records persisted daemon path override changes in the remote setup action ledger @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --dry-run reports planned daemon path override persistence without writing service configuration, creating directories, or restarting a Host Daemon @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup defaults to the all setup component set when no component filter is provided @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup default component set configures or diagnoses every readiness-critical prerequisite for prompt execution, including transport, Host Daemon setup, Codex runtime setup, detectable native Computer Use prerequisites, desktop binding, and required provider authentication @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports prerequisite configuration separately from live native Computer Use action-path readiness verification @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not require --component provider-auth for ordinary first-run onboarding @spec @mvp
- satelle setup supports repeatable --component <transport|host|codex|computer-use|desktop|provider-auth|all> filters for targeted setup runs, reruns, repairs, and AI-agent workflows @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed component-selection-conflict usage error when --component all is combined with any other setup component value @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup has no short alias for --component in MVP because component selection changes onboarding scope @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup --component provider-auth limits planning and mutation to provider authentication descriptor configuration, interactive provider secret provisioning when explicitly confirmed, provider authentication validation, and provider smoke tests unless another selected setup component is a prerequisite that the plan explicitly reports @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input --json is the stable AI-agent onboarding contract and emits setup components, planned_actions, applied_actions, required_input, recovery_commands, and readiness_summary fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input --json reports required_input entries for any setup component that needs human-only material, including provider secret entry, instead of blocking on prompts or accepting secrets through automation-only channels @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input --json without --yes may build a setup plan but never applies planned mutations, writes action-ledger entries for unapplied actions, installs services, changes configuration, or provisions secrets; it updates readiness caches only through an explicit --verify after required prerequisites are already satisfied @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input --json without --yes reports a typed setup-consent-required error when the setup plan contains any remote mutation that would be applied only after consent @spec @mvp
- when setup --verify discovers consent-required setup mutations but receives no applicable consent, it reports setup-consent-required before running live probes or updating readiness and provider smoke-test caches @spec @mvp
- satelle setup setup-consent-required output states that no remote changes were applied and includes the planned_actions plus a safe recovery command that reruns the same setup selection with --no-input --json --yes @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input --json --yes may apply remote mutations only after rebuilding or revalidating the setup plan in the same invocation and then following the normal setup action ledger, partial-failure, and postcheck rules @spec @mvp
- satelle setup accepts noninteractive mutation consent for ordinary setup mutations only from the current command's --yes flag or from an applicable user-level Satelle Trusted Profile, excluding raw provider secret entry, provider-secret provisioning, and provider-secret overwrite confirmation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup never treats project-level configuration as noninteractive mutation consent, even when project-level configuration selects the host, profile, provider, model, or component set @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports setup-consent-required instead of applying remote mutations when the only available consent-like setting comes from project-level configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle setup treats provider authentication onboarding as part of getting a configured host ready for Satelle prompt execution when the selected model and provider require provider credentials @spec @mvp
- satelle setup distinguishes configuring a provider authentication Secret Source descriptor from provisioning the raw provider secret material that descriptor references @spec @mvp
- satelle setup can configure host-resolved provider authentication Secret Source descriptors for a concrete host alias in user-level configuration or remote-host owned configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup uses cliclack prompts to help the user choose a supported provider authentication Secret Source kind for the target host when provider authentication is missing or incomplete @spec @mvp
- satelle setup can validate that a configured provider authentication Secret Source is resolvable by the target Host Daemon without returning the resolved secret value to the local CLI @spec @mvp
- satelle setup supports --verify as an explicit request to run the live native Computer Use readiness smoke test and any required provider smoke test after prerequisite planning or mutation completes @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --verify runs a provider smoke test after provider authentication onboarding when the selected provider and model require provider validation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --verify is valid with --no-input and is explicit authorization for the same harmless desktop and provider probes used by doctor refresh, but it is not consent for setup mutations @spec @mvp
- a non-dry-run setup --verify invocation that reaches a live probe writes that probe's successful or failed native readiness and provider smoke-test cache entries under the normal cache keys and time-to-live rules @spec @mvp
- setup --verify exits with the host-readiness failure class and typed setup-verification-failed error when prerequisite actions complete but a requested live probe fails @spec @mvp
- setup-verification-failed output preserves changed and applied action results, the failed verification result, cache updates, and a safe recovery command instead of describing completed setup mutations as rolled back @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --dry-run --verify reports the live checks that would run without opening a probe surface or operating the desktop @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports provider authentication onboarding results in its human plan and JSON output as descriptor_configured, secret_provisioned, validation_status, provider_smoke_test_status, and recovery_commands instead of exposing secret values @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --dry-run reports planned provider authentication descriptor changes and secret provisioning requirements without reading, writing, validating, or transmitting provider secret material @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input never prompts for provider authentication choices or raw provider secrets and instead requires provider authentication Secret Source descriptors to be supplied by configuration or explicit flags @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input reports a typed provider-secret-source-required error when provider authentication is required and no usable Secret Source descriptor is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --no-input reports a typed provider-secret-provisioning-required error when the configured Secret Source descriptor exists but the target Host Daemon reports that the referenced provider secret material is missing @spec @mvp
- satelle setup JSON errors for provider-secret-source-required and provider-secret-provisioning-required include safe suggested_commands that an AI agent can present or execute without containing raw secret material @spec @mvp
- satelle setup help text documents an agent-safe noninteractive flow: configure host-resolved Secret Source descriptors, run setup with --no-input --json, and treat missing raw secret material as a user action requirement rather than an agent-handled value @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP does not migrate existing SQLite stores, operator log files, or recording artifacts when daemon path overrides change @spec @mvp
- satelle setup preserves old storage directories when daemon path overrides change and warns that previous sessions may be invisible until the old path is restored or a future migration command is used @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP exposes satelle host storage migrate as the explicit command for moving Host Daemon-owned SQLite stores, operator log files, and recording artifacts between Satelle Path Sets @spec @later
- satelle setup, repair, and host update do not migrate Host Daemon-owned storage as an implicit side effect after satelle host storage migrate exists @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate targets one concrete host alias and refuses to run when host selection is ambiguous @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate supports --dry-run to report the source Satelle Path Set, destination Satelle Path Set, migration items, estimated bytes when available, service restart impact, backup location, validation checks, and rollback plan without mutating the remote host @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate follows the same interactive confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, Trusted Profile, setup action ledger, and partial-failure rules as setup, repair, and host update for remote mutations @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate refuses prompt execution and steer attachment for the selected host while a migration is in progress @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate validates that source paths exist and are readable, destination parent paths are absolute and writable, source and destination path sets do not overlap, and destination storage paths do not already contain unrelated Satelle data before applying mutations @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate reports typed storage-migration-source-invalid, storage-migration-destination-invalid, storage-migration-paths-overlap, and storage-migration-destination-not-empty errors for failed preflight validation @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate migrates the Host Daemon SQLite store through a SQLite-consistent backup or closed-database copy path instead of copying a live database file with ordinary filesystem copy semantics @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate does not rely on cross-filesystem rename as an atomic commit mechanism because supported source and destination Satelle Path Sets may be on different mount points or volumes @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate stages destination data, validates staged data, then switches persistent Host Daemon service path configuration only after staging validation succeeds @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate preserves the source Satelle Path Set by default after a successful migration and reports a separate cleanup command instead of deleting source storage automatically @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate attempts rollback to the previous Satelle Path Set and service configuration when migration fails after remote mutation begins @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate reports a typed storage-migration-rollback-failed error with preserved source paths, destination staging paths, service state, and manual recovery commands when automatic rollback cannot restore the previous ready state @spec @later
- satelle host storage migrate runs post-migration checks for Host Daemon API reachability, expected Satelle Path Set, SQLite integrity, operator log writability, recording artifact path writability when recordings are enabled, and native Computer Use readiness-cache invalidation @spec @later
- satelle setup reports a typed host-binary-newer-than-cli error instead of downgrading automatically when the reachable Satelle Host Daemon version is newer than the invoking local CLI version @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed host-artifact-unavailable error when the invoking local CLI release artifact set lacks a verified Host Daemon binary for the detected remote platform @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle host update as the explicit maintenance command for ordinary updates to Satelle host binaries and supported standalone Codex runtime components @implemented @mvp
- satelle host update is distinct from setup and repair: setup onboards prerequisites, repair restores broken readiness or compatibility, and host update performs user-requested maintenance updates @spec @mvp
- satelle host update does not start prompt execution or modify Satelle sessions as a side effect @spec @mvp
- satelle host update checks all supported update targets by default when no component filter is provided @mvp @spec
- satelle host update supports a repeatable --component <host|codex|all> filter for selecting update targets @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --component host selects only Satelle-owned host binaries and Host Daemon service assets, not Codex runtime components @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --component host targets the Satelle host binary version that exactly matches the invoking local CLI release for the remote host platform @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support selecting an arbitrary Satelle host binary version, update channel, or latest remote release independently from the invoking local CLI version @spec @mvp
- satelle host update does not intentionally leave the Satelle Host Daemon on a Satelle version different from the invoking local CLI version after a successful host component update @spec @mvp
- satelle host update may use SSH bootstrap or a narrow versioned update handshake only to replace an older or missing Satelle host binary with the invoking CLI's matching host artifact @spec @mvp
- satelle host update reports a typed host-binary-newer-than-cli error instead of downgrading automatically when the reachable Satelle Host Daemon version is newer than the invoking local CLI version @spec @mvp
- satelle host update reports a typed host-update-requires-cli-upgrade error when the selected host update requires a Satelle host binary version newer than the invoking local CLI can provide @spec @mvp
- satelle later host update --component host --version <version> is the sole explicit Host binary version selector @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP CLI-host compatibility matrix defines supported version skew, protocol version negotiation, feature gating, upgrade order, downgrade policy, artifact verification policy, and recovery path @spec @later
- satelle exact Satelle CLI and Host Daemon version matching remains the default host update target when --version is absent @spec @later
- satelle later Host binary version selection never downgrades a reachable Host Daemon unless the user explicitly selects a lower version and the compatibility matrix permits that downgrade @spec @later
- satelle later Host binary version selection verifies the selected version's release artifact integrity metadata for the detected remote platform before upload or execution @spec @later
- Satelle does not add Host update channels in current committed scope @spec @later
- satelle host update --component codex selects the standalone Codex runtime and Codex-owned native Computer Use components required by that runtime for native Computer Use readiness @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --component codex does not select the Satelle host binary or Host Daemon service assets @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --component codex does not update unrelated browser extensions, operating-system packages, third-party tools, user browser profiles, provider credentials, or non-Codex automation software @mvp @spec
- satelle host update shows Codex runtime updates and Codex-owned native Computer Use component updates as separate planned actions even when they are selected by the same --component codex filter @mvp @spec
- satelle host update reports a typed ambiguous-codex-component-ownership error when a candidate update target cannot be confidently classified as Codex-owned @spec @mvp
- satelle host update treats --component all as an explicit request to check every supported update target on the selected host @mvp @spec
- satelle host update reports a typed component-selection-conflict usage error when --component all is combined with any other --component value @implemented @mvp
- satelle host update has no short alias for --component in MVP because component selection is a clarity-sensitive maintenance contract @implemented @mvp
- satelle host update never mutates the remote host during its update check; mutation starts only after the planned update actions pass the command's consent rules @spec @mvp
- satelle host update presents current versions, target versions, update targets, restart impact, and planned remote mutations before mutating the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --yes skips only the final interactive confirmation prompt and does not skip update checks, plan presentation, safety blockers, action ledger recording, or post-update readiness checks @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --yes prints planned remote mutations in human output before applying when --quiet is not active and JSON output mode is not active @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --no-input --yes follows the same human plan-output rule as --yes when human output mode is active @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --quiet --yes suppresses non-error human plan and progress output but does not suppress final failure summaries or required recovery guidance @spec @mvp
- satelle host update JSON output includes planned_actions before mutation and applied_actions after mutation instead of printing human plan text @mvp @spec
- satelle host update does not expose a --plain output mode in MVP because --json is the stable automation contract for update plans, results, and typed errors @implemented @mvp
- satelle host update help text directs scripts and other agents to --json instead of human output or --quiet output for stable automation data @spec @mvp
- satelle later adds satelle host update --plain as a stable line-oriented scripting output mode narrower than --json and not a replacement for the complete JSON automation contract @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain is mutually exclusive with --json and every explicit --format value and reports a typed output-mode-conflict usage error for either combination @spec @contract @later
- satelle host update --plain writes only machine-readable plain records to stdout and writes diagnostics, prompts, progress, and errors to stderr @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain disables colors, spinners, progress bars, tables, hyperlinks, and human summary prose even when stdout is a TTY @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain emits UTF-8 LF-terminated records with TAB-separated fields and no header row @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain v1 records use field order schema, host, component, phase, status, current_version, target_version, changed, restart_required, error_code, and recovery_command @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain uses schema value satelle.host.update.plain.v1 for every v1 record @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain escapes TAB, LF, CR, and backslash inside field values as \t, \n, \r, and \\ @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain represents unavailable optional field values as - and represents booleans as true or false @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain component, phase, status, and error_code fields use lowercase snake_case tokens instead of localized or human-formatted text @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain emits one record for each planned, skipped, applied, failed, and postcheck-failed update target before emitting the final process exit status @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain represents partial failure with status failed or postcheck_failed on the affected target records while preserving succeeded, unchanged, or skipped records for other targets @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain failure records include the typed Satelle error code in error_code and a shell-safe recovery command in recovery_command when a recovery command exists @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain exits with the same exit code class as the equivalent non-plain host update invocation @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain compatibility policy freezes v1 field order and escaping rules until a new schema token such as satelle.host.update.plain.v2 is introduced @spec @later
- satelle host update --plain may add new schema versions after v1 but does not change v1 field order, field meanings, escaping, or enum token meanings in a minor release @spec @later
- satelle host update reports unsupported selected update components as typed unsupported-update-component errors instead of silently ignoring an explicit component selection @implemented @mvp
- satelle host update reports unsupported default update targets as skipped diagnostics when checking all supported update targets by default @spec @mvp
- satelle host update exits 0 with status up_to_date and does not ask for mutation confirmation when all selected supported components are already current @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --quiet exits 0 with no human output when all selected supported components are already current @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --quiet prints one concise human changed summary when one or more selected components changed and no error occurs @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --quiet still prints failure summaries and required recovery guidance when the command fails or leaves the host in a partial or postcheck-failed state @spec @mvp
- satelle host update supports --dry-run to preview update actions without mutating the selected host @mvp @spec
- satelle host update --dry-run treats the update plan as preview diagnostics and does not persist or emit a reusable apply plan @spec @mvp
- satelle host update JSON dry-run output includes reusable_plan false so automation does not treat the preview as an apply artifact @mvp @spec
- satelle host update non-dry-run invocations always re-probe the selected host and rebuild the update plan from live host state and local release metadata before asking for mutation consent @spec @mvp
- satelle host update may apply the in-memory plan shown immediately before final confirmation within the same CLI process without repeating the full dry-run command @spec @mvp
- satelle host update revalidates selected host identity, current component versions, selected component set, target artifact digests, and restart impact before mutating the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle host update follows the same final interactive confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, manual-action-required, action ledger, and partial-failure rules as setup and repair for remote mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle host update records maintenance update actions in the Host Daemon SQLite action-ledger storage model with an action kind that distinguishes host_update from setup and repair @spec @mvp
- satelle host update may restart the Host Daemon or Codex app-server only when the planned update requires it and reports that restart impact before applying the update @spec @mvp
- satelle host update runs relevant post-update readiness checks after applying any update that can affect Host Daemon health, Codex app-server lifecycle, Codex control-plane compatibility, or native Computer Use readiness @spec @mvp
- satelle host update verifies Host Daemon API reachability, expected Satelle host version, and required storage migration state after updating Satelle host binaries or Host Daemon service assets @spec @mvp
- satelle host update verifies Codex app-server startup and required control-plane protocol compatibility after updating the standalone Codex runtime @spec @mvp
- satelle host update runs the native Computer Use readiness smoke test after updating the standalone Codex runtime or Codex-owned native Computer Use components @spec @mvp
- satelle host update invalidates native Computer Use readiness cache entries affected by applied host, Codex runtime, or native Computer Use component updates before running post-update readiness checks @spec @mvp
- satelle host update invalidates provider Computer Use smoke-test cache entries whose cache keys are affected by applied Codex runtime, native Computer Use runtime, or native Computer Use component updates @spec @mvp
- satelle host update does not rerun provider Computer Use smoke tests by default after ordinary maintenance updates because provider smoke tests are provider/model-specific and are already enforced before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle host update stores successful post-update readiness check results in the Host Daemon readiness cache when the cache key still matches the updated host state @spec @mvp
- satelle host update treats post-update readiness check failure after successful update mutations as a typed host-update-postcheck-failed error instead of reporting the update as fully successful @spec @mvp
- satelle host update uses the remote execution failure exit-code class for host-update-postcheck-failed because the command changed remote state but did not leave the host in the requested ready state @spec @mvp
- satelle host update does not automatically roll back completed update actions when a post-update readiness check fails @spec @mvp
- satelle host update human postcheck-failure output states the updates that were applied, the failed readiness check, preserved remote state, invalidated caches, and the recommended repair or doctor command @spec @mvp
- satelle host update JSON postcheck-failure output includes status postcheck_failed, changed true, applied_actions, postcheck_results, invalidated_caches, preserved_state, and recovery_command fields @spec @mvp
- satelle host update --dry-run reports the post-update readiness checks that would run after applying the plan without running those post-update checks @spec @mvp

## doctor-and-diagnostics
- satelle treats Codex thread goals as lifecycle metadata for objective, status, budget, and usage tracking, not as a replacement for thread and turn control @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes one top-level doctor command for selected-host diagnostics @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor supports repeatable --scope <transport|codex|computer-use|provider|config|all> for selected-host diagnostics @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor defaults to scope all when no --scope is provided, so doctor --refresh without an explicit scope refreshes both computer-use and provider probes @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor reports a typed scope-selection-conflict usage error when --scope all is combined with another scope @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor reports Satelle Doctor Findings with stable fixability values repairable, manual_action_required, blocked, and informational @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor exit status is based on whether selected diagnostics prove the checked target is ready, not on whether findings are repairable @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor exits 0 when all selected diagnostics pass or produce only informational findings that do not block Satelle prompt execution @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor exits with the host readiness failure class when selected diagnostics complete and report any readiness-blocking finding, including repairable findings @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor reports a typed doctor-readiness-blockers-found error when diagnostics complete but readiness-blocking findings remain @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor exits with the usage error, configuration error, unreachable host, or internal error class when the diagnostic command cannot complete because of that broader failure class @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --json emits one final JSON object after selected diagnostics and any accepted fix flow finish @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --json does not emit newline-delimited JSON progress events or multiple top-level JSON values @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --json final object includes schema_version, status, target, scopes, started_at, finished_at, duration_ms, summary, probe_results, findings, recovery_commands, changed, and cache_updates fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --json final object includes fix_flow fields only when an interactive fix flow was accepted or an explicit repair path was invoked through doctor @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --events is an explicit diagnostic event streaming output mode for agents and shell pipelines @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events is mutually exclusive with --json and every explicit --format value and reports a typed output-mode-conflict usage error for either combination @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events preserves the satelle doctor --json contract by never making --json emit newline-delimited events, progress objects, or multiple top-level JSON values @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events emits newline-delimited JSON records to stdout, with each LF-terminated line containing one valid UTF-8 JSON object @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events writes pre-stream validation and transport errors to stderr instead of mixing them into the stdout event stream @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events disables human TTY progress, spinners, tables, colors, hyperlinks, prompts, and interactive fix offers even when stdin and stdout are TTYs @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events records include schema_version, event_id, event_type, target, scope, probe_id, timestamp, status, and data fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events uses schema_version satelle.doctor.events.v1 for every v1 event record @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events event_type values include doctor_started, probe_started, probe_finished, finding_reported, cache_updated, doctor_finished, and doctor_failed @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events emits probe_finished events in actual probe completion order while preserving deterministic probe order inside the final doctor_finished data object @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events emits finding_reported events only after the corresponding Doctor Finding is stable enough to appear in the final doctor result @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events emits exactly one terminal event with event_type doctor_finished or doctor_failed before the process exits unless the process is interrupted or crashes @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events doctor_finished data contains the same final doctor result object shape that satelle doctor --json would emit for the same completed diagnostic run @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events doctor_failed data contains the typed Satelle error code, exit code class, partial probe results when available, and recovery commands when available @implemented @mvp
- doctor --events failures detected before doctor_started use the global machine-error contract on stderr and leave stdout empty @spec @contract @mvp
- after doctor_started, doctor --events emits exactly one doctor_failed terminal record on stdout for any handled failure and does not emit a second machine-readable error object on stderr @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle doctor --events exits with the same exit code class as the equivalent non-events doctor invocation @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --events compatibility policy freezes v1 event field names, terminal event semantics, and enum token meanings until a new schema_version such as satelle.doctor.events.v2 is introduced @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor schedules Satelle Doctor Probes with an explicit dependency graph instead of relying on textual output order @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor runs independent Satelle Doctor Probes concurrently by default with bounded per-host concurrency @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor default probe concurrency is at most 4 probes per target host @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor never starts a dependent probe before its prerequisite probes complete @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor skips a dependent probe when a prerequisite proves the dependent probe cannot produce useful new evidence @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor continues running independent probes after another probe reports a finding, fails, times out, or is skipped @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor serializes probes that share native Computer Use, visible desktop control, a provider probe surface, readiness-cache writes, or the same remote service-manager resource @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor applies per-probe timeouts and reports timed_out probe results without cancelling unrelated independent probes @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor final human and JSON output orders probe results by scope and stable probe id instead of probe completion order @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor may show transient TTY progress in completion order while preserving deterministic final output order @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --json probe_results entries include probe_id, scope, status, started_at, finished_at, duration_ms, cache_status, dependency_status, and finding_ids fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor supports --serial-probes to run at most one probe at a time for debugging and reproducible diagnostic runs @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor MVP does not expose a general probe concurrency tuning flag because --serial-probes is the only user-facing probe scheduling override @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor diagnoses and reports findings before offering or starting any fix flow @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor does not run setup, repair, install, host update, service, or configuration mutations during the diagnostic phase @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor in an interactive terminal offers to start a fix flow when at least one finding is repairable @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor interactive fix offer defaults to No so pressing Enter after diagnostics does not start a mutation flow @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor fix offer is consent to build the appropriate repair or host update plan, not consent to apply unseen mutations immediately @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor accepted fix flow delegates mutation to setup, repair, or host update ownership boundaries instead of applying ad hoc doctor-specific mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor supports --fix as the explicit noninteractive request to build a delegated setup, repair, or host update fix plan after diagnostics complete @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --fix --dry-run emits the delegated fix plan and never mutates local or remote state @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --fix --no-input requires --yes or applicable Trusted Profile consent before delegated mutations begin @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --fix with prompts disabled and without --yes or applicable Trusted Profile consent emits the delegated plan, performs no mutation, and reports a typed doctor-fix-consent-required error @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --events with --fix reports a typed output-mode-conflict usage error @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor accepted fix flow uses the target command's plan presentation, final confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, --dry-run, action ledger, partial-failure, and postcheck rules @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor does not prompt for fixes when --no-input is set, stdin is not a TTY, JSON output mode is active, --events is active, --quiet is active, or --dry-run is active @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor noninteractive and JSON outputs include recommended recovery commands for repairable findings instead of prompting @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor accepted fix flow reruns affected readiness diagnostics before deciding the final doctor exit status @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor exits 0 after an accepted fix flow only when the post-fix diagnostics no longer report readiness-blocking findings @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor exits with the host readiness failure class when the user declines a fix offer and readiness-blocking findings remain @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor may mutate readiness or provider smoke-test caches only when --refresh is explicitly provided; refresh never performs setup, repair, install, host update, service, or configuration mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor supports --scope computer-use --refresh to rerun the native Computer Use readiness smoke test and update the host readiness cache without starting prompt execution @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor accepts --refresh only when the selected scopes include computer-use, provider, or all and otherwise reports a typed refresh-scope-required usage error @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor --scope all --refresh reruns both native Computer Use readiness and required provider smoke tests before updating their independent caches @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor computer-use refresh accepts an explicit timeout option for diagnostics without changing stored timeout configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor computer-use refresh timeout option is --timeout <duration> and uses the same explicit-unit duration syntax as configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor --scope provider --refresh reruns provider Computer Use smoke tests and updates the host-side provider smoke-test cache without starting prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor provider refresh accepts an explicit timeout option for diagnostics without changing stored timeout configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor provider refresh timeout option is --timeout <duration> and uses the same explicit-unit duration syntax as configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor accepts --timeout only with --refresh and a selected computer-use, provider, or all scope and otherwise reports a typed refresh-timeout-without-refresh usage error @spec @mvp
- when doctor refresh selects both computer-use and provider, one --timeout value applies independently to each live probe rather than to their combined wall-clock duration @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor implementation uses modular probes internally instead of encoding subsystem checks directly in the command handler @implemented @mvp
- satelle diagnostic bundle export is deferred until after MVP logs, status, and doctor behavior is implemented @spec @later
- satelle diagnostic bundle export is a post-MVP support workflow instead of a prerequisite for MVP logs, status, or doctor @spec @later
- satelle diagnostic bundle export uses the dedicated satelle support bundle command instead of satelle logs --export @spec @later
- satelle support bundle --host <alias> --output <path> is the exact diagnostic bundle command @spec @later
- satelle support bundle JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.support.bundle.v1 and includes status, source Host, output path, artifact byte size, included and not_collected categories, redaction policy version, and created_at @spec @contract @later
- satelle diagnostic bundles redact secrets and exclude screenshots, raw prompts, full transcripts, and desktop recordings by default @spec @later
- the default diagnostic bundle includes redacted configuration shape, version information, readiness results, structured errors, up to 2000 recent redacted Log Entries, setup-ledger summaries, and transport diagnostics and marks unavailable categories as not_collected in its manifest @spec @later
- satelle MVP normal diagnostics are limited to redacted metadata, normalized Satelle Log Entries, Doctor Findings, setup action ledger summaries, typed errors, exit statuses, readiness probe results, and recovery commands @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP normal diagnostics do not capture, persist, display, or export raw protocol payloads, raw setup or repair subprocess streams, raw prompts, full transcripts, screenshots, desktop snapshots, or desktop recordings by default @spec @mvp
- satelle post-MVP Raw Diagnostic Exports are enabled only by explicit command-specific flags and are never enabled by --verbose, --debug, --json, --events, --plain, YOLO mode, Trusted Profiles, user-level configuration, or project-level configuration @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports require an explicit --output <path> destination and never choose an upload destination, support endpoint, cloud bucket, or public URL automatically @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports write artifacts to local filesystem paths controlled by the invoking OS user by default and do not upload artifacts to Satelle maintainers, third-party support systems, or remote storage @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports for remote hosts transfer selected raw material over the authenticated Satelle transport only for the requested export and do not persist transferred raw material in the local CLI cache @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports are excluded from normal diagnostic bundles, normal logs, status output, doctor output, setup action ledger summaries, Satelle Events, and Satelle Operator Log Files unless a command-specific raw export fact explicitly includes them @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports apply the default Satelle redaction policy before writing the artifact, including known provider secrets, bearer tokens, authorization headers, credential-store references marked secret, raw provider credentials, and configured schema-marked sensitive fields @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports include a manifest that lists included data categories, redaction policy version, redaction categories applied, known unredacted risk categories, source host, selected session or command scope, created_at, and artifact format version @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export warnings state that the export may contain secrets, prompts, transcripts, provider payloads, visible desktop content, file paths, user names, host names, internal addresses, and other sensitive diagnostic data even after redaction @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export warnings state the exact output path, that Satelle will not upload the artifact automatically, that normal Satelle diagnostics are unchanged, and that the user should inspect the artifact before sharing it @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports require interactive confirmation after showing the warning when stdin is a TTY, and report a typed raw-diagnostics-consent-required error when noninteractive consent is missing @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports in noninteractive mode require the command-specific raw export flag, --output <path>, --no-input, and --yes before capture or export begins @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export consent is scoped to one command invocation and cannot be stored in project configuration, user configuration, Trusted Profiles, or environment variables @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export staging files are stored outside normal Satelle logs and caches and are deleted after successful export or after a bounded failure-retention window @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export failed staging data is retained for at most 24 hours by default, and the failure output reports the staging path, cleanup command, and whether raw material may remain there @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Exports record audit metadata in the Host Daemon SQLite store without storing raw artifact contents, raw payloads, raw subprocess streams, screenshots, transcripts, prompts, provider credentials, or provider response bodies in the audit record @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export audit metadata includes actor identity when known, host alias, command, selected scope, data categories, artifact byte size when available, redaction policy version, created_at, and success or failure status @spec @later
- satelle Raw Diagnostic Export failures use typed errors such as raw-diagnostics-output-required, raw-diagnostics-consent-required, raw-diagnostics-redaction-failed, raw-diagnostics-staging-failed, and raw-diagnostics-export-failed with recovery guidance that states what data was preserved or deleted @spec @later
- satelle commands that report state use human-readable output by default and support JSON output for automation @spec @mvp
- satelle JSON output is treated as a stable command contract for scripts and other agents @spec @mvp
- satelle human output may be optimized for readability as long as equivalent structured data is available through JSON output for state-reporting commands @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not add stable --plain output modes to state-reporting commands unless a command-specific fact defines the plain format and compatibility contract @spec @mvp

# implementation-quality
- satelle is implemented as a small Rust workspace with separate crates for the binary entrypoints, shared domain model, Codex adapter, and transport boundary @spec @mvp
- satelle avoids crate explosion by adding new crates only when they enforce a real ownership boundary or materially simplify testing and reuse @spec @mvp
- satelle defines shared Satelle domain types as hand-written Rust structs first and may generate schemas or API documentation from those types after the contract stabilizes @spec @mvp
- satelle implementation keeps CLI presentation, host configuration, transport, host daemon API, Codex app-server protocol, capability probing, and session lifecycle as separate ownership boundaries @spec @mvp
- satelle command handlers delegate to typed orchestration code instead of embedding transport, Codex protocol, or Computer Use readiness logic inline @spec @mvp
- satelle represents transport kinds, host readiness states, and provider Computer Use support with explicit typed models instead of stringly typed or nullable mode flags @spec @mvp
- satelle avoids scattered platform-specific conditionals by routing OS-specific host checks through dedicated platform capability probes @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects silent fallback behavior in favor of explicit unsupported-capability diagnostics and user-selected alternatives @spec @mvp
- satelle decomposes implementation files when a file combines unrelated ownership boundaries; file length alone does not require a split @spec @mvp
- satelle uses separate public API, persistence, and upstream-adapter data types so internal identifiers and sensitive storage fields cannot enter public output by ordinary serialization @spec @mvp
- satelle public response types use enums and discriminated states instead of independent string and boolean fields that can represent contradictory state @spec @mvp
- satelle derives redundant state such as Session activity and readiness summaries from canonical records instead of maintaining independently mutable copies @spec @mvp
- satelle uses structured tracing for internal diagnostics across CLI, transport, Host Daemon, Codex adapter, and capability probes @spec @mvp
- satelle keeps diagnostic logs separate from user-facing command output @spec @mvp
- satelle supports configurable log verbosity through flags, environment variables, or config without changing JSON command output contracts @spec @mvp

# api

## http-and-versioning
- satelle Host Daemon exposes an HTTP JSON API for request and response operations such as readiness checks, session creation, status reads, logs, and stop requests @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle Host Daemon exposes a WebSocket JSON event stream for live Session and Turn lifecycle updates @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle Host Daemon v1 HTTP routes use the /v1 path prefix @spec @mvp @implemented
- every Host Daemon JSON request declares one supported Satelle API schema version @spec @mvp @implemented
- every Host Daemon JSON response and error declares one Satelle API schema version @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle rejects unsupported API schema versions before executing an operation @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle rejects incompatible CLI and Host Daemon protocol versions before executing a mutating request @spec @mvp
- satelle API JSON decoding rejects unknown fields instead of ignoring misspelled security, authority, or execution-policy fields @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle API endpoints reject unsupported content types before reading operation data @spec @mvp @implemented
- every API request receives a correlation request_id returned in the response and included in redacted diagnostic records @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle request_id values are not authorization or idempotency credentials @spec @mvp @implemented
- every authenticated Host Daemon response includes the stable Host Identity in a response header or envelope field @spec @mvp @implemented
- authenticated Host Daemon responses without a JSON envelope return the stable Host Identity in the Satelle-Host-Identity response header @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- Satelle Session, diagnostic, setup, and secret-provisioning responses include Cache-Control: no-store @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon shutdown stops accepting new HTTP connections, drains in-flight HTTP requests for a finite configured grace period that defaults to 5 seconds, and returns a typed shutdown-timeout result after aborting the serving task when the grace period expires @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle Host Daemon does not enable cross-origin browser access by default @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle Host Daemon v1 JSON request bodies use the exact schema_version token satelle.api.v1 @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- authenticated Host Daemon requests use Satelle-Request-Id for caller-supplied UUIDv7 correlation and Satelle-Expected-Host-Identity for Host pinning; neither header grants authority or idempotency @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- authenticated Host Daemon HTTP requests without Satelle-Request-Id receive a generated canonical UUIDv7 except GET /v1/events, whose WebSocket upgrade contract requires a caller-supplied Satelle-Request-Id; malformed or duplicate supplied request-id headers are rejected @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle Host Daemon MVP uses GET /v1/live, GET /v1/capabilities, GET /v1/host/status, GET /v1/host/desktop-sessions, POST /v1/setup, POST /v1/doctor, POST /v1/sessions, POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/turns, GET /v1/sessions/{session_id}, POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/stop, GET /v1/logs, and GET /v1/events as its canonical route set and exposes no run, steer, blocking-run, SSE, or HTTP logs-follow aliases @spec @contract @mvp
- Host Daemon response schemas use the exact tokens satelle.capabilities.v1, satelle.host.status.v1, satelle.host.desktop-sessions.v1, satelle.logs.page.v1, and satelle.ws.control.v1 for their corresponding v1 surfaces @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs accepts only the query fields mode, cursor, limit, session_id, sources, minimum_severity, and since; unknown fields, duplicate singleton fields, empty source tokens, and duplicate source tokens report a typed invalid-request error @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs mode is tail or forward, defaults to tail, and permits cursor only with forward mode @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs limit defaults to 200 and accepts only integers from 1 through 10000 inclusive @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs sources is an optional comma-separated set limited to host_daemon, storage, and codex_adapter, while minimum_severity is info, warn, or error and defaults to info @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs since is an optional RFC 3339 timestamp, session_id is an optional canonical Satelle Session identifier, and every filter is applied by the Host before the page limit @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs tail mode returns the newest matching entries in ascending Log Cursor order, while forward mode returns matching entries strictly after cursor in ascending Log Cursor order and starts at the retained-history origin when cursor is omitted @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs rejects a forward cursor above the Host-captured log high-water cursor as typed invalid-request instead of accepting a position that could skip later logs @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/logs returns schema_version satelle.logs.page.v1 in one flat envelope containing request_id, host_identity, entries, next_cursor, and truncated @spec @contract @mvp
- a satelle.logs.page.v1 next_cursor is the last delivered Log Cursor when a forward page is truncated and otherwise advances to the Host-captured log high-water cursor even when no entry matches the filters @spec @contract @mvp
- a satelle.logs.page.v1 truncated value is true when tail mode omitted older matching entries or forward mode has newer matching entries beyond the returned page @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle.logs.entry.v1 contains exactly schema_version, cursor, timestamp, source, severity, event, subject, message, and redacted; redacted is always true @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle.logs.entry.v1 subject is either a host subject containing only kind host or a turn subject containing kind turn plus session_id, turn_id, session_state_revision, and turn_state_revision @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle.logs.entry.v1 source tokens are host_daemon, storage, and codex_adapter; severity tokens are info, warn, and error; current event tokens are session_started, follow_up_started, turn_state_committed, stop_confirmed, stop_not_confirmed, restart_recovery_pending, and store_opened @spec @contract @mvp
- logs-cursor-expired uses HTTP 410 and schema_version satelle.error.v1; details.earliest_available_cursor contains the first retained entry cursor or null, while details.resume_cursor contains the exclusive cursor boundary that returns that first retained entry without skipping it @spec @contract @mvp
- POST /v1/sessions, POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/turns, and GET /v1/sessions/{session_id} return the exact response schema token satelle.session.v1 and one flat envelope containing request_id, host_identity, and the canonical PublicSession fields @spec @contract @mvp
- POST /v1/sessions and POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/turns return HTTP 202 only after durable asynchronous Turn admission, while GET /v1/sessions/{session_id} returns HTTP 200 @spec @contract @mvp
- POST /v1/sessions/{session_id}/stop returns the exact response schema token satelle.session.stop.v1 and one flat envelope containing request_id, host_identity, stop outcome fields, and canonical Session and Turn state revisions @spec @contract @mvp
- the authenticated capabilities operations list uses the exact route-semantic tokens live, capabilities, host_status, session_create, turn_create, session_read, session_stop, logs_read, and events_read for the currently available v1 routes and never advertises CLI run or steer command names @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- Host Daemon v1 success and error responses use operation-specific flat JSON envelopes with request_id and host_identity where authenticated, and never use a generic data wrapper @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- GET /v1/live returns only schema_version satelle.live.v1 and alive true and reveals no version, capability, identity, readiness, or Session metadata @spec @contract @mvp @implemented

## idempotency-and-capacity
- satelle mutating Host Daemon API requests use the Idempotency-Key HTTP header @spec @mvp
- run, steer, stop, setup, repair, host update, storage migration, token mutation, and destructive maintenance API requests require an idempotency key @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI generates a UUIDv7 idempotency key when the caller does not supply one @spec @mvp
- an Idempotency Record digest covers the full canonical typed operation payload after defaults and normalization, excludes only transport authentication credentials, request_id, tracing metadata, and the idempotency key itself, and includes operation payload secrets through the sensitive HMAC path without storing their raw values @spec @contract @mvp
- prompt-bearing or otherwise sensitive idempotency digests use HMAC-SHA-256 with a Host Daemon-owned key and are never returned through public APIs or logs @spec @mvp
- idempotency HMAC keys inherit the token-verifier sensitive-state boundary, survive Host Daemon restart and migration restore for at least the maximum Idempotency Record retention window, and are never exposed through public APIs, logs, or diagnostics @spec @mvp
- each Idempotency Record stores non-secret digest-schema and HMAC-key versions, and retired HMAC keys remain available until every record using them expires @spec @mvp
- an Idempotency Record durable outcome never contains raw bearer-token material or another one-time secret @spec @contract @mvp
- repeating a request with the same API Principal, operation, idempotency key, and request digest returns the original durable outcome without repeating side effects @spec @mvp
- a matching duplicate received while the original operation is in progress returns the same operation, Session, and Turn handles that exist at that point and never starts a second execution @spec @contract @mvp
- a matching duplicate received after the original operation is terminal returns its durable terminal result @spec @contract @mvp
- a matching duplicate of a completed bearer-token issuance or rotation returns the original durable token metadata plus a typed token-secret-not-replayable result and revoke-and-reissue recovery guidance and never returns the raw token again @spec @contract @mvp
- reusing an idempotency key with a different request digest fails with a typed idempotency-key-conflict error @spec @mvp
- Satelle Idempotency Records are retained for at least 24 hours after their operation becomes terminal @spec @mvp
- a successful mutating API response is emitted only after the corresponding state and Idempotency Record are durably committed @spec @mvp
- the authenticated capabilities response advertises effective JSON body, attachment, WebSocket message, connection, and operation-concurrency limits @spec @mvp
- requests exceeding a body or attachment limit fail before prompt execution with a typed payload-too-large error @spec @mvp
- requests exceeding an operation or connection capacity limit fail with a typed capacity-exceeded error @spec @mvp
- failed authentication attempts are limited to 10 per minute per network source by default @spec @mvp
- failed-authentication rate limiting derives network source from the transport peer address and ignores Forwarded, X-Forwarded-For, and equivalent headers by default @spec @mvp
- Satelle trusts forwarded client addresses only from an explicit Host-owned trusted-proxy allowlist and derives the client source from the nearest untrusted hop @spec @mvp
- authenticated read operations are limited to 600 requests per minute per API Principal by default @spec @mvp
- authenticated control and admin operations are limited to 120 requests per minute per API Principal by default @spec @mvp
- API rate limits are configurable only through Host-owned or user-level configuration and cannot be weakened by project-level configuration @spec @mvp
- rate-limited responses use the typed rate-limited error and include retry_after_ms when retry timing is known @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon does not log raw HTTP request bodies, Authorization headers, prompt text, or attachment bytes @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon run and steer HTTP operations always return after durable asynchronous Turn admission; attach and detach are Controller presentation behaviors and are excluded from the operation payload and idempotency digest @spec @contract @mvp

## mcp
- satelle exposes a local MCP stdio server command for AI clients that speak JSON-RPC over stdin and stdout @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP stdio server handles initialize, tools/list, and tools/call without requiring the AI client to know Satelle CLI argument syntax @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP stdio server exposes read-only tools for config check, config explain, paths, status, logs, doctor, host status, and host sessions @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP stdio server exposes mutating tools for run, steer, stop, setup, repair, host update, and host lifecycle only when explicit MCP mutating-tool enablement is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP mutating tools preserve the same consent, --yes, YOLO, Trusted Profile, host-busy, readiness, and provider smoke-test rules as equivalent CLI commands @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP tool results use Satelle JSON envelopes and typed Satelle errors instead of inventing MCP-only result shapes for the same operations @spec @mvp
- satelle MCP server writes JSON-RPC protocol messages only to stdout and writes diagnostics only to stderr so AI clients can parse the stream safely @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle mcp install as the AI client bootstrapper for configuring Satelle MCP server entries in supported local AI clients @spec @mvp
- satelle mcp install supports --target <client>, --all, --server-name <name>, --satelle-path <path>, and --dry-run options @spec @mvp
- satelle mcp install supports Claude Code, Claude Desktop, Codex, Cursor, VS Code, Windsurf, Gemini, OpenCode, Cline, Roo Code, Droid, and Antigravity as named Satelle AI Client Install Targets @spec @mvp
- satelle mcp install --dry-run reports planned client configuration changes without writing AI client config files or restarting client applications @spec @mvp
- satelle mcp install never stores provider credentials, Host Daemon bearer tokens, raw prompts, session transcripts, screenshots, or desktop recordings in AI client configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle mcp install preserves unrelated existing MCP server entries in each AI client configuration file instead of rewriting the whole file from a Satelle-only template @spec @mvp

## event-streams
- satelle Host Daemon WebSocket event streams are live-only in MVP and begin at connection or subscription time @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not expose a durable event history, event replay cursor, event resume token, or event replay endpoint for Satelle Events @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon WebSocket event stream emits the same Satelle Event JSON envelope used by CLI --events json @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon is the canonical producer for remote Session and Turn lifecycle Satelle Events observed on the controlled Host @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI is the canonical producer for local preflight, configuration, and transport Satelle Events observed before or around Host Daemon communication @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI --events json may merge CLI-produced Satelle Events with Host Daemon-produced Satelle Events in one newline-delimited stream while preserving the shared envelope @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI --events json assigns seq values for the CLI output stream even when relaying Host Daemon-produced Satelle Events @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon WebSocket assigns seq values for each WebSocket event stream and does not expose seq as a durable stored event id @spec @mvp
- satelle automation consumers correlate durable Satelle state with session_id, turn_id, type, timestamp, and structured data rather than seq alone @spec @mvp
- a Host Daemon WebSocket connection authenticates and authorizes its API Principal before accepting subscriptions @spec @mvp
- an MVP WebSocket subscription selects one or more explicit host, session, or turn scopes allowed by its API Principal @spec @contract @mvp
- operation subscriptions are not part of MVP until a public operation identity exists, log subscriptions are not part of MVP because normalized logs use the separate cursor-based log contract, and goal subscriptions are not part of MVP until Goal lifecycle event types exist @spec @contract @mvp
- GET /v1/events authenticates and authorizes read scope before upgrading, requires the ordinary Satelle-Request-Id and Satelle-Expected-Host-Identity headers, and rejects query parameters, cookies, and request bodies @spec @contract @mvp
- a WebSocket client sends a satelle.ws.control.v1 subscribe message containing exactly schema_version, type, request_id, and subscriptions, where type is subscribe and subscriptions contains from 1 through 16 unique typed scopes @spec @contract @mvp
- a host subscription contains only kind host, a session subscription contains kind session plus one canonical session_id, and a turn subscription contains kind turn plus one canonical session_id and turn_id @spec @contract @mvp
- each valid subscribe message atomically replaces the connection's complete subscription set without resetting the stream-local seq, and the server acknowledges it with a satelle.ws.control.v1 subscribed message echoing request_id, Host Identity, and the exact validated scopes before delivering matching events @spec @contract @mvp
- an event matching multiple WebSocket subscription scopes is delivered once, and replacing subscriptions begins from a fresh live receiver so events captured before the replacement are not replayed under the new scopes @spec @contract @mvp
- WebSocket control decoding accepts text frames only, rejects unknown or duplicate fields and duplicate subscriptions, accepts only canonical identifiers and schema tokens, and never accepts bearer credentials in a control message @spec @contract @mvp
- one WebSocket connection has a bounded outbound event queue @spec @mvp
- a slow WebSocket subscriber never blocks Turn execution, SQLite commits, cancellation, or delivery to other subscribers @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon closes a subscriber whose outbound queue overflows with a typed slow-consumer close reason @spec @mvp
- WebSocket overflow diagnostics record only Principal token id, subscription scope, last delivered seq, and dropped event count @spec @mvp
- stream-local seq values may contain gaps after authorization filtering or slow-consumer overflow @spec @mvp
- a terminal Turn event is published only after the terminal state transaction commits @spec @mvp
- clients never treat receipt of a WebSocket event as proof of committed state unless the event references the committed session_state_revision or turn_state_revision for its state_subject @spec @mvp
- loss of a terminal event does not lose terminal state because satelle status remains authoritative @spec @mvp
- clients reconcile status and normalized logs after any WebSocket disconnect or seq discontinuity @spec @mvp
- WebSocket ping, pong, idle timeout, maximum message size, and outbound queue limits are advertised through authenticated capabilities @spec @mvp
- authenticated capabilities advertise the maximum subscriptions per WebSocket and the inbound WebSocket message rate per API Principal @spec @mvp
- exceeding a WebSocket subscription or inbound-message limit closes the connection with a typed capacity or rate-limit reason without affecting active Turns or other subscribers @spec @mvp
- every inbound WebSocket text, binary, ping, or pong frame consumes the API Principal's inbound-message allowance, while a close frame may terminate without consuming allowance @spec @contract @mvp
- WebSocket connection capacity and inbound-message limits both aggregate by the authenticated Principal reference rather than by bearer token id, so rotating or issuing another token cannot multiply one Principal's limits @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle.ws.control.v1 protocol failures send a best-effort flat typed error control message containing an exact reason field and then a close frame whose ASCII reason token remains authoritative when the error message cannot be delivered @spec @contract @mvp
- the typed WebSocket error reason, close-frame reason token, and close code use one closed mapping and never contradict one another @spec @contract @mvp
- authenticated WebSocket clients validate both request_id and Host Identity on every subscribed or error control message and reject a typed error whose following close frame does not carry its mapped reason and code @spec @contract @mvp
- WebSocket close reason tokens are invalid-request, unsupported-schema, authorization-insufficient-scope, capacity-exceeded, rate-limited, authentication-failed, slow-consumer, payload-too-large, internal-error, idle-timeout, and server-shutdown @spec @contract @mvp
- invalid-request, unsupported-schema, authorization-insufficient-scope, capacity-exceeded, rate-limited, authentication-failed, slow-consumer, and idle-timeout use WebSocket close code 1008, payload-too-large uses 1009, internal-error uses 1011, and server-shutdown uses 1001 @spec @contract @mvp
- authenticated capabilities advertise 4 WebSocket connections per Principal, 65536 message bytes, 16 subscriptions per connection, 120 inbound messages per minute per Principal, 256 outbound queued events, a 15000 millisecond ping interval, and a 45000 millisecond idle timeout @spec @contract @mvp
- existing WebSocket connections revalidate token id and credential revision during activity and heartbeat checks so expiration, revocation, or rotation closes them with the generic authentication-failed reason @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon uses Axum on Tokio for its HTTP JSON and WebSocket API implementation @spec @mvp
- satelle API keeps streaming event flow separate from command response flow instead of forcing every operation through one transport shape @spec @mvp
- satelle API does not mirror Codex app-server JSON-RPC as its public contract @spec @mvp
- attached satelle run and steer subscribe to live Host Daemon WebSocket events and reconcile authoritative Session status after stream loss, while detached commands return the same durable admission handles without waiting @spec @contract @mvp

# errors
- satelle reports failures with stable typed error codes plus human-readable messages @spec @mvp
- satelle supports global --error-format human and --error-format json modes for commands that can fail before normal output mode is selected @spec @mvp
- satelle supports SATELLE_ERROR_FORMAT as the environment default for the global error format @spec @mvp
- satelle error-format precedence is an explicit --error-format value, then SATELLE_ERROR_FORMAT, then a successfully parsed machine selector consisting of --json, a non-human --format value, run or steer --events json, or doctor --events, then human @spec @contract @mvp
- parser failures that cannot recognize the command's result-format selector use an explicit --error-format value, then SATELLE_ERROR_FORMAT, then human @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle JSON parser failures use the same typed JSON error envelope as semantic usage failures @spec @mvp
- satelle machine-readable error modes never emit ANSI styling, spinners, progress bars, hyperlinks, or human help prose to stdout @spec @mvp
- satelle parser and semantic usage errors write their error contract to stderr and leave stdout empty unless a command-specific streaming contract states otherwise @spec @mvp
- every satelle.error.v1 envelope includes schema_version, code, category, retryable, message, details, docs_url, and suggested_commands, using null for unavailable details or docs_url and an empty array for unavailable suggestions @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle machine-readable error output is stable enough for AI clients and scripts to branch on code, category, retryable, and suggested_commands without parsing human text @spec @mvp
- satelle JSON errors include a stable code, a human message, optional structured details, and actionable recovery guidance when the recovery path is known @implemented @mvp
- satelle human error messages state the user-visible outcome first, explain the known cause, identify preserved state when relevant, and provide the next recovery step @spec @mvp
- satelle does not use generic failure messages when a specific failed host, transport, Codex, Computer Use, provider, config, or session check is known @spec @mvp
- satelle separates user-facing error messages from diagnostic implementation details and exposes low-level details only when they help the user or agent act @spec @mvp
- satelle typed error codes are the stable automation contract while human copy may improve for clarity without changing the code @spec @mvp
- satelle uses a small fixed set of process exit codes for broad failure classes and keeps specific failure causes in typed JSON error codes @spec @mvp
- satelle exit codes distinguish success, usage error, configuration error, unreachable host, host readiness failure, remote execution failure, and internal error @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 0 for success and clean user-declined no-op outcomes @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 64 for usage errors @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 66 for configuration errors @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 69 for unreachable Host errors @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 75 for Host readiness failures @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 74 for remote execution failures @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 70 for internal errors @spec @mvp
- satelle exits 130 when an attached command is interrupted by Ctrl-C after applying its interruption contract @spec @mvp
- setup-consent-required and doctor-fix-consent-required use the usage-error exit class because required noninteractive consent was absent and no mutation occurred @spec @contract @mvp

# config
- satelle uses TOML for human-edited configuration files @implemented @mvp
- satelle config parsing uses serde-backed typed Rust structs instead of ad hoc string parsing @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects unknown config keys as configuration errors instead of warning and continuing @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects unknown config keys in both user-level and project-level configuration files @implemented @mvp
- satelle unknown-config-key errors include the config file path, TOML path, unknown key name, accepted keys for that object, and a nearest spelling suggestion when one is available @implemented @mvp
- satelle JSON unknown-config-key errors include code, message, file, path, key, accepted_keys, and suggestion fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP does not reserve or silently ignore extension key namespaces such as x_ or x- in configuration files @implemented @mvp
- satelle config validation reports every unknown key it can identify after successful TOML parsing before exiting with a configuration error @implemented @mvp
- satelle configuration files describe non-secret host settings, transport settings, defaults, and policies while delegating secrets to external secret stores @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes a read-only satelle config check command that validates local configuration without contacting any remote host @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check does not support --fix, --apply, --write, --yes, or any other flag that mutates local configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check never creates, edits, formats, deletes, backs up, or migrates user-level or project-level configuration files @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check validates TOML syntax, typed schema decoding, unknown-key rejection, unsupported config composition, interpolation syntax, explicit duration-unit syntax, path environment overrides, user/project merge precedence, selected profile resolution, effective host alias binding, and project-level forbidden keys when those checks can be decided locally @spec @mvp
- satelle config check always performs file-level validation for every loaded user-level and project-level config file before context-specific validation @spec @mvp
- satelle config check without --all applies the effective profile overlay, validates the resulting selected context, and reports the source of each context selection @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle config check --all validates context-specific local semantics for the default context, each configured host alias without a profile override, each configured profile without a host override, and each explicit project host/profile default pair @spec @mvp
- satelle config check --all does not synthesize every possible host/profile cross product unless a host/profile pair is explicitly selectable from defaults or configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle config check human output states whether it checked selected-context mode or all-contexts mode @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check never opens SSH connections, Tailscale connections, Host Daemon connections, Codex app-server control-plane sessions, native Computer Use sessions, provider probe surfaces, or provider smoke tests @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check reports remote-dependent validation such as remote-host owned provider bindings, host reachability, Host Daemon health, Codex availability, native Computer Use readiness, and provider Computer Use compatibility as not_checked instead of pass or fail @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check exits 0 only when every locally decidable configuration check passes @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check exits with the configuration error class when any locally decidable configuration check fails @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check supports --host and --profile as context selectors without changing stored defaults @spec @mvp
- satelle config check human output may include suggested recovery commands and minimal config snippets, but labels them as suggestions that were not applied @spec @mvp
- satelle config check --json emits one final JSON object with schema_version, status, mode, checked_files, checked_contexts, selected_host, selected_profile, checks, errors, not_checked, and recovery_commands fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check --json checked_contexts entries include host, profile, source, status, checks, errors, and not_checked fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle exposes a read-only satelle config explain command separate from satelle config check @implemented @mvp
- satelle config check does not support --explain in MVP because validation status and source-precedence reporting have different output contracts @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain reports the effective merged configuration for a selected context and explains which source won each reported value @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain validates loaded configuration enough to compute the effective merged configuration and exits with the configuration error class when parsing, schema validation, or local merge validation fails @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain never opens SSH connections, Tailscale connections, Host Daemon connections, Codex app-server control-plane sessions, native Computer Use sessions, provider probe surfaces, or provider smoke tests @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain supports --host and applies the --profile overlay to the explained effective configuration without changing stored defaults @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle config explain human output is optimized for debugging precedence and should not duplicate the full validation checklist from satelle config check @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain --json emits one final JSON object with schema_version, status, selected_host, selected_profile, checked_files, sources, effective, values, and not_checked fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain redacts schema-marked sensitive, secret, credential, token, auth-command, and secret-source fields by default in both human and JSON output @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain never reads, resolves, or prints secret material from environment variables, files, keychains, credential helpers, command output, provider auth stores, or remote-host owned configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain prints schema-marked non-secret effective values exactly as parsed and merged unless that value is inside a redacted sensitive object @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain shows redacted fields as <redacted> in human output and as value null with redacted true and redaction_reason in JSON output @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain reports the winning source for redacted fields without revealing the redacted value @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain supports --show-secret-references to reveal non-secret secret-source descriptors such as environment variable names or credential store item names when the schema marks those descriptors revealable @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain --show-secret-references never reveals raw secret values, secret file contents, command output, bearer tokens, or provider credentials @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain does not support a --show-secrets flag in MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP supports both user-level configuration and project-level configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle resolves user-level configuration through OS-native config directories rather than hardcoded Unix-only paths @implemented @mvp
- satelle stores user-level configuration in a satelle config directory with a config.toml file @implemented @mvp
- satelle stores project-level configuration at .satelle/config.toml relative to the project root @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP reads at most one user-level config file and at most one discovered project-level config file for a command @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP rejects config includes, imports, extends, extension namespaces, and glob-loaded config fragments as configuration errors instead of treating them as composition or plugin hooks @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed unsupported-config-composition configuration error when a config file defines include, imports, extends, or fragments keys @implemented @mvp
- satelle resolves user config, cache, and local state roots with the Rust directories crate ProjectDirs API or an equivalent OS-native directory resolver @implemented @mvp
- satelle uses ProjectDirs::from("dev", "Microck", "Satelle") as the canonical application identity for OS-native user directory resolution @implemented @mvp
- satelle default path resolution does not use ProjectDirs::from_path because verbatim paths bypass OS-specific project naming conventions @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level config file resolves to ProjectDirs::config_dir joined with config.toml @implemented @mvp
- satelle cache root resolves to ProjectDirs::cache_dir @implemented @mvp
- satelle local mutable state root resolves to ProjectDirs::state_dir when available and ProjectDirs::data_local_dir joined with state otherwise @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed platform-directories-unavailable error when the current OS user cannot resolve a required ProjectDirs path @implemented @mvp
- satelle default Linux user-level config file is ${XDG_CONFIG_HOME:-$HOME/.config}/satelle/config.toml @implemented @mvp
- satelle default Linux local mutable state root is ${XDG_STATE_HOME:-$HOME/.local/state}/satelle @implemented @mvp
- satelle default Linux cache root is ${XDG_CACHE_HOME:-$HOME/.cache}/satelle @spec @mvp
- satelle default Windows user-level config file is the Roaming AppData Known Folder joined with Microck\Satelle\config\config.toml @spec @mvp
- satelle default Windows local mutable state root is the Local AppData Known Folder joined with Microck\Satelle\data\state @spec @mvp
- satelle default Windows cache root is the Local AppData Known Folder joined with Microck\Satelle\cache @spec @mvp
- satelle default macOS user-level config file is $HOME/Library/Application Support/dev.Microck.Satelle/config.toml @spec @mvp
- satelle default macOS local mutable state root is $HOME/Library/Application Support/dev.Microck.Satelle/state @spec @mvp
- satelle default macOS cache root is $HOME/Library/Caches/dev.Microck.Satelle @spec @mvp
- satelle supports SATELLE_HOME as an optional process environment override for portable installs, CI jobs, and hermetic tests @spec @mvp
- satelle derives config_file from SATELLE_HOME/config/config.toml when SATELLE_HOME is set and SATELLE_CONFIG_FILE is unset @spec @mvp
- satelle derives state_root from SATELLE_HOME/state when SATELLE_HOME is set and SATELLE_STATE_DIR is unset @spec @mvp
- satelle derives cache_root from SATELLE_HOME/cache when SATELLE_HOME is set and SATELLE_CACHE_DIR is unset @spec @mvp
- satelle derives operator_log_root from SATELLE_HOME/logs when SATELLE_HOME is set and SATELLE_LOG_DIR is unset @spec @mvp
- satelle derives recording_root from SATELLE_HOME/state/recordings when SATELLE_HOME is set and no more specific recording storage setting is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle supports SATELLE_CONFIG_FILE, SATELLE_STATE_DIR, SATELLE_CACHE_DIR, and SATELLE_LOG_DIR as explicit process environment path overrides @spec @mvp
- satelle explicit path environment overrides take precedence over paths derived from SATELLE_HOME @spec @mvp
- satelle path environment overrides take precedence over OS-native ProjectDirs defaults and do not change project-level .satelle/config.toml discovery @implemented @mvp
- satelle treats empty path environment override values as unset @implemented @mvp
- satelle requires SATELLE_HOME, SATELLE_CONFIG_FILE, SATELLE_STATE_DIR, SATELLE_CACHE_DIR, and SATELLE_LOG_DIR to resolve to absolute paths when they are set @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed path-override-not-absolute configuration error when a path environment override is relative or tilde-prefixed @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support ambiguous path override names such as SATELLE_CONFIG, SATELLE_STATE, SATELLE_CACHE, or SATELLE_LOG @spec @mvp
- satelle path override environment variables apply only to the Satelle process that receives the environment variable @implemented @mvp
- satelle local CLI path override environment variables do not change daemon storage paths unless host setup or service configuration sets matching daemon path overrides @implemented @mvp
- satelle paths output identifies each resolved path source as os_default, satelle_home, explicit_environment, service_config, project_discovery, or host_reported @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes a read-only satelle paths command that prints the resolved Satelle Path Set for the local CLI user by default @implemented @mvp
- satelle paths supports --host <alias> to request the resolved Satelle Path Set from a configured remote Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle paths supports --json with stable keys for config_file, cache_root, state_root, sqlite_store, operator_log_root, recording_root, project_config_file, and install_receipt @implemented @mvp
- satelle exposes a read-only satelle host sessions command that lists active compatible Satelle Desktop Sessions for a configured host alias @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions first attempts the configured direct Host Daemon connection before using SSH bootstrap @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions may use SSH bootstrap to start an on-demand Host Daemon inspection process when the direct Host Daemon connection is unavailable and the host alias has SSH bootstrap configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions SSH bootstrap mode does not install, register, update, or configure a persistent Host Daemon service @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions SSH bootstrap mode may upload or verify the invoking local CLI release's matching host artifact only when that artifact is needed to run the on-demand inspection process @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions SSH bootstrap mode stops or disconnects from its on-demand inspection process after the session listing unless another active Satelle command has claimed the same process @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions non-quiet human output states whether results came from direct Host Daemon connection or SSH bootstrap @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions --json includes connection_mode, bootstrapped, bootstrap_actions, and host_daemon_version fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions supports --no-bootstrap to require an already reachable Host Daemon connection and fail instead of starting an SSH-bootstrap inspection process @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions reports a typed host-daemon-unreachable diagnostic when --no-bootstrap is set and no configured direct Host Daemon connection is reachable @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions reports a typed ssh-bootstrap-unavailable diagnostic when no direct Host Daemon is reachable and the host alias lacks SSH bootstrap configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle host sessions MVP returns session metadata only and does not include screenshots, thumbnails, window previews, or captured frame data @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions does not request OS screen-recording or screen-capture permissions, launch capture pickers, or create recording artifacts @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions display_summary intentionally avoids window titles, app names, page titles, clipboard contents, and other visible desktop content @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions metadata may include display resolution, display server or session type, seat or display identifier, remote state, console state, lock or active state when available, and native selector labels @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions human output marks the session selected by current host configuration, portable selector matches, and available native selectors @implemented @mvp
- satelle host sessions --json includes session_id, desktop_user, state, session_kind, is_console, is_remote, display_summary, portable_selectors, native_selectors, and selected_by_current_config fields @implemented @mvp
- satelle Native Desktop Session Selector values must be copied from native_selectors reported by satelle host sessions for the same host platform @spec @mvp
- satelle discovers project-level configuration by walking upward from the current working directory to the nearest .satelle/config.toml @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration discovery works outside Git repositories @implemented @mvp
- satelle treats a Git repository root as a helpful boundary for project discovery when present but does not require Git for project configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration discovery stops at the nearest .satelle/config.toml and does not merge parent project configuration files in MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle treats project-level configuration as untrusted repository input @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration is limited to non-secret shared Host Aliases, model and provider intent, output defaults, timeout defaults, and non-authoritative transport preferences @spec @mvp
- every project-declared Host Alias resolves through a user-level Satelle Host Binding before remote communication or mutation begins @spec @mvp
- a user-level Host Binding is selectable by project configuration only when that exact binding sets allow_project_selection = true @spec @mvp
- project Host selection permission is scoped to one exact Host Alias and does not grant mutation consent, YOLO, provider-secret consent, Trusted Profile consent, or sensitive-export consent @spec @mvp
- a Provider Binding in user-level or Host-owned configuration is selectable by project configuration only when that exact Operator-controlled binding sets allow_project_selection = true @spec @mvp
- project Provider selection permission is scoped to one exact provider alias and does not grant provider-secret access, endpoint override authority, experimental-provider opt-in, mutation consent, YOLO, or sensitive-export consent @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define or override a concrete network address, SSH destination, direct API URL, TLS trust material, bearer-token descriptor, Tailscale node identity, Desktop Binding, daemon path, provider endpoint binding, or provider credential binding @spec @mvp
- a project transport preference may select a transport kind only when the user-level Host Binding supplies and authorizes the concrete destination and authentication details @spec @mvp
- satelle configuration merging never allows a project object to replace a user-owned Host Binding as a whole object @spec @mvp
- satelle preflight reports when Host, model, provider, profile, timeout, or transport intent came from project-level configuration @spec @mvp
- project-level output defaults cannot suppress Host identity, desktop target, YOLO, authority, consent, or sensitive-export warnings required by the selected command @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define --yes equivalents, assume-yes behavior, trusted profile declarations, or any setting that grants noninteractive mutation consent for setup, repair, host update, self update remote-update flows, or doctor fix flows @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed project-mutation-consent-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration attempts to grant noninteractive mutation consent @implemented @mvp
- satelle applies configuration precedence as built-in defaults, then user-level configuration, then project-level configuration, then explicit Satelle process environment variables, then CLI flags for non-secret overlapping settings @implemented @mvp
- satelle applies project-level precedence only to fields that the project-level schema is authorized to define @spec @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration may define Satelle Trusted Profiles that grant noninteractive mutation consent only for configured command families and host aliases @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Trusted Profiles require a non-empty explicit host alias allowlist for noninteractive mutation consent @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Trusted Profiles do not support all-hosts consent scopes, wildcard host scopes, glob host scopes, regex host scopes, project-host scopes, or default-host scopes @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Trusted Profile host allowlists match the resolved target host alias selected for the command before remote mutation planning starts @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed trusted-profile-host-allowlist-required configuration error when a Satelle Trusted Profile grants noninteractive mutation consent without at least one explicit host alias @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed unsupported-trusted-profile-host-scope configuration error when a Satelle Trusted Profile uses an all-hosts, wildcard, glob, regex, project-host, or default-host scope @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Trusted Profiles require a non-empty explicit Satelle Mutation Command Family allowlist for noninteractive mutation consent @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Trusted Profiles do not support all-mutating-command consent scopes, wildcard command scopes, glob command scopes, regex command scopes, or future-command scopes @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP Satelle Mutation Command Family values are setup, repair, host_update, self_update_remotes, and doctor_fix @spec @mvp
- satelle later adds config_repair and host_storage_migrate Satelle Mutation Command Family values when those commands become available @spec @later
- satelle Satelle Trusted Profile command-family allowlists match the command family for the selected mutating command before remote mutation planning starts @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed trusted-profile-command-allowlist-required configuration error when a Satelle Trusted Profile grants noninteractive mutation consent without at least one explicit Satelle Mutation Command Family @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed unsupported-trusted-profile-command-scope configuration error when a Satelle Trusted Profile uses an all-mutating-command, wildcard, glob, regex, or future-command scope @spec @mvp
- satelle does not apply Satelle Trusted Profile noninteractive mutation consent when either the resolved target host alias or the command family is outside the trusted profile allowlists @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Trusted Profiles are durable user-level configuration records that remain active until the local OS user edits or removes them @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not automatically expire Satelle Trusted Profiles by age, last use, CLI version, project, calendar date, or host update state @spec @mvp
- satelle later supports optional Satelle Trusted Profile expiration through an explicit user-level field named expires_at with an RFC 3339 UTC timestamp @spec @later
- satelle project-level configuration, environment variables, CLI flags, defaults, and profile selection cannot set or imply Satelle Trusted Profile expiration @spec @later
- satelle Satelle Trusted Profiles without expires_at remain durable user-level configuration records that stay active until the local OS user edits or removes them @spec @later
- satelle adding Trusted Profile expiration does not assign a default expires_at value to existing Satelle Trusted Profiles during config load, setup, repair, config check, config explain, or host update @spec @later
- satelle config check validates Trusted Profile expires_at syntax, timezone, and schema placement locally and reports invalid expiration fields as configuration errors @spec @later
- satelle config check reports a typed trusted-profile-expired diagnostic when a selected or --all checked Satelle Trusted Profile has an expires_at timestamp at or before the command evaluation time @spec @later
- satelle config explain shows each selected Satelle Trusted Profile expiration state as absent, active, or expired and reports the winning source for expires_at without contacting remote hosts @spec @later
- satelle does not apply Satelle Trusted Profile noninteractive mutation consent when the profile is expired at command evaluation time @spec @later
- satelle commands that would otherwise use an expired Satelle Trusted Profile report a typed trusted-profile-expired error and require interactive confirmation or another valid consent source before mutating local or remote state @spec @later
- satelle accepts Satelle Trusted Profile mutation consent only when the trusted profile comes from user-level configuration and is selected by a user-level default or explicit --profile option, not when project-level configuration or SATELLE_PROFILE selects the profile @spec @mvp
- satelle config check treats project-level mutation consent settings as locally decidable configuration errors without contacting remote hosts @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain reports the effective noninteractive mutation consent source for the selected context while distinguishing command flags, user-level trusted profiles, and absent consent @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot enable YOLO mode or be the winning source that makes YOLO mode active @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed project-yolo-enable-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration attempts to enable YOLO mode @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration and user-level profiles may enable YOLO mode only for an explicit Host Alias @spec @mvp
- satelle does not support a process-global or all-host persistent YOLO default @spec @mvp
- satelle resolves YOLO policy per command and per target host instead of treating it as only a process-global switch @implemented @mvp
- satelle Host-specific YOLO policy is the only persistent base YOLO policy within a user-level configuration source @spec @mvp
- satelle selected user-level profile YOLO policy overlays the merged base configuration according to the same precedence model used for other profile settings @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle accepts selected profile YOLO enablement only when that policy comes from user-level configuration, names an explicit Host Alias, and the profile is selected by a user-level default or explicit --profile option; project and SATELLE_PROFILE selection may apply yolo = false but never yolo = true @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle does not activate Trusted Profile consent or YOLO policy solely because SATELLE_PROFILE selected a profile @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle CLI flags can enable or disable YOLO mode for one command and take precedence over user-level YOLO policy @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain output shows the effective YOLO policy, target host, selected_profile field, contributing config files, and winning source @implemented @mvp
- satelle non-quiet preflight output identifies when YOLO mode is active and whether it came from a CLI flag, user-level Host configuration, or an explicitly selected Host-bound user-level profile @spec @mvp
- satelle JSON state output includes whether YOLO mode is active and the configuration source that selected it @implemented @mvp
- satelle supports explicit environment variables for selecting config paths, default host, profile, and logging behavior @spec @mvp
- satelle does not use environment variables as a full nested configuration language for host definitions or policy trees @implemented @mvp
- satelle config files do not expand process environment variables inside TOML values during MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle config files do not expand shell home syntax such as ~ inside TOML values during MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle supports environment influence only through documented Satelle-owned process environment variables and explicit secret-source configuration fields @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed config-interpolation-not-supported configuration error when a schema-owned config field contains recognizable environment interpolation syntax such as $VAR, ${VAR}, or %VAR% @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain output reports explicit Satelle process environment overrides as separate contributing sources instead of presenting them as expanded config-file values @implemented @mvp
- satelle supports SATELLE_HOST as an optional process environment default Host selector that is lower precedence than --host and higher precedence than config-file Host defaults @spec @mvp
- satelle supports SATELLE_PROFILE as an optional process environment profile selector that is lower precedence than --profile and higher precedence than config-file profile defaults @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle supports configuration profiles that select default values and policy overlays on top of the merged base configuration @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle named profiles can define host selection, model and provider intent, timeout policy, output preferences, log verbosity, YOLO policy, and Trusted Profile references subject to each field's existing source restrictions @spec @mvp
- satelle profile overlays are applied after base user and project configuration and before explicit environment variables and CLI flags @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle project-level configuration may request a profile name only as shared intent and cannot define trusted profiles, mutation consent, YOLO enablement, or secret-source locations through that profile @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle profiles do not redefine the entire host configuration tree independently from base user and project configuration @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle timeout configuration lives under a nested timeouts table at host and profile scopes instead of as direct host or profile keys @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle timeout configuration may be set in any configuration source that can define host or profile defaults, subject to normal configuration precedence @spec @mvp @implemented
- satelle MVP timeout configuration keys are timeouts.native_readiness, timeouts.provider_smoke_test, and timeouts.turn_execution @spec @mvp
- satelle timeouts.turn_execution configuration values are finite human duration strings with explicit units @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects bare integer timeouts.turn_execution values with a typed duration-unit-required configuration error @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed unknown-timeout-key configuration error for unrecognized keys under a timeouts table @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support direct native_readiness_timeout or provider_smoke_test_timeout configuration keys outside the nested timeouts table @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration may reference host aliases that users bind to concrete personal host access details in user-level configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define or override a concrete Host Binding @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a missing host binding when the effective configuration context references a project-level host alias that the user has not configured @spec @mvp
- satelle config check --all reports missing host binding for every locally selectable project-level host alias context that lacks a user-level binding @spec @mvp
- satelle user-level host configuration may define desktop_user as the Satelle Desktop Binding account for that concrete host alias @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level host configuration may define desktop_session_preference for that concrete host alias @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level host configuration may define desktop_session_native_selector as a Satelle Native Desktop Session Selector object with platform, kind, and value fields for that concrete host alias @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define desktop_user because the controlled desktop account is personal and machine-local @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define desktop_session_preference because the active desktop session topology is personal and machine-local @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define desktop_session_native_selector because native desktop session identifiers are personal, machine-local, and OS-specific @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level host configuration may define daemon_home, daemon_config_file, daemon_state_dir, daemon_cache_dir, and daemon_log_dir as persistent daemon path override defaults @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define daemon_home, daemon_config_file, daemon_state_dir, daemon_cache_dir, or daemon_log_dir because concrete daemon storage paths are machine-local personal configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed project-daemon-path-override-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration defines a concrete persistent daemon path override @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration containing Host Bindings, Provider Bindings, TLS or bearer-token descriptors, Trusted Profile consent, or YOLO policy must be owned by the invoking OS user @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects such user-level security configuration when it is writable by group or other users on POSIX systems @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects such user-level security configuration when its Windows ACL grants write access to unrelated principals @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain output shows persistent daemon path override values, their resolved source, and whether setup must persist them before the Host Daemon uses them @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration may request model and provider aliases as shared project defaults @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration does not define concrete provider credentials, provider auth commands, bearer tokens, secret environment variables, or provider endpoint bindings @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define Satelle Secret Sources for provider authentication because provider credential locations are personal or host-owned @implemented @mvp
- satelle project-level configuration may request a non-OpenAI provider alias but does not satisfy the experimental provider Computer Use opt-in by itself @implemented @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration may opt into experimental non-OpenAI provider Computer Use globally, per profile, per host, or per provider alias @spec @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration uses experimental_provider_computer_use as the exact key for experimental non-OpenAI provider Computer Use opt-in @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed project-experimental-provider-opt-in-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration sets experimental_provider_computer_use @implemented @mvp
- satelle CLI flags may opt into experimental non-OpenAI provider Computer Use for one command and take precedence over user-level and project-level configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed experimental-provider-opt-in-required error when project configuration requests a non-OpenAI provider for Computer Use and no CLI or user-level experimental opt-in is active @spec @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration or remote-host owned configuration binds project model and provider aliases to concrete Codex model, modelProvider, endpoint, and authentication sources @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP provider authentication configuration supports only typed Satelle Secret Source references for operating-system credential stores, environment variables, files, and remote-host owned provider auth stores @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP provider authentication Secret Sources are Satelle Host-Resolved Secret Sources instead of local-CLI-resolved secrets @implemented @mvp
- satelle local CLI may transmit Satelle Host-Resolved Secret Source descriptors to the target Host Daemon only when the descriptor contains no secret material @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI never reads local environment variables, local files, local operating-system credential stores, local keychains, local credential helpers, or local provider auth stores to obtain provider authentication secret material for a target host @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI never forwards provider bearer tokens, API keys, OAuth tokens, secret file contents, or resolved provider credential material to a target Host Daemon except through the explicit interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow requires stdin to be a TTY, disables terminal echo for secret entry, and is unavailable when --no-input, --json, --quiet, or --dry-run is active @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow shows the target host, selected provider alias, selected Secret Source kind, destination descriptor, persistence location class, and overwrite behavior before asking for the raw secret @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow requires an explicit confirmation immediately before transmitting raw secret material to the target Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow sends raw secret material only over the authenticated setup transport to the target Host Daemon and only for the selected host alias @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Trusted Profiles do not authorize raw provider secret entry, provider-secret provisioning, or provider-secret overwrite confirmation even when the trusted profile matches the selected host alias and setup command family @spec @mvp
- satelle --yes does not authorize raw provider secret entry, provider-secret provisioning, or provider-secret overwrite confirmation because provider-secret provisioning uses a separate interactive TTY confirmation from ordinary setup mutation consent @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow never accepts raw secret material through CLI arguments, config files, process environment variables, JSON input, recovery commands, logs, or action-ledger fields @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup provider-secret provisioning flow never writes raw secret material to local CLI logs, local state, shell history, config explain output, config check output, JSON output, Satelle Events, diagnostic bundles, or setup action ledgers @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon persists raw provider secret material from interactive setup only into the selected host-resolved Secret Source destination and records only redacted metadata in Satelle-owned stores @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports a typed provider-secret-overwrite-required diagnostic when interactive provider-secret provisioning would replace an existing provider secret and no explicit overwrite confirmation has been given @spec @mvp
- satelle setup with valid noninteractive mutation consent still reports provider-secret-provisioning-required or provider-secret-overwrite-required when raw provider secret material must be created or replaced, and does not transmit, persist, or overwrite raw provider secret material in that invocation @spec @mvp
- satelle user-level configuration may define host-resolved provider authentication Secret Source descriptors for a concrete host alias, but those descriptors are interpreted on the target host rather than on the invoking CLI machine @implemented @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon resolves provider authentication Secret Sources only when a provider smoke test or prompt execution needs provider authentication on that target host @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon never persists resolved provider secret material in Satelle Event streams, SQLite stores, readiness caches, provider smoke-test caches, setup action ledgers, operator log files, diagnostic bundles, or config explain output @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed provider-secret-resolution-failed error when the target Host Daemon cannot resolve a configured provider authentication Secret Source during a provider smoke test or prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle doctor provider-auth diagnostics inspect configured provider Secret Source descriptors and host-side resolution status without printing raw provider secret values @spec @mvp
- satelle provider-auth diagnostics distinguish missing descriptor, unsupported descriptor kind, unresolved host-side secret, resolved-but-invalid provider credential, and provider Computer Use smoke-test failure as separate outcomes @spec @mvp
- satelle provider-auth diagnostics are diagnostic checks and do not create, overwrite, reveal, or transmit raw provider secrets to the local CLI @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP requires Satelle File Secret Source values to be absolute paths @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support relative paths or shell home syntax such as ~ in Satelle File Secret Source values @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects relative or tilde-prefixed Satelle File Secret Source values with a typed secret-file-path-not-absolute configuration error @implemented @mvp
- satelle validates Satelle File Secret Source absolute-path syntax according to the operating system that resolves the provider authentication binding @spec @mvp
- satelle config check validates Satelle File Secret Source path syntax but does not read the referenced file contents @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain redacts Satelle File Secret Source values by default and never reads the referenced file contents @implemented @mvp
- a Host Daemon resolves a Satelle File Secret Source only from a regular file owned by its OS user and rejects symlinks, directories, devices, sockets, and files readable or writable by unrelated principals @spec @mvp
- a Satelle File Secret Source is limited to 64 KiB, must be valid UTF-8, and rejects NUL bytes @spec @mvp
- Satelle strips exactly one terminal LF or CRLF from a Satelle File Secret Source value and otherwise preserves its UTF-8 contents exactly @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle MVP provider authentication configuration does not support shell commands, command arrays, inline scripts, shell snippets, process execution, or credential helper commands as Satelle Secret Sources @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects unsupported provider authentication Secret Source kinds with a typed unsupported-secret-source-kind configuration error @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP config loading, validation, merging, config check, config explain, setup, repair, doctor diagnostics, preflight, run, and steer never execute shell commands, command arrays, inline scripts, shell snippets, process execution hooks, or credential helper commands declared by configuration files @spec @mvp
- satelle config check validates provider authentication Secret Source shape and source kind locally but does not read or resolve provider secret material @implemented @mvp
- satelle config explain reports provider authentication Secret Source kind and winning source according to its redaction and --show-secret-references rules instead of resolving provider secret material @implemented @mvp
- satelle reports a typed model-provider-binding-missing error when project configuration requests a model or provider alias that has no user-level or host-owned binding @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain output shows requested model and provider aliases, resolved Codex model and modelProvider values, contributing config files, and the winning source @spec @mvp
- satelle config explain output shows whether experimental non-OpenAI provider Computer Use is active and whether it was selected by CLI flag or user-level configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle preflight and JSON state output include the resolved model, resolved provider, provider source, experimental-provider status, and provider Computer Use smoke-test status @spec @mvp
- satelle later config composition supports only explicit Satelle Config Includes declared by a schema-owned include key and continues rejecting imports, extends, glob-loaded fragments, plugin-discovered fragments, URLs, and extension namespaces unless later facts separately enable them @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Config Include paths resolve relative paths against the directory of the configuration file that declares the include and resolve absolute paths on the machine reading that configuration file @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP Satelle Config Includes must target existing regular TOML files and reject missing targets, directories, unsupported symlinks, globs, URLs, environment interpolation, and shell home syntax with typed configuration errors @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP user-level Satelle Config Includes must resolve inside the resolved user-level Satelle config directory tree @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP project-level Satelle Config Includes must resolve inside the discovered project .satelle directory tree @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP included configuration files inherit the source class of the file that includes them, so project-level includes remain subject to project-level forbidden-key and consent-boundary rules @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition detects include cycles before merging values and reports a typed config-include-cycle configuration error that includes the include chain without printing secret material @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition merges included files before the file that includes them, so the including file has higher precedence than its includes within the same source class @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition applies multiple includes in list order, with later include entries overriding earlier include entries before the including file is applied @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition does not change the existing global precedence order of built-in defaults, user-level configuration, project-level configuration, explicit Satelle process environment variables, and CLI flags @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config check validates every loaded included configuration file for TOML syntax, typed schema decoding, unknown-key rejection, include source-boundary rules, include cycles, and locally decidable merge errors before reporting success @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config explain output reports included configuration files in checked_files and sources, shows each included file's parent file and normalized include path, and attributes every effective value to the exact included or including file that won precedence @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition never reads, resolves, dereferences, prints, or includes raw secret material from Satelle Secret Sources while loading includes, running config check, or running config explain @spec @later
- satelle post-MVP config composition treats included files as ordinary Satelle configuration files, so included project-level files cannot define Satelle Secret Sources, Satelle Trusted Profiles, YOLO enablement, concrete daemon paths, provider credentials, credential helpers, or noninteractive mutation consent @spec @later
- satelle MVP does not include a mutating satelle config repair command @spec @mvp
- satelle later config repair is an explicit user-invoked command and never runs as an implicit side effect of config check, config explain, setup, repair, doctor, preflight, run, or steer @spec @later
- satelle later config repair changes only local CLI-visible Satelle configuration files and does not mutate remote-Host-owned configuration unless a separate remote-Host config repair command is specified @spec @later
- satelle later config repair edits project-level configuration only when the project config file is explicitly selected on the command line @spec @later
- satelle later config repair plans edits only from local config loading, parsing, schema, precedence, and config check diagnostics that have deterministic repairs @spec @later
- satelle later config repair reports a typed config-repair-manual-action-required diagnostic instead of editing configuration when a diagnostic requires a user choice, raw secret material, remote Host probe, provider smoke test, OS permission change, or app approval @spec @later
- satelle later config repair does not install, update, start, stop, restart, or reconfigure remote Host Daemon services, Codex runtime installations, operating-system permissions, app approvals, Desktop Sessions, or provider secret material @spec @later
- satelle later config repair does not write Satelle Setup Action Ledger entries because it does not perform remote setup or repair actions @spec @later
- satelle doctor, after satelle config repair exists, may recommend satelle config repair as a recovery command for local configuration diagnostics but never applies config repair edits itself @spec @later
- satelle later config repair supports --dry-run to show target config files, addressed diagnostics, planned writes, backup paths, and a redacted unified diff without mutating files @spec @later
- satelle later config repair uses the same redaction policy as config explain for human and JSON diff output and never prints raw provider secret material @spec @later
- satelle later config repair treats dry-run previews as diagnostics and does not persist or emit a reusable apply plan @spec @later
- satelle later config repair rebuilds and revalidates the repair plan in every non-dry-run invocation instead of applying a plan persisted by an earlier dry-run @spec @later
- satelle later config repair creates all required byte-for-byte backups before replacing any target configuration file and aborts without writes when any backup cannot be created @spec @later
- satelle later config repair writes backups under the invoking user's Satelle local state directory instead of beside project configuration files by default @spec @later
- satelle later config repair reports each backup path, original file path, original digest, repaired digest, and restore command in human and JSON output @spec @later
- satelle later config repair asks for one final interactive confirmation after showing the redacted diff and backup plan and before writing any configuration file when the plan contains mutations and --yes is absent @spec @later
- satelle later config repair treats a user choosing No at final confirmation as a clean cancelled no-op with changed false @spec @later
- satelle later config repair supports --yes as the explicit flag for accepting planned configuration-file mutations without final interactive confirmation @spec @later
- satelle later config repair does not write configuration files when --no-input is set unless --yes is also set or an applicable user-level Satelle Trusted Profile supplies config_repair consent @spec @later
- satelle later config repair accepts Satelle Trusted Profile consent only for Host-scoped edits when the selected user-level Trusted Profile includes the config_repair Satelle Mutation Command Family and target Host Alias @spec @later
- satelle later config repair never treats project-level configuration as noninteractive mutation consent even when project-level configuration selected the Host, profile, or file needing repair @spec @later
- satelle later executable credential helpers are provider authentication Secret Sources resolved by the target Host Daemon instead of by the local CLI @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helper descriptors may be defined only in user-level configuration or remote-host owned user-level configuration for the OS user that resolves the provider authentication binding @spec @later
- satelle project-level configuration cannot define executable credential helper descriptors, helper executable paths, helper arguments, helper environment variables, helper timeouts, or helper protocol options @implemented @later
- satelle reports a typed project-credential-helper-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration defines executable credential helper behavior @implemented @later
- satelle project-level model or provider aliases do not by themselves authorize executable credential helper execution; the winning provider authentication binding must come from user-level or remote-host owned configuration @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helper descriptors use a structured argv array whose first element is an absolute executable path and whose remaining elements are literal arguments @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helpers are never invoked through a shell and do not perform shell parsing, shell quoting, PATH lookup, glob expansion, pipe handling, redirection, command substitution, environment interpolation, or tilde expansion on helper argv values @spec @later
- satelle rejects executable credential helper descriptors with empty argv, relative executable paths, shell strings, inline scripts, or shell metacharacter-only command forms with a typed credential-helper-argv-invalid configuration error @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helpers use a 10 second timeout by default unless a user-level helper descriptor sets an explicit-unit timeout value @spec @later
- satelle reports a typed credential-helper-timeout error and treats provider secret resolution as failed when an executable credential helper exceeds its effective timeout @spec @later
- satelle writes exactly one UTF-8 JSON request object to executable credential helper stdin, closes stdin, reads exactly one UTF-8 JSON response object from stdout, and treats stderr as diagnostic text outside the protocol @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helper request JSON includes schema_version, provider_alias, resolved_provider, host_alias, and operation fields, and does not include existing provider secret material, bearer tokens, transport tokens, or raw prompt text @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helper response JSON must either return a secret value with status success or a structured non-secret failure with status error or interaction_required @spec @later
- satelle treats nonzero helper exit status, invalid JSON stdout, multiple JSON stdout values, missing required response fields, or status interaction_required as provider secret resolution failure before prompt execution starts @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helpers are not connected to a TTY and Satelle does not answer helper prompts, GUI prompts, pinentry prompts, password prompts, MFA prompts, or confirmation prompts on the helper's behalf @spec @later
- satelle starts executable credential helpers with a documented allowlist environment plus explicit user-level helper environment entries instead of inheriting the full Host Daemon or local CLI process environment @spec @later
- satelle executable credential helper environment inheritance never includes Satelle transport bearer tokens, provider secrets, raw prompt text, setup secret-entry values, or project-level configuration values @spec @later
- satelle logs executable credential helper execution only as redacted metadata such as helper source, helper kind, duration, timeout, exit status, and typed error code, and never logs helper stdout, raw stderr, resolved secret values, or unredacted helper environment values @spec @later
- satelle config check validates executable credential helper descriptor placement, argv shape, timeout syntax, environment key shape, and unsupported project-level usage without executing the helper @spec @later
- satelle config explain reports executable credential helper kind, winning source, redacted executable identity, timeout, and redacted environment key names without executing the helper or revealing argv values marked sensitive @spec @later
- satelle later user-level tilde expansion accepts tilde-prefixed File Secret Source paths only in user-level provider authentication descriptors and never in project-level configuration @spec @later
- satelle treats tilde-prefixed Satelle File Secret Source syntax as configuration input shorthand only and never as the canonical Satelle File Secret Source value @spec @later
- satelle Satelle File Secret Source tilde expansion resolves ~ against the home directory of the OS account running the target Host Daemon process that resolves the provider authentication binding, not against the invoking local CLI user, project directory, SSH bootstrap user, or configured desktop_user unless that account is also the resolving Host Daemon account @spec @later
- satelle Satelle File Secret Source tilde expansion supports only bare ~ and a leading ~/ path prefix on Linux and macOS resolver platforms @spec @later
- satelle Satelle File Secret Source tilde expansion supports only bare ~, a leading ~/ path prefix, and a leading ~\ path prefix on Windows resolver platforms @spec @later
- satelle Satelle File Secret Source tilde expansion rejects ~user, ~domain\user, mid-string tilde, repeated leading tildes, environment-variable syntax, and shell command substitution as configuration errors instead of invoking a shell @spec @later
- satelle expands an accepted Satelle File Secret Source tilde path before absolute-path syntax validation and treats the expanded platform-native absolute path as the effective File Secret Source value @spec @later
- satelle config check validates Satelle File Secret Source tilde syntax without reading the referenced file, resolving secret material, or contacting the target Host Daemon @spec @later
- satelle config explain redacts tilde-expanded Satelle File Secret Source values by default under the same rules as absolute File Secret Source values @spec @later
- satelle config explain --show-secret-references reports the effective normalized absolute Satelle File Secret Source path after tilde expansion when the resolving home directory is known locally, and otherwise reports normalization_status remote_home_not_checked without contacting the target Host Daemon @spec @later
- satelle project-level configuration cannot use Satelle File Secret Source tilde expansion to bypass the prohibition on project-level provider authentication Secret Sources @implemented @later
- satelle reports a typed project-secret-source-not-allowed configuration error when project-level configuration defines a provider authentication Satelle Secret Source, including a tilde-prefixed Satelle File Secret Source @implemented @later
- satelle reports a typed secret-file-tilde-form-unsupported configuration error when a Satelle File Secret Source uses unsupported tilde syntax @spec @later
- satelle reports a typed secret-file-home-unavailable error when a Host Daemon must expand a tilde-prefixed Satelle File Secret Source but the resolving OS account has no available home directory @spec @later
- satelle.error.v1 errors for secret-file-tilde-form-unsupported and secret-file-home-unavailable place config_file, toml_path, host, secret_source_kind, resolver_os, and supported_forms under details and place safe recovery commands under suggested_commands @spec @later
- satelle user-level TOML defines named profile overlays under [profiles.<name>], while top-level profile selects a config-file default; project TOML may select profile but cannot define profiles @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle profile overlays place host selection at host, model and provider intent at model_alias and provider_alias, provider opt-in at its existing key, host-bound YOLO policy at yolo, and timeout policy under nested timeouts; profile overlays do not define a hosts tree @spec @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle selects profiles in precedence order user config default, project config default, SATELLE_PROFILE, then global --profile; selecting an undefined profile reports typed profile-not-found with exit 66 @spec @contract @mvp @implemented

# roadmap

- every lifecycle-specification fact remains required project scope; MVP and later labels define delivery order rather than optionality @spec @mvp
- roadmap phases are dependency gates, so a later phase does not replace unresolved acceptance criteria from an earlier phase @spec @mvp

## phase-0-upstream-contract
- phase 0 is complete when one real supported Host exposes readiness and approval state, performs one harmless action, completes one attached native Codex Computer Use Turn through app-server, restores current Session state to a fresh Client after reconnect, starts one detached steer Turn, stops that Turn, and confirms its stopped state @spec @phase0 @mvp
- phase 0 records the supported Codex and app-server version range plus the required start, event, approval, steer, stop, and recovery capability matrix without exposing upstream method names as public Satelle contracts @spec @phase0 @mvp
- a missing required upstream capability produces an explicit typed blocker and prevents Satelle from claiming the affected workflow as supported @spec @phase0 @mvp
- phase 0 rejects terminal UI scraping or undocumented GUI automation as a substitute for a missing app-server contract unless the product specification is explicitly revised @spec @phase0 @mvp

## phase-1-core-contracts
- phase 1 freezes Satelle domain vocabulary, public identifiers, API envelopes, typed errors, configuration trust boundaries, event schemas, Control Lease invariants, and persistence contracts @spec @phase1 @mvp
- phase 1 provides transport-independent conformance tests through a deterministic internal adapter implementation @spec @phase1 @mvp
- phase 1 is complete when public types cannot serialize upstream identifiers, raw prompts, secret values, or contradictory lifecycle states @spec @phase1 @mvp

## phase-2-local-vertical-slice
- phase 2 implements one real Host Daemon API, SQLite-backed authoritative state, transactional Control Lease acquisition, and the Codex adapter on one supported Computer Use Host Platform @spec @phase2 @mvp
- phase 2 proves setup, doctor, run, status, steer, stop, logs, reconnect, restart recovery, redaction, and idempotency through the same public contracts @spec @phase2 @mvp
- phase 2 transport conformance uses real HTTP and WebSocket connections even when the Host Daemon runs in the same test process @spec @phase2 @mvp

## phase-3-remote-mvp
- phase 3 adds verified binary upload, SSH bootstrap, loopback tunneling, on-demand Host Daemon lifecycle, and the second MVP Computer Use Host Platform without changing the public Session model @spec @phase3 @mvp
- phase 3 completes persistent services, scoped authenticated direct transport, Tailscale integration, MCP, distribution, documentation, and release hardening required by every MVP-tagged fact @spec @phase3 @mvp
- public MVP release is blocked until the README, license, security policy, version-matched docs and bundled skills, security and legal review, release dry run or manual runbook rehearsal, signed protected tag checks, archive checksum and attestation checks, npm registry visibility and clean-install checks, every Controller suite, and every macOS and Windows Computer Use Host suite pass @spec @phase3 @mvp @release-gate @verification

## phase-4-full-scope
- phase 4 implements every fact tagged both spec and later in dependency order while preserving the public identifier, authority, safety, and compatibility contracts established by MVP @spec @phase4 @later
- later queueing, recording, raw diagnostics, config composition, package expansion, telemetry, and multi-user features do not weaken MVP consent, isolation, redaction, or Host identity boundaries @spec @phase4 @later
- phase 4A completes operational foundations: Config Includes, config repair, storage migration, credential helpers, Trusted Profile expiration, CLI-Host compatibility, explicit Host version selection, package repair, remote images, advanced output contracts, and mutual TLS @spec @phase4 @later
- phase 4B completes sensitive observability only after shared redaction, retention, manifest, consent, and audit conformance: diagnostic bundles, Raw Diagnostic Exports, recording, Platform-Native Log Sinks, and telemetry @spec @phase4 @later
- phase 4C completes durable queueing before the Multi-User Broker and proves restart recovery, cancellation, Principal reauthorization, isolation, and per-binding lease behavior before multi-user release @spec @phase4 @later
- phase 4D completes Automation Workflows, ecosystem distribution expansion, and native action relay only after their versioned command, schema, capability, security, and acceptance contracts pass without weakening earlier phase gates @spec @phase4 @later

# sessions

## lifecycle-state
- Satelle Turn nonterminal states are starting, running, and recovery_pending @spec @mvp
- Satelle Turn terminal states are completed, blocked, failed, and stopped @spec @mvp
- a terminal Satelle Turn never transitions to another Turn state @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Session has at most one nonterminal Turn @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Session is active exactly when it references one nonterminal Turn @spec @mvp
- satelle derives Session activity from the active Turn instead of storing an independently mutable duplicate status @spec @mvp
- a Satelle Session remains steerable after a terminal Turn while its Host and internal Codex thread mapping remain available @spec @mvp
- the Host Identity and Desktop Binding of a Satelle Session are immutable after Session creation @spec @mvp
- each Turn stores the effective model, Provider Binding, desktop target, approval policy, sandbox policy, timeout policy, and experimental-feature choices used for that Turn @spec @mvp
- every Session record has a monotonically increasing session_state_revision and every Turn record has a monotonically increasing turn_state_revision updated by each committed lifecycle mutation of that record @spec @contract @mvp
- public Session responses include session_state_revision and public Turn responses include turn_state_revision @spec @contract @mvp
- lifecycle Satelle Events include state_subject plus the corresponding session_state_revision or turn_state_revision, and Turn lifecycle events may include both revisions when one commit mutates both records @spec @contract @mvp
- the Host Daemon passes the committed Turn Execution Policy to the Codex adapter before Turn start @spec @mvp
- the Codex adapter never infers YOLO, provider, model, timeout, or desktop target from CLI presentation fields @spec @mvp

## admission-and-leases
- the Host Daemon acquires the selected Control Lease and creates the starting Turn in one SQLite transaction @spec @mvp
- Control Lease ownership is keyed by Host Identity and Desktop Binding instead of a Client-selected Host Alias @spec @mvp
- Host Aliases resolving to the same Host Identity and Desktop Binding share one Control Lease @spec @mvp
- Control Lease acquisition conflicts report host-busy without creating a Session, Turn, Codex thread, or attachment staging record @spec @mvp
- native Computer Use readiness smoke tests, provider smoke tests, and prompt Turns use the same exclusive Control Lease @spec @mvp
- doctor refresh reports host-busy instead of operating the desktop while a prompt Turn owns the Control Lease @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon releases the Control Lease in the same transaction that persists a terminal Turn state @spec @mvp
- a standalone readiness or provider probe releases its Control Lease in the same transaction that persists the terminal Readiness Result only after the Codex adapter confirms that no upstream probe Turn remains active @spec @mvp
- setup, repair, host update, storage migration, and service restart acquire a Maintenance Lease before mutation @spec @mvp
- a Maintenance Lease cannot coexist with a Control Lease for the same Host except when the same maintenance operation owns a postcheck Control sublease @spec @mvp
- Turn admission requires both the selected Control Lease and absence of a Maintenance Lease for the same Host @spec @mvp
- a maintenance operation that requires a live Computer Use postcheck retains its Maintenance Lease and atomically acquires an operation-owned postcheck Control sublease before running the probe @spec @mvp
- no other Turn, probe, or maintenance operation is admitted while a maintenance operation owns its postcheck Control sublease @spec @mvp
- a queued Turn Request does not start while a Maintenance Lease exists for its Host @spec @later
- a maintenance operation without a live postcheck releases its Maintenance Lease only in the transaction that durably commits its final action-ledger state @spec @mvp
- a maintenance operation with a live postcheck releases its postcheck Control sublease and Maintenance Lease only in the transaction that commits the final Readiness Result and final action-ledger state @spec @mvp
- Control and Maintenance Leases contain an operation id, owner process identity, acquisition time, and heartbeat time @spec @mvp
- lease owner process identity includes a process-start discriminator and operating-system boot identity instead of relying on a reusable process id alone @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon refreshes live Control and Maintenance Lease heartbeats at least every 5 seconds, and a missing heartbeat becomes stale after 30 seconds by default without permitting automatic lease release @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon startup treats an orphaned Control or Maintenance Lease as recovery_pending and blocks conflicting admission until reconciliation completes @spec @mvp
- an orphaned non-Turn Control Lease for a readiness or provider probe is classified outcome_unknown, reconciled against its probe process and upstream capability state, and resolved to a durable terminal Readiness Result before lease release @spec @mvp
- an orphaned Maintenance Lease operation is classified outcome_unknown and reconciled from its action postconditions before retry or release @spec @mvp
- lease expiry alone never proves that an external Computer Use or maintenance side effect stopped @spec @mvp
- timeout expiry, a cancellation request, transport loss, adapter failure, or lease expiry never by itself proves that an upstream Computer Use execution stopped and never by itself permits Control Lease release @spec @mvp
- initial setup, missing-daemon repair, and Host binary replacement acquire a Bootstrap Lock before mutating remote files or starting a replacement Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- a Bootstrap Lock uses atomic filesystem creation under the remote OS user's Satelle state boundary @spec @mvp
- a Bootstrap Lock records a non-secret operation id, Controller identity when known, acquisition time, and heartbeat time @spec @mvp
- a Controller refreshes its owned Bootstrap Lock heartbeat at least every 5 seconds while the bootstrap operation remains live @spec @mvp
- concurrent Bootstrap Lock acquisition fails with a typed bootstrap-busy error before remote mutation @spec @mvp
- every Bootstrap Lock mutation verifies immediately beforehand that the lock still contains the same operation id, and an owner that loses that check aborts without further mutation @spec @mvp
- stale Bootstrap Lock recovery probes remote process, binary, service, and Host Daemon state before the lock can be removed or replaced @spec @mvp
- stale Bootstrap Lock removal or replacement uses compare-and-set against the observed operation id after the required postcondition probes, so a recovered owner cannot delete a newer lock @spec @mvp
- initial setup and missing-daemon repair acquire Bootstrap Lock, start the Host Daemon, obtain a Maintenance Lease carrying the same operation id, and release Bootstrap Lock only after that handoff is durable @spec @mvp
- Host binary replacement on a reachable daemon first obtains a Maintenance Lease, then obtains Bootstrap Lock with the same operation id before stopping or replacing the daemon @spec @mvp
- the replacement Host Daemon reconciles and adopts that maintenance operation before Bootstrap Lock release, and no workflow acquires these locks in the opposite order for the same operation class @spec @mvp
- a Bootstrap Lock operation that fails before any remote mutation or managed process starts records a clean failure and releases the lock @spec @mvp
- a Bootstrap Lock operation that may have mutated remote state or started a managed process preserves the lock and recovery metadata until postcondition reconciliation proves the outcome @spec @mvp

## stop-and-recovery
- satelle stop transitions a starting, running, or recovery_pending Turn to stopped only after the adapter confirms cancellation or otherwise proves that the same upstream Turn is no longer active @spec @mvp
- satelle stop on a terminal Turn returns already_terminal without changing stored history @spec @mvp
- concurrent completion and stop use a compare-and-set transition so exactly one terminal state wins @spec @mvp
- a late Codex completion cannot overwrite a previously committed stopped state @spec @mvp
- a stop request that cannot confirm upstream cancellation reports stop-not-confirmed instead of persisting a false stopped state @spec @mvp
- stop-not-confirmed leaves the Turn nonterminal, preserves running when the same upstream Turn is known active or recovery_pending when its state is ambiguous, and retains the Control Lease @spec @mvp
- satelle stop is idempotent for the same Session, Turn, and idempotency key @spec @mvp
- transport disconnection does not stop a remote Turn @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer support --detach-on-interrupt to leave an already-created remote Turn running when the attached CLI receives Ctrl-C @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed interrupt-mode-conflict usage error when --detach-on-interrupt and --detach are combined @spec @mvp
- interrupting an attached run or steer command after Turn creation sends a stop request before the CLI exits unless --detach-on-interrupt was selected @spec @mvp
- interrupting run or steer before Turn creation requests cancellation of any active readiness or provider probe without sending a stop request for a nonexistent prompt Turn; it releases the Control Lease only after probe termination is confirmed and otherwise leaves recovery_pending ownership for reconciliation @spec @mvp
- an attached CLI that cannot confirm stop after interruption prints the Session identifier and a status recovery command before exiting 130 @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon startup marks every stored nonterminal Turn as recovery_pending before accepting a new Turn for the same Control Lease @spec @mvp
- startup reconciliation queries the Codex adapter before resolving a recovery_pending Turn @spec @mvp
- startup reconciliation restores running only when the adapter proves that the same upstream Turn remains active @spec @mvp
- startup reconciliation records failed with a typed daemon-restart-recovery-failed cause and releases the Control Lease only when the adapter proves that the same upstream Turn is no longer active and cannot be recovered @spec @mvp
- when startup reconciliation cannot determine whether the same upstream Turn remains active, the Turn remains recovery_pending, the Control Lease remains held, and conflicting admission remains blocked with outcome_unknown recovery guidance @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon never admits a new Turn while previous Turn ownership remains ambiguous @spec @mvp

## public-identity-and-retention
- satelle exposes Satelle-owned Session identifiers to CLI users and JSON output consumers instead of exposing Codex thread IDs as the public Session contract @spec @mvp
- satelle session identifiers are opaque unique IDs suitable for scripts instead of human-readable prompt-derived slugs @implemented @mvp
- satelle Session identifiers use the exact rs_ prefix followed by a canonical lowercase UUIDv7 @contract @mvp @implemented
- satelle Turn identifiers use the exact rt_ prefix followed by a canonical lowercase UUIDv7 @contract @mvp @implemented
- public turn_id fields always contain Satelle Turn identifiers and never upstream Codex turn identifiers @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle sessions may have optional display names for human listing without making display names the primary identifier @spec @mvp
- satelle never exposes Codex thread, turn, goal, app-server request, or provider request identifiers in public CLI, API, MCP, event, log, or diagnostic contracts @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP allows multiple stored Sessions per Host but only one active native Computer Use Turn per Control Lease at a time @spec @mvp
- satelle run and steer report a typed host-busy error when they would start a second active Computer Use Turn for the same Control Lease @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not automatically queue run or steer commands when a host is busy @implemented @mvp
- satelle later explicit queueing is disabled by default and never changes MVP host-busy behavior unless the user opts in for the selected Host, selected profile, or specific run or steer command @spec @later
- satelle run and steer use --queue as the exact per-command queue opt-in @spec @later
- every accepted Queued Turn Request receives a public identifier using the exact rq_ prefix followed by a canonical lowercase UUIDv7 @spec @contract @later
- enqueueing creates a Queued Turn Request but no upstream thread or Turn; queued run creates its Session, upstream thread, and starting Turn atomically only when admitted, while queued steer links to its existing Session @spec @later
- satelle queue status <queue_request_id> and satelle queue cancel <queue_request_id> are the canonical inspection and cancellation commands @spec @later
- satelle queue status JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.queue.status.v1 and includes queue_request_id, status, position, enqueued_at, expires_at, session_id, turn_id, failure, and state revision fields where applicable @spec @contract @later
- satelle queue cancel JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.queue.cancel.v1 and includes queue_request_id, outcome, changed, session_id, and turn_id; outcome is cancelled or already_terminal @spec @contract @later
- queue cancel on an already admitted request reports queue-already-admitted with its Session and Turn identifiers plus a stop command instead of attempting to cancel the queue record @spec @later
- user-level Host and profile configuration use queue.enabled, queue.max_depth, and queue.ttl as the exact queue settings @spec @later
- queue lifecycle results and events include queue_request_id and link the admitted Session and Turn identifiers when admission succeeds @spec @contract @later
- satelle project-level configuration, install scripts, setup defaults, --yes, YOLO mode, Trusted Profile mutation consent, and transport defaults cannot enable queued prompt execution @spec @later
- satelle queued run and steer requests preserve the one active native Computer Use Turn per Control Lease invariant by starting only after the current active Turn releases that Control Lease @spec @later
- satelle queued run and steer requests are stored, ordered, and started by the target Host Daemon instead of by the local CLI process @spec @later
- satelle queued run and steer requests revalidate host reachability, native Computer Use readiness, provider Computer Use compatibility, desktop session resolution, and session existence immediately before starting instead of treating enqueue-time preflight as authorization to execute later @spec @later
- each Queued Turn Request stores the non-secret API Principal token id and token credential revision, immutable request digest, and requested execution policy without storing bearer-token material @spec @later
- immediately before a queued request starts, the Host Daemon revalidates that its API Principal and token credential revision still exist, are not expired or revoked, retain the required scopes, and remain authorized by current Host, Desktop Binding, provider, YOLO, and execution-policy constraints @spec @later
- token expiry, revocation, or rotation cancels not-yet-started queued requests authorized by the affected token credential revision and records a typed queued-principal-no-longer-authorized outcome @spec @later
- satelle queued run and steer requests support explicit cancellation before they start and report typed errors for canceled, expired, full-queue, and pre-start-validation-failed outcomes @spec @later
- satelle explicit queueing uses FIFO ordering within one Control Lease @spec @later
- satelle queued Turn Requests default to a maximum queue depth of 16 per Control Lease @spec @later
- queue.max_depth accepts values from 1 through 256 @spec @later
- satelle queued Turn Requests expire after 1 hour by default @spec @later
- queue.ttl is configurable per Host or profile with a finite maximum of 24 hours @spec @later
- queued Turn Requests survive Host Daemon restart in the authoritative SQLite store @spec @later
- explicit queueing warns that the queued prompt and attachment staging must be retained until the request starts, is cancelled, or expires @spec @later
- queued prompt payloads are stored separately from Session and Turn metadata under the sensitive-state filesystem boundary @spec @later
- queued prompt payloads and attachments are deleted after Turn admission, cancellation, expiry, or bounded crash-recovery cleanup @spec @later
- satelle queue status and logs expose queued position, enqueue time, expiry time, and normalized pre-start failure without exposing raw prompt or attachment content @spec @later
- Satelle Events distinguish turn_queued, queue_position_changed, turn_dequeued, turn_queue_cancelled, turn_queue_expired, and turn_queue_validation_failed @spec @later
- satelle maps each Satelle session to the underlying Codex thread, turn, and goal identifiers inside the Host Daemon adapter layer @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon durably persists each newly observed upstream Codex thread or Turn identifier before the Codex adapter continues waiting for later upstream work @mvp @implemented
- persisting an upstream Codex identifier does not change Session or Turn lifecycle state, state revisions, safe logs, idempotency outcomes, or Control Lease ownership @mvp @implemented
- recording the same upstream Codex identifier again is idempotent, while recording a different identifier for the same Session or Turn fails closed without overwriting the original @mvp @implemented
- satelle session records include enough host, readiness, provider, goal, and lifecycle metadata to survive transport changes without changing the public session identifier @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon is the canonical store for session metadata because it owns the Codex thread, app-server lifecycle, Computer Use readiness, logs, and recovery state @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI may keep read-only convenience cache for recently used sessions but must refresh from the Host Daemon before reporting authoritative status @spec @mvp
- satelle status reconnects to the session's remote host automatically when the local CLI has no active connection @spec @mvp
- satelle status and logs are the MVP surfaces for later inspection after a user disconnects from a live event stream @implemented @mvp
- satelle clients that reconnect after missing live Satelle Events read current session state and normalized logs instead of replaying missed events @spec @mvp
- satelle status for SSH bootstrap hosts may restart the on-demand Host Daemon before reading stored remote session metadata @spec @mvp
- satelle status reports a typed session-not-found error when the selected host cannot find the requested session metadata @implemented @mvp
- a Session operation verifies that the requested Session belongs to the connected Host Identity @spec @mvp
- the local CLI uses its non-authoritative Session-to-Host cache only to select a candidate Host @spec @mvp
- satelle requires --host when a Session identifier cannot be mapped to exactly one configured Host without probing unrelated Hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle remote host retains minimal session metadata for 7 days by default @spec @mvp
- satelle session metadata retention can be configured per host or profile @spec @mvp
- session retention cleanup never deletes a nonterminal Session or Turn @spec @mvp
- session retention age begins when the Session's most recent Turn becomes terminal @spec @mvp
- expiration of Satelle metadata does not claim to delete Codex, provider, or operating-system records outside Satelle ownership @spec @mvp
- satelle can export a redacted task artifact set containing plan.md, worklog.md, and goal.md for a selected session so another agent or human can audit what happened without replaying raw desktop content @spec @mvp
- satelle records local redacted command history for setup, repair, run, steer, status, stop, logs, doctor, host, config, and MCP installer commands when local state storage is available @spec @mvp
- satelle later extends local redacted command history to batch, watch, notify, and REPL Automation Workflows @spec @later
- satelle local command history stores command family, selected host, selected profile, session id when present, started_at, duration_ms, outcome status, typed error code, and Satelle CLI version without storing raw provider secrets, raw prompts, screenshots, or transcripts by default @spec @mvp
- satelle local command history can be disabled through user-level configuration or an environment option before the command starts @spec @mvp
- satelle local aggregate stats summarize command counts, success and failure counts, last-used hosts, last-used profiles, and common typed error codes from redacted command history @spec @mvp
- satelle local aggregate stats are diagnostic convenience data and are never treated as authoritative remote host state @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes a top-level logs command in MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs is a read-only diagnostic command that never starts prompt execution, setup, repair, host update, service mutation, or configuration mutation @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs reads authoritative Satelle Log Entries from the remote Host Daemon instead of relying on a local CLI cache @spec @mvp
- satelle logs targets the resolved current or default host when no host or session selector is provided @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs supports --host <alias> to read host-scoped logs for a configured remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle logs supports --session <session_id> to read logs scoped to one Satelle session @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs reports a typed logs-target-required error when no host, default host, current host, or session selector can be resolved @spec @mvp
- satelle logs for SSH bootstrap hosts may restart the on-demand Host Daemon before reading stored normalized logs @spec @mvp
- satelle logs supports --tail <n> to limit output to the most recent n matching log entries @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs defaults to --tail 200 when neither --tail nor --since is provided @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs accepts --tail values from 1 through 10000 and reports a typed log-tail-limit-exceeded usage error for larger values @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs supports --since <duration-or-rfc3339> to show only matching log entries at or after the requested time @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs supports -f and --follow to continue streaming new matching log entries after the initial result set @spec @mvp
- satelle logs supports repeatable --source <host_daemon|codex_adapter|transport|readiness|provider_smoke|setup|repair> filters @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs without --source includes all MVP log sources that pass the default redaction policy @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs supports --level <trace|debug|info|warn|error> as a minimum severity filter @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs default minimum severity is info @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs MVP does not support --export <path> or support bundle creation @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs uses stdout as the data output contract instead of adding file destination flags in MVP @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs human output writes log entries to stdout and diagnostics or command errors to stderr @implemented @mvp
- satelle logs --json emits the initial matching set as one LF-terminated satelle.logs.entry.v1 JSON record per entry without a top-level wrapper @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle logs --json without --follow exits 0 with empty stdout when no entries match, while satelle logs --json --follow remains attached waiting for later matching entries until interrupted or failed @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle logs JSON records include target, source, severity, timestamp, optional Session id, message, structured fields, redaction metadata, and their opaque Log Cursor @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle logs supports --after <log_cursor> to return entries strictly after one previously delivered Log Cursor @spec @mvp
- satelle logs reports a typed log-position-conflict usage error when --after and --since are both provided @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --json --follow continues the same newline-delimited satelle.logs.entry.v1 record stream after the initial matching set @spec @contract @mvp
- satelle logs --follow exits 130 when interrupted by Ctrl-C and does not treat the interrupt as a remote host failure @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow automatically attempts to reconnect when the log stream ends because of transient transport loss or Host Daemon restart @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow resumes after reconnect by querying stored Satelle Log Entries newer than the last delivered log cursor instead of replaying missed live Satelle Events @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow validates target host identity and session scope before resuming after reconnect @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow stops reconnecting and reports a typed logs-follow-identity-changed error when the reconnected host identity or requested session scope does not match the original target @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow uses a default reconnect budget of 60 seconds per stream interruption @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow stops after 10 stream interruptions in one command and reports a typed logs-follow-reconnect-exhausted error @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow reconnect backoff starts at 250 milliseconds and caps at 5 seconds with jitter @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow does not retry forever after the reconnect budget or interruption cap is exhausted @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow reports a typed logs-follow-reconnect-exhausted error with the last delivered log cursor and a rerun command when reconnection fails within the budget @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow writes reconnect notices and reconnect failures to stderr while preserving stdout for log entries or JSON log-entry objects @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --json --follow does not emit reconnect control records to stdout in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle logs --follow supports --no-reconnect to fail immediately on stream loss after reporting the last delivered log cursor @spec @mvp
- satelle logs show Satelle daemon events and normalized Codex event summaries by default @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP logs command exposes normalized daemon events, session lifecycle changes, readiness summaries, provider smoke-test summaries, and structured errors instead of raw protocol payloads @spec @mvp
- satelle logs do not expose raw Codex app-server protocol messages by default @implemented @mvp
- satelle MVP logs command does not expose raw Codex app-server protocol messages, provider request or response bodies, full prompts, screenshots, desktop recordings, or full transcripts by default @implemented @mvp
- satelle later raw protocol diagnostics are implemented only as a command-specific Raw Diagnostic Export that explicitly selects raw Codex app-server protocol messages or provider request and response bodies for one Session or command scope @spec @later
- satelle later run and steer use --raw-protocol --output <path> as the prospective command-specific raw protocol capture request for that invocation @spec @later
- a raw protocol capture begins only after its warning and consent complete and never reconstructs or labels protocol data for an earlier Turn from normal retained Session metadata @spec @later
- satelle raw protocol diagnostic exports do not make raw Codex app-server protocol messages, provider request bodies, provider response bodies, full prompts, screenshots, desktop recordings, or full transcripts available through satelle logs, status, doctor, diagnostic bundles, Satelle Events, Satelle Operator Log Files, or setup action ledger summaries @spec @later
- satelle stores minimal lifecycle metadata and structured errors by default instead of persisting desktop screenshots or full event transcripts @spec @mvp
- satelle does not persist full Satelle Event streams by default @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not provide session recording modes, screenshot recording, full event transcript recording, desktop recording, or host-level recording defaults @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP normal status, logs, run, and steer commands do not capture, display, persist, or export desktop snapshot imagery by default @implemented @mvp
- satelle later exposes satelle desktop snapshot --host <alias> --output <path> as the only Desktop Snapshot Export command @spec @later
- satelle desktop snapshot JSON v1 uses schema_version satelle.desktop.snapshot.v1 and includes source Host, Host Identity, Desktop Binding, output path, artifact format, artifact byte size, redaction metadata, and created_at @spec @contract @later
- a Desktop Snapshot Export requires the selected Host Alias to resolve to exactly one trusted Host Identity and Desktop Binding and reports typed desktop-snapshot-target-required or desktop-snapshot-ambiguous errors otherwise @spec @later
- a Desktop Snapshot Export captures only the current visible desktop at invocation time, acquires the applicable Control Lease, reports host-busy on conflict, and never claims to export imagery from an earlier Session or Turn @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports require an explicit --output <path> destination controlled by the invoking OS user and never choose an upload destination, support endpoint, cloud bucket, public URL, or remote storage destination automatically @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports show the exact output path, artifact format, storage implication, redaction policy version, and remaining unredacted visual-risk categories before asking for confirmation @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports require interactive confirmation after showing the warning and report a typed desktop-snapshot-consent-required error before capture when stdin is not a TTY, --no-input is set, or interactive consent cannot be obtained @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Export consent is scoped to one command invocation and cannot be stored in project configuration, user configuration, Trusted Profiles, Host defaults, or environment variables @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports run native Computer Use capture permission diagnostics before capture and fail before capture with a typed desktop-snapshot-permission-required diagnostic when OS privacy permissions, app approvals, desktop-session availability, or native Computer Use runtime permissions are missing @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports do not open a provider probe surface, start prompt execution, move the pointer, type, or attempt permission repair as a side effect of capture @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports apply a declared desktop-snapshot redaction policy before writing the artifact and fail with a typed desktop-snapshot-redaction-failed error when required redaction cannot be applied @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports do not persist imagery outside the confirmed output artifact and bounded command staging files; they never write imagery to Host Daemon SQLite, normal logs, status output, diagnostic bundles, Satelle Events, Satelle Operator Log Files, readiness caches, setup ledgers, or recording artifacts @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Export staging files are stored outside normal Satelle logs and caches and are deleted after successful export or after a bounded failure-retention window @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Export manifests include source Host, Host Identity, Desktop Binding, desktop session identity when known, included data categories, redaction policy version, redaction categories applied, known unredacted visual-risk categories, created_at, artifact format version, and artifact byte size when available @spec @later
- Desktop Snapshot Exports record audit metadata in the Host Daemon SQLite store without storing imagery, thumbnails, OCR text, raw desktop pixels, output artifact contents, provider credentials, prompts, or transcripts in the audit record @spec @later
- satelle later run and steer accept --record <events|transcript|screenshots|video> and --record-retention <duration>; recording applies only to the Turn started by that invocation and begins only after preflight and explicit consent complete @spec @later
- satelle never reconstructs or labels a recording for an earlier Turn from retained Session metadata @spec @later
- recording modes require explicit consent for the prospective Turn before capturing screenshots, desktop video, full transcripts, or replayable Satelle Event streams @spec @later
- satelle recording mode consent is scoped to one prospective Turn request and its resulting Session and Turn and cannot be stored in project configuration, user configuration, Satelle Trusted Profiles, environment variables, YOLO mode, --yes, --verbose, --debug, --json, --events, or --plain @spec @later
- satelle Host Daemon enforces host recording policy before recording capture begins and refuses recording modes that the selected host policy disables or narrows @spec @later
- satelle recording mode preflight reports the selected mode, source Host, Host policy constraints, resolved recording_root, retention expiry, and known unredacted risk categories before asking for consent @spec @later
- satelle recording modes must resolve a finite retention period before capture begins and reject unbounded retain-forever retention values @spec @later
- satelle recording artifacts include a manifest with recording mode, session id, source host, created_at, artifact paths, retention expiry, redaction policy version, redaction categories applied, and known unredacted risk categories @spec @later
- satelle recording modes apply the default Satelle redaction policy to transcript, event, metadata, and text-derived artifacts before export or display @spec @later
- satelle recording modes that capture visible desktop pixels warn that screenshots or desktop video may contain unredacted visible desktop content even when metadata and text artifacts are redacted @spec @later
- satelle recording mode output reports every produced artifact path, retention expiry, and cleanup command so storage remains visible to the invoking user @spec @later
- satelle recording modes record audit metadata in the Host Daemon SQLite store without storing screenshot bytes, desktop video bytes, full transcripts, raw prompts, provider request bodies, provider response bodies, or raw artifact contents in the audit record @spec @later
- Host Daemon Session HTTP responses use the canonical PublicSession and PublicTurn lifecycle states and revisions and never embed Satelle Event streams or Controller-owned Host Alias fields @spec @contract @mvp
- one upstream Codex thread identifier belongs to at most one Satelle Session, and recording it for another Session fails closed @implemented @mvp
- one upstream Codex Turn identifier belongs to at most one Satelle Turn, and recording it for another Turn fails closed @implemented @mvp

# storage

## transactional-integrity
- satelle Host Daemon uses SQLite on the remote host as the canonical local store for session metadata, turn lifecycle, readiness cache, provider Computer Use smoke results, setup action ledgers, and normalized log summaries @spec @mvp
- one Host Daemon process holds an exclusive ownership lock for one SQLite store while serving requests @spec @mvp
- a second Host Daemon process for the same SQLite store fails with a typed store-in-use error before accepting API requests @spec @mvp
- satelle enables SQLite foreign-key enforcement for every Host Daemon connection @spec @mvp
- SQLite busy exhaustion returns a typed storage-busy error instead of dropping or overwriting state @spec @mvp
- Turn admission, active-Turn uniqueness, Session linkage, Idempotency Record creation, and Control Lease ownership are committed atomically @spec @mvp
- every lifecycle transition uses the prior session_state_revision and turn_state_revision of every affected record as transaction preconditions @spec @contract @mvp
- a failed lifecycle transition precondition returns a typed state-conflict error without rewriting the winning state @spec @mvp
- a failed startup integrity check blocks state-changing operations plus ordinary status and log reads until repair or restore succeeds, while exposing only minimal redacted integrity diagnostics needed for safe repair @spec @mvp

## privacy-and-filesystem
- Satelle-owned SQLite Session and Turn records do not store raw prompt text by default @spec @mvp
- Satelle-owned stores do not persist raw Codex final transcripts by default @spec @mvp
- prompt-derived summaries are redacted before persistence @spec @mvp
- when required redaction fails, Satelle omits the sensitive field or fails the entire record, output, or artifact write and never persists or emits the unredacted value as a fallback @spec @mvp
- internal Codex and provider identifiers are schema-marked sensitive storage fields and never enter public response types @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon state directories are accessible only to the daemon OS user and required operating-system service principals @spec @mvp
- Satelle creates sensitive POSIX directories with mode 0700 and sensitive POSIX files with mode 0600 @spec @mvp
- Satelle applies equivalent current-user restricted ACLs to sensitive Windows state @spec @mvp
- SQLite database, WAL, SHM, token verifier, attachment staging, and sensitive export staging files inherit the same restricted access boundary @spec @mvp
- Satelle Operator Log Files, local CLI state and cache, migration backups, setup recovery metadata, and recording artifacts inherit the same OS-user-private directory and file boundary @spec @mvp
- Satelle refuses to use a sensitive state path that resolves through an unsafe writable directory boundary @spec @mvp
- retention deletion does not claim cryptographic erasure from SQLite pages, filesystem snapshots, backups, or upstream services @spec @mvp
- Satelle documents that Codex and model providers may retain data independently from Satelle-owned retention @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI cache stores only convenience data such as redacted command history, aggregate stats, AI client installer state, downloaded release metadata, and non-authoritative recent host summaries @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI cache root is configurable through SATELLE_CACHE_DIR @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI cache entries have explicit time-to-live or retention policies instead of persisting indefinitely by default @spec @mvp
- satelle local CLI cache never stores provider credentials, raw prompts, screenshots, desktop recordings, full transcripts, raw Codex protocol payloads, or raw provider request and response bodies by default @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon stores its SQLite database under the resolved Satelle local mutable state root @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon stores recording artifacts under a recordings directory inside the resolved Satelle local mutable state root by default @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon writes Satelle Operator Log Files by default when the resolved OS-native Satelle log directory is writable @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log Files are a best-effort local inspection mirror and are never authoritative for satelle logs, satelle status, recovery, retention, or support bundle collection @spec @mvp
- satelle logs command reads Satelle Log Entries from SQLite through the Host Daemon API instead of parsing Satelle Operator Log Files @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log Files contain human-readable redacted summaries derived from Satelle Log Entries instead of raw protocol payloads or raw subprocess streams @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log Files do not include provider request bodies, provider response bodies, full prompts, screenshots, desktop recordings, full transcripts, raw setup stdout, raw setup stderr, raw repair stdout, or raw repair stderr by default @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log Files rotate at 10 MiB and retain at most 5 files total per Host Daemon instance by default @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log File retention can be configured per host or profile without changing SQLite log retention @spec @mvp
- satelle Satelle Operator Log Files are stored under an OS-native Satelle log directory on the remote host instead of project directories @spec @mvp
- satelle default Linux Satelle Operator Log File root is ${XDG_STATE_HOME:-$HOME/.local/state}/satelle/logs @spec @mvp
- satelle default Windows Satelle Operator Log File root is the Local AppData Known Folder joined with Microck\Satelle\data\state\logs @spec @mvp
- satelle default macOS Satelle Operator Log File root is $HOME/Library/Logs/dev.Microck.Satelle @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon continues running when Satelle Operator Log File writes fail while SQLite remains writable, and records the degraded log-file sink as a typed diagnostic finding @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon writes startup, shutdown, and fatal-error notices to stdout or stderr so service managers and containers can capture minimal process diagnostics @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not require direct journald, Windows Event Log, or macOS unified logging API integration as a separate log sink @spec @mvp
- satelle later adds Platform-Native Log Sinks only as optional mirrors of redacted Satelle Log Entries @spec @later
- satelle Satelle Platform-Native Log Sinks never replace the Host Daemon SQLite store, Satelle Operator Log Files, or the Host Daemon API as the authoritative source for satelle logs, status, recovery, retention, or support bundle collection @spec @later
- satelle Satelle Platform-Native Log Sinks emit the same redacted summaries and default exclusions as Satelle Operator Log Files instead of raw protocol payloads, provider bodies, prompts, screenshots, transcripts, recordings, or raw setup and repair subprocess streams @spec @later
- satelle Host Daemon continues running when a Satelle Platform-Native Log Sink fails while SQLite remains writable, and records the degraded platform-native log sink as a typed diagnostic finding @spec @later
- satelle Satelle Platform-Native Log Sink retention and query behavior are treated as operating-system-managed mirror behavior and do not change SQLite Satelle Log Entry retention, Satelle Operator Log File retention, or satelle logs output semantics @spec @later
- satelle SQLite Satelle Log Entries are retained for 7 days by default @spec @mvp
- satelle SQLite Satelle Log Entry retention can be configured per host or profile @spec @mvp
- each persisted Satelle Log Entry receives a monotonic Log Cursor in its Host Daemon store @spec @mvp
- logs pagination resumes strictly after the last delivered Log Cursor @spec @mvp
- logs follow reconnection uses a Log Cursor instead of timestamp alone @spec @mvp
- a Log Cursor older than retained log history reports a typed logs-cursor-expired error and identifies the earliest available cursor @spec @mvp
- satelle stores the Satelle Setup Action Ledger in the remote Host Daemon SQLite store instead of storing it only on the local CLI machine @spec @mvp
- satelle treats the remote Host Daemon SQLite setup action ledger as authoritative for setup and repair recovery because it records mutations against that remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI may cache setup action ledger summaries for display convenience but must refresh from the Host Daemon before reporting authoritative setup or repair state @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger records are scoped to the target host, OS user or desktop session when relevant, Satelle host binary version, and setup run identifier @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger entries store stable action id, action label, action status, start time, completion or failure time, retry safety, error code, and recovery hint metadata @spec @mvp
- a setup action is durably recorded as started before its external mutation begins @spec @mvp
- a setup action is durably recorded as completed only after its postcondition is verified @spec @mvp
- a setup action left started after a crash is classified as outcome_unknown @spec @mvp
- repair never reruns an outcome_unknown action until live probes determine its postcondition @spec @mvp
- repair reruns an incomplete action automatically only when the action is marked retry_safe @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger entries store normalized action summaries instead of raw installer, shell, service-manager, or operating-system command output by default @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger entries do not store raw stdout or raw stderr from setup and repair subprocesses by default @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger entries store subprocess exit status or platform-specific termination status when that status is available @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger entries store redacted failure hints only when the hint can be derived without preserving raw stdout or stderr @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair human output does not print raw installer stdout or stderr by default, even in verbose mode @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair verbose output expands normalized action status, typed errors, exit status, and recovery hints without exposing raw subprocess streams by default @spec @mvp
- satelle logs and status commands do not expose raw setup or repair subprocess stdout or stderr by default @spec @mvp
- satelle diagnostic bundles do not include raw setup or repair subprocess stdout or stderr by default @spec @later
- satelle MVP does not include a CLI flag, configuration key, API option, or diagnostic bundle mode for capturing or exporting raw setup and repair subprocess stdout or stderr @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP setup and repair diagnostics rely on normalized action summaries, typed errors, exit status, readiness probes, and recovery commands instead of raw subprocess streams @spec @mvp
- satelle later setup and repair raw subprocess output capture is implemented only as a Raw Diagnostic Export for one invocation and requires a command-specific raw export flag plus --output <path> before capture begins @spec @later
- satelle setup and repair Raw Diagnostic Exports may include selected raw stdout and raw stderr from setup or repair subprocesses, subprocess command identifiers, exit or termination status, timestamps, and redaction metadata, but do not include raw provider secrets, raw prompts, full transcripts, screenshots, desktop recordings, or provider request or response bodies unless another command-specific raw export fact explicitly allows them @spec @later
- satelle setup and repair Raw Diagnostic Exports apply the shared Satelle Raw Diagnostic Export warning, interactive and noninteractive consent, redaction, manifest, audit metadata, staging, failure-retention, and typed-error rules before any raw subprocess stream is captured or exported @spec @later
- satelle setup and repair Raw Diagnostic Export staging for raw subprocess streams is stored outside the setup action ledger, Satelle Log Entries, Satelle Operator Log Files, status state, diagnostic bundle inputs, readiness caches, and normal CLI caches @spec @later
- satelle setup action ledger entries for invocations that produce a setup or repair Raw Diagnostic Export may store only redacted export audit metadata or an export reference identifier, never raw stdout, raw stderr, artifact contents, staging paths containing raw material, or redaction-failed data @spec @later
- satelle setup and repair Raw Diagnostic Exports are not included in normal setup action ledger summaries, satelle logs, satelle status, satelle doctor, Satelle Events, Satelle Operator Log Files, or diagnostic bundles unless the user explicitly invokes the command-specific raw export mode for that command @spec @later
- satelle setup action ledger records follow the same SQLite migration, retention, repair, reset, and export rules as other Host Daemon metadata unless a more specific setup retention policy is configured @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger records are retained for 30 days by default @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger retention can be configured per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle setup action ledger retention cleanup deletes ledger metadata only and does not uninstall, roll back, or modify completed setup actions @spec @mvp
- satelle normal prompt execution does not require retained setup action ledger records after the host passes current native Computer Use readiness checks @spec @mvp
- satelle repair uses retained setup action ledger records when available but can re-plan from live host probes when the relevant ledger records expired or are missing @spec @mvp
- satelle repair treats missing, expired, or incompatible setup action ledger records as non-blocking when live host probes can run @spec @mvp
- satelle repair reports setup action ledger availability as diagnostic context instead of treating missing history as the repair cause when live host probes identify current blockers @spec @mvp
- satelle repair performs fresh OS-aware live probes before generating a repair plan when no usable setup action ledger is available @spec @mvp
- satelle repair generates a fresh idempotent action plan from current host probe results, effective configuration, target operating system, transport capabilities, and current Codex readiness blockers when no usable setup action ledger is available @spec @mvp
- satelle repair does not assume previously completed setup actions succeeded unless the current host probes verify the resulting state @spec @mvp
- satelle repair writes a new setup action ledger for the new repair run even when the previous setup action ledger expired or is missing @spec @mvp
- satelle repair does not automatically execute a live-probe-derived repair plan solely because no usable setup action ledger is available @spec @mvp
- satelle repair follows the same plan presentation, final interactive confirmation, --dry-run, --yes, and --no-input --yes mutation consent rules when no usable setup action ledger is available @spec @mvp
- satelle repair with no usable setup action ledger requires --no-input --yes before mutating the remote host in non-interactive mode @spec @mvp
- satelle repair --dry-run with no usable setup action ledger reports the live-probe-derived repair plan without mutating the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle repair human output mentions unavailable setup history as a warning only when it affects explanation quality, then shows the live-probe-derived repair plan @spec @mvp
- satelle repair JSON output includes ledger_status and plan_source fields when repair planning uses live probes because no usable setup action ledger is available @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed setup-ledger-unavailable diagnostic when a user asks to inspect or resume a specific setup run whose ledger records expired or are missing @spec @mvp
- satelle SQLite does not store a replayable Satelle Event history in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle stores opt-in recording artifacts as files referenced by SQLite metadata instead of storing large screenshots or transcripts directly in SQLite @spec @later
- satelle SQLite recording metadata includes artifact path, timestamp, type, hash or integrity marker, and retention state @spec @later
- satelle stores recording artifact files under an OS-native Satelle app data directory on the remote host @spec @later
- satelle does not store recording artifacts in project directories by default @spec @later
- satelle recording artifact retention defaults to 24 hours @spec @later
- satelle recording artifact retention can be configured per host, profile, or recording-enabled session @spec @later
- satelle SQLite access uses rusqlite behind a small storage boundary instead of spreading SQL calls through daemon handlers @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon keeps blocking SQLite work off Tokio runtime worker threads through a storage service boundary or spawn_blocking pattern @spec @mvp
- satelle embeds SQLite schema migrations in the binary so on-demand remote bootstrap does not require sidecar migration files @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon applies embedded SQLite migrations on startup before accepting API requests @spec @mvp
- satelle runs each migration step transactionally when SQLite supports transactional execution for that step @spec @mvp
- satelle creates a SQLite-consistent backup before the first irreversible migration step @spec @mvp
- a pre-migration backup is flushed to durable storage and passes SQLite integrity validation before the first irreversible migration step begins @spec @mvp
- each migration backup records the source schema version, source database digest, created_at, Satelle version, and restore-compatibility metadata without adding plaintext secrets @spec @mvp
- a failed migration never deletes or overwrites the only validated backup capable of restoring the pre-migration store @spec @mvp
- satelle does not automatically downgrade, reset, or delete the SQLite store when migration fails @spec @mvp
- satelle reports migration failures with typed errors and repair guidance instead of starting with a partially migrated store @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle host storage restore --host <alias> --backup <path> as the explicit authenticated restore operation @spec @mvp
- host storage restore verifies backup integrity and compatibility, preserves the failed store separately, runs under the applicable Maintenance Lease or Bootstrap Lock, and atomically activates the restored store before restarting API service @spec @mvp
- host storage restore follows maintenance plan presentation, --dry-run, interactive confirmation, --yes, --no-input --yes, action-ledger, and partial-failure rules @spec @mvp
- migration-backup cleanup retains the newest validated pre-migration backup and at least one previous validated backup by default @spec @mvp
- satelle host storage backup cleanup --host <alias> is the explicit command for deleting older eligible migration backups after a dry-run plan and mutation consent @spec @mvp
- satelle destructive store reset is available only through an explicit host maintenance command @spec @mvp
- satelle host store reset deletes metadata only by default and does not delete recordings unless the user explicitly requests recording deletion @spec @mvp
- satelle does not use ad hoc JSON files as the canonical store for session metadata, readiness cache, provider smoke results, or log summaries @spec @mvp
- satelle storage remains local to the remote host unless the user explicitly exports diagnostics or recordings @spec @mvp

# bridge

## security
- satelle does not store plaintext secrets in Satelle configuration files @spec @mvp
- satelle delegates SSH keys, provider API keys, Codex authentication, and app-server tokens to existing secret stores or remote-host token files @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not collect telemetry or send crash reports from the CLI or Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle later telemetry is an explicit opt-in feature with documented collection scope, redaction rules, retention policy, disable behavior, and exclusion rules for secrets, raw prompts, screenshots, desktop recordings, full transcripts, and provider request or response bodies @spec @later
- satelle telemetry opt-in cannot be enabled by project-level configuration, install scripts, setup defaults, Host bootstrap, package-manager installation, --yes, or Satelle Trusted Profile mutation consent @spec @later
- later telemetry exports OpenTelemetry Protocol over HTTP metrics and traces only to an Operator-configured endpoint and does not introduce a Satelle-hosted collection service @spec @later
- telemetry is disabled independently on each Controller and Host by default and requires both telemetry.enabled = true and telemetry.otlp_endpoint in that machine's user-level or Host-owned configuration @spec @later
- telemetry OTLP transport requires HTTPS except for a loopback HTTP collector and follows the same certificate-validation and no-insecure-fallback rules as direct Host transport @spec @later
- optional telemetry endpoint authentication uses a typed Secret Source resolved on the emitting machine and never stores an authorization value inline in Satelle configuration @spec @later
- Satelle telemetry resource attributes are limited to Satelle version, component kind, Controller or Host platform class, and an Operator-configured deployment label; they exclude Host Alias, Host Identity, API Principal, Session, Turn, user, machine, path, address, and prompt-derived identifiers by default @spec @later
- telemetry records contain bounded operation duration, outcome class, typed error code, retry count, queue depth, and resource-usage measurements and never contain command arguments, raw protocol bodies, prompts, transcripts, desktop content, file paths, secret descriptors, or diagnostic artifact contents @spec @later
- telemetry buffering uses an OS-user-private local queue capped at 10 MiB and 24 hours, drops oldest records on overflow, and never blocks command execution or Host control when delivery fails @spec @later
- disabling telemetry stops new capture immediately, deletes queued unsent telemetry for that machine, and does not contact the configured endpoint @spec @later
- satelle telemetry status reports enabled state, endpoint origin without credentials or path secrets, buffered record count and bytes, oldest record age, last delivery outcome, and excluded data categories @spec @later
- satelle allows plaintext HTTP and WebSocket transport only on loopback listeners used locally or through authenticated SSH tunnels @spec @mvp
- satelle rejects plaintext non-loopback HTTP and WebSocket transport @spec @mvp
- satelle requires authenticated HTTPS for HTTP and authenticated WSS for WebSocket on every non-loopback direct Host Daemon connection @spec @mvp
- satelle direct TLS validates the certificate chain and requested Host name against platform trust roots or an explicitly configured user-level CA bundle @spec @mvp
- a configured CA bundle must be a regular non-symlink file owned by the invoking OS user or a trusted system administrator, must not be writable by unrelated principals, and must use an owner-controlled Windows ACL @spec @mvp
- satelle direct TLS requires TLS 1.2 or newer @spec @mvp
- satelle direct TLS reports typed certificate-untrusted, certificate-hostname-mismatch, certificate-expired, and tls-version-unsupported errors before API authentication @spec @mvp
- satelle does not expose an insecure direct-transport option that disables certificate or Host-name verification @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not manage TLS certificate issuance or renewal for non-loopback direct Host Daemon transport @spec @mvp
- satelle non-loopback direct transport relies on user-provided TLS termination or configured TLS materials outside MVP certificate automation @spec @mvp
- when the Host Daemon terminates TLS, its certificate-chain and private-key files must be regular non-symlink files under a Host-owned configuration boundary, and the private key must not be readable or writable by unrelated principals @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon TLS startup fails closed on an unreadable key, unsafe permissions, an expired certificate, or a certificate and private-key mismatch and never falls back to plaintext @spec @mvp
- when TLS terminates in an external reverse proxy, the plaintext Host Daemon backend binds only to loopback and still requires normal Satelle bearer-token authentication and authorization @spec @mvp
- TLS reload installs a new certificate and key atomically only after full validation; failed reload retains the previous valid TLS configuration and emits a typed diagnostic instead of exposing plaintext @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon API authentication uses bearer tokens for MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle stores Host Daemon API bearer tokens in external secret stores or token files instead of inline Satelle configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon generates durable API bearer tokens by default during setup or persistent service installation @spec @mvp
- durable API bearer tokens remain valid until explicitly revoked by default and may instead define an optional expires_at timestamp @spec @mvp
- bearer-token expires_at values are RFC 3339 UTC timestamps evaluated against Host Daemon time @spec @mvp
- expired bearer tokens are rejected before authorization and token metadata reports their optional expiry without exposing token material @spec @mvp
- satelle allows explicitly provided API bearer tokens for automation or managed environments when stored outside inline Satelle configuration @spec @mvp
- an external bearer-token file must be a regular file owned by the resolving OS user; Satelle rejects symlinks, directories, devices, sockets, and files readable or writable by unrelated principals, using mode 0600 on POSIX and an owner-only Windows ACL @spec @mvp
- every Host Daemon bearer token has a stable non-secret token id @spec @mvp
- every Host Daemon bearer token has one or more read, control, admin, and diagnostics_sensitive scopes @spec @mvp
- read scope authorizes readiness, status, Host session metadata, paths, and redacted logs @spec @mvp
- control scope authorizes read operations plus run, steer, stop, and attachment upload @spec @mvp
- admin scope authorizes control operations plus setup, repair, Host lifecycle, Host update, storage migration, token management, and destructive maintenance @spec @mvp
- diagnostics_sensitive scope is required in addition to command-specific consent for Raw Diagnostic Export, recording, and Desktop Snapshot Export operations @spec @mvp
- transport authorization never substitutes for mutation consent, provider-secret consent, raw-diagnostic consent, recording consent, desktop-snapshot consent, or YOLO selection @spec @mvp
- a request with valid authentication but insufficient scope fails with a typed authorization-insufficient-scope error @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon bearer tokens contain at least 256 bits of cryptographically random entropy @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon stores only a one-way token verifier and non-secret token metadata @spec @mvp
- a newly issued raw bearer token is returned exactly once @spec @mvp
- a successful bearer-token issuance or rotation response contains durable token metadata plus raw token material generated for that response and never persisted by Satelle @spec @mvp
- bearer-token verification uses a timing-safe comparison @spec @mvp
- bearer tokens are accepted only through the Authorization header @spec @mvp
- bearer tokens are rejected in URLs, query strings, cookies, JSON bodies, WebSocket subscription messages, command-line arguments, and process environment variables @spec @mvp
- token logs and audit records identify tokens only by non-secret token id @spec @mvp
- admin Principals can rotate or revoke individual bearer tokens without replacing unrelated tokens @spec @mvp
- bearer-token rotation preserves the token id and API Principal identity, increments its credential revision, atomically invalidates the previous verifier, and commits the replacement verifier before returning the replacement raw token @spec @mvp
- token revocation takes effect immediately for new HTTP requests and new WebSocket connections @spec @mvp
- existing WebSocket connections are closed when their authenticating token expires, is revoked, or is rotated @spec @mvp
- failed authentication returns one generic typed authentication-failed response and does not reveal whether a token id exists, is expired, was rotated, was revoked, or has different scopes @spec @mvp
- bearer-token issuance and rotation responses include Cache-Control: no-store @spec @mvp
- initial SSH bootstrap may use one ephemeral API bearer token generated by the Controller for the current bootstrap operation @spec @mvp
- an SSH bootstrap token contains at least 256 bits of cryptographically random entropy and only the scopes required by that bootstrap operation @spec @mvp
- the Controller transmits an SSH bootstrap token through the started Host Daemon process stdin instead of SSH command arguments, remote process arguments, environment variables, or files @spec @mvp
- the bootstrap Host Daemon stores only the ephemeral token verifier in memory @spec @mvp
- an SSH bootstrap token expires after 15 minutes, when the bootstrap Host Daemon exits, or when the bootstrap operation explicitly revokes it, whichever occurs first @spec @mvp
- an SSH bootstrap token is never accepted by a non-loopback listener or a later Host Daemon process @spec @mvp
- SSH bootstrap tokens are never written to Satelle configuration, SQLite, local cache, shell history, logs, events, diagnostics, action ledgers, or service configuration @spec @mvp
- prompt execution after setup uses a durable scoped API token and never reuses an initial SSH bootstrap token @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon API authentication is required for direct, loopback, Tailscale, and SSH-tunneled API connections @spec @mvp
- SSH authentication and Tailscale identity do not replace Host Daemon API authentication or authorization @spec @mvp
- an unauthenticated liveness endpoint may reveal only that the Host Daemon process is alive @spec @mvp
- readiness details, versions, capabilities, Host Identity, and Session metadata require read scope @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not support mTLS client certificate authentication for direct Host Daemon transport @spec @mvp
- satelle later supports optional mutual TLS as defense in depth in addition to scoped bearer-token authentication and authorization @spec @later
- satelle mTLS does not replace bearer token authorization because mTLS authenticates the client connection while Satelle still needs application-layer operation scopes and audit metadata @spec @later
- satelle later mutual TLS uses user-level client certificate, private-key, and CA descriptors with certificate rotation, revocation, service reload, expiry, trust-chain, and cross-platform storage diagnostics @spec @later
- satelle later maps a verified client certificate identity into audit metadata while bearer-token scopes remain authoritative for application operations @spec @later
- satelle Tailscale-backed direct transport still requires Satelle Host Daemon authentication and authorization because Tailscale reachability identity is not the Satelle operation permission model @spec @mvp
- after explicit setup or trust acceptance, the CLI writes the observed stable Host Identity to expected_host_id in the user-level Host Binding @spec @mvp
- any Host Binding with expected_host_id = null permits identity discovery only through explicit setup or trust acceptance and cannot start ordinary Session, log, or maintenance operations @spec @mvp
- all communication after first trust requires the observed Host Identity to match the user-level Host Binding's expected_host_id @spec @mvp
- after first trust, every authenticated HTTP request and WebSocket handshake includes the expected Host Identity through the Satelle-Expected-Host-Identity header, and the Host Daemon compares it before handling the operation or returning protected data @spec @contract @mvp
- a Host Identity mismatch permits only the minimal liveness response and a typed identity-mismatch response containing the expected and observed non-secret identities plus recovery guidance; it returns no other Host, Session, log, readiness, capability, or mutation data @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle host trust --host <alias> as the explicit Host Identity trust operation for an unpinned or replaced Host Binding @spec @mvp
- interactive Host trust displays the transport-authenticated endpoint, observed Host Identity, current expected_host_id, Host Alias, and Desktop Binding before asking for confirmation @spec @mvp
- noninteractive Host trust requires --no-input --yes plus --expected-host-id <exact-id>; --yes alone never accepts a discovered Host Identity @spec @mvp
- replacing a non-null expected_host_id additionally requires --replace and is never implied by setup, repair, host update, project configuration, a Trusted Profile, or ordinary --yes consent @spec @mvp
- setup with expected_host_id = null performs the same Host trust confirmation after the Host Identity becomes reachable and before durable token issuance, provider-secret provisioning, or any subsequent daemon-owned mutation @spec @mvp
- provider-secret provisioning refuses to transmit raw secret material until the observed Host Identity matches the newly pinned or previously configured expected_host_id @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not require local user confirmation before starting a remote Computer Use run on a ready host @spec @mvp
- satelle prompt execution never bypasses host readiness, native Computer Use readiness, or unsupported-capability checks @spec @mvp
- satelle treats instructions visible in remote desktop content as untrusted content that cannot override the operator prompt, consent gates, host policy, YOLO policy, or configured safety boundaries @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not implement Satelle-owned confirmation prompts for individual native Computer Use actions after a prompt turn starts @spec @mvp
- satelle surfaces detected native Codex Computer Use app approvals, operating-system permission prompts, administrator authentication prompts, security prompts, and sensitive-action prompts as action_required events or manual-action-required blockers instead of replacing them with Satelle confirmations @spec @mvp
- satelle does not auto-answer native Codex Computer Use app approvals, operating-system permission prompts, administrator authentication prompts, security prompts, or sensitive-action prompts unless Codex exposes the specific prompt as a documented app-server approval callback that Satelle is allowed to answer @spec @mvp
- satelle only adds Satelle-owned native action confirmation relay after MVP as an opt-in feature guarded by an explicit per-command flag and only when Codex exposes stable native Computer Use action events and accept or deny callbacks @spec @later
- satelle later run and steer use --relay-native-actions as the exact per-command native action confirmation relay opt-in @spec @later
- --relay-native-actions fails before Turn start with typed native-action-relay-not-supported when the Codex adapter does not advertise stable action request plus accept and deny callbacks @spec @later
- every relayed native action request receives an ra_ identifier followed by a canonical lowercase UUIDv7 and emits an action_required event containing that id, a bounded redacted action summary, expiry, Session id, and Turn id without screenshots or raw desktop content @spec @contract @later
- an attached interactive run or steer may answer the currently displayed action request with an explicit allow or deny choice, and the default choice is deny @spec @later
- satelle action respond <action_request_id> --allow and satelle action respond <action_request_id> --deny are the exact detached response commands and require control scope for the owning Session @spec @later
- an unanswered relayed action request expires after 5 minutes or when its Turn becomes terminal, whichever occurs first, and Satelle sends deny when the upstream callback remains available @spec @later
- --relay-native-actions is mutually exclusive with YOLO mode, reports a typed native-action-policy-conflict for that combination, and is never implied by --yes @spec @later
- satelle run and steer support an explicit YOLO option for users who want Codex-controlled approvals to be auto-accepted @implemented @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode is disabled by default and must be selected by a command option, user-level configuration policy, or user-level profile policy @spec @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode does not ask for an additional Satelle confirmation prompt after the user explicitly selects the mode @spec @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode starts or updates the Codex thread with approval policy never and sandbox danger-full-access when the compatible app-server protocol supports those settings @spec @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode auto-accepts documented Codex app-server approval callbacks that Satelle receives and can answer with an accept decision @spec @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode does not bypass host authentication, transport security, host readiness, native Computer Use readiness, or unsupported-platform checks @spec @mvp
- satelle YOLO mode does not grant operating-system privacy permissions, approve administrator authentication, approve security prompts, unlock machines, or click through Codex app UI permission prompts that are not exposed as supported app-server approval callbacks @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed yolo-not-supported error when the remote Codex control plane cannot honor the requested YOLO approval and sandbox behavior @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed yolo-blocked-by-native-approval error when native Computer Use blocks on a non-bypassable OS, app, or sensitive-action approval while YOLO mode is active @spec @mvp

## control-plane
- satelle MVP supports Codex app-server as the only Codex control plane used by the Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not implement multiple Codex protocol backends or terminal-UI scraping backends for remote Computer Use control @spec @mvp
- satelle keeps Codex app-server behind an internal adapter boundary so a future backend can be added without changing the public Satelle API @spec @mvp
- satelle probes the remote Codex app-server protocol for required methods before treating a Codex runtime as compatible @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon startup performs an app-server protocol version and capability handshake before reporting the Codex control plane ready @spec @mvp
- the Codex adapter defines an exact required capability set for Session creation, Turn start, event observation, steering, status, and cancellation @spec @mvp
- absence of a required Codex capability blocks the affected operation with a typed incompatible-control-plane error @spec @mvp
- optional Codex goal methods are capability-gated and never block core Session and Turn control when goals are unavailable @spec @mvp
- unknown app-server notifications are ignored or normalized without changing committed Satelle state @spec @mvp
- raw app-server messages never enter normal logs, errors, events, or SQLite records @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed incompatible-control-plane error when the remote Codex runtime cannot expose the required app-server protocol @spec @mvp
- satelle does not expose app-server over a public unauthenticated listener @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP requires a standalone installer-managed Codex runtime on the remote host instead of treating npm-installed Codex as a supported remote runtime @spec @mvp
- satelle target architecture includes a Satelle Host Daemon running on the controlled remote machine and a local satelle CLI acting as the client @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon binds to loopback by default even when installed as a persistent service @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon non-loopback binding is an explicit configuration choice that requires the direct transport security requirements @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP may bootstrap or run the remote host component through SSH before persistent service installation is implemented @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP starts the remote host component on demand instead of installing a persistent OS service by default @spec @mvp
- satelle run automatically starts the on-demand Host Daemon for SSH bootstrap hosts when it is not already running @spec @mvp
- satelle run requires an already reachable Host Daemon for direct transport hosts and reports a direct-daemon-unreachable error when none is available @spec @mvp
- satelle on-demand Host Daemon stays alive after a session ends for a short configurable idle timeout so follow-up commands can reuse it @spec @mvp
- satelle on-demand Host Daemon default idle timeout is 10 minutes @spec @mvp
- satelle on-demand Host Daemon idle timeout can be configured per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle on-demand Host Daemon idle timeout counts active Turns, active control probes, active maintenance operations, queued Turn Requests, and connected Clients instead of retained Session records @spec @mvp
- retained idle Sessions do not prevent an on-demand Host Daemon from exiting after its idle timeout @spec @mvp
- satelle persistent host service installation is an explicit setup action separate from ordinary prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP can bootstrap the remote host component by uploading a matching self-contained host binary to the remote machine when a supported transport can copy and execute files @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not require Satelle to already be installed on the remote host before prompt execution when bootstrap upload is available @spec @mvp
- satelle bootstrap invokes the uploaded binary in host-daemon mode on the remote machine @spec @mvp
- satelle stores uploaded on-demand host binaries in a user-scoped versioned cache directory on the remote machine instead of temporary directories or global install paths @spec @mvp
- uploaded Host binary cache directories and files are owner-only, and bootstrap rejects a cached binary before execution when it is not a regular file, is a symlink, or is group- or other-writable @spec @mvp
- satelle remote binary cache paths include the Satelle version and target platform so different client and host builds do not overwrite each other @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP never deletes uploaded Host binary cache entries automatically @spec @mvp
- satelle provides an explicit host cleanup command that removes only remote on-demand binary cache entries proven unused by running or persistent Host Daemons and retains the current version plus at least one previous compatible version by default @spec @mvp
- satelle automatic cache cleanup does not remove binaries used by persistent host service installations @spec @mvp
- satelle persistent service installation may reuse the same host binary that on-demand bootstrap uses @spec @mvp
- satelle clients communicate with a Satelle-specific API instead of speaking the Codex app-server protocol directly @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon treats the Codex app-server protocol as an internal adapter boundary behind the Satelle API @spec @mvp
- satelle API exposes host readiness, sessions, goals, turns, state, logs, and errors as Satelle concepts independent from Codex protocol details @spec @mvp

## capabilities
- satelle reports Codex runtime availability, native Computer Use availability, and model-provider compatibility as separate host capabilities @spec @mvp
- satelle validates native Computer Use with a host-side action-path smoke test instead of only checking that a plugin or feature flag exists @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP readiness requires native Codex Computer Use to be installed, enabled, and passing the host-side smoke test @spec @mvp
- the Host Daemon caches every terminal native Computer Use Readiness Result @spec @mvp
- a matching successful native Computer Use Readiness Result no older than 5 minutes is sufficient for native readiness during prompt preflight unless an invalidation condition applies @spec @mvp
- satelle native Computer Use readiness cache time-to-live values are configurable per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon is the canonical store for readiness cache entries because it observes the remote runtime directly @spec @mvp
- satelle CLI may keep read-only readiness cache entries for convenience but must refresh from the Host Daemon before reporting authoritative readiness @spec @mvp
- satelle revalidates host reachability, native Computer Use readiness, and provider Computer Use compatibility before starting prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle does not use native Computer Use readiness cache entries to skip live host reachability or Codex app-server control-plane availability checks before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle does not treat stale cached readiness results as sufficient authorization to start a remote run @spec @mvp
- satelle treats missing, stale, or invalidated native Computer Use readiness cache entries as requiring a live harmless native Computer Use smoke test before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle invalidates native Computer Use readiness cache entries when the target host, OS user or desktop session, Codex version, native Computer Use runtime version, Computer Use plugin version, detectable OS permission state, or detectable app approval state changes @spec @mvp
- satelle retains failed native Computer Use readiness cache entries for diagnostics but does not treat a cached failure as the only current blocker when the host and Codex control plane are reachable for a fresh prompt execution attempt @spec @mvp
- satelle native Computer Use readiness smoke tests use a 120 second timeout by default @spec @mvp
- satelle native Computer Use readiness smoke-test timeout values are configurable per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle timeouts.native_readiness configuration values are human duration strings with explicit units such as "120s" or "2m" @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects bare integer timeouts.native_readiness configuration values with a typed duration-unit-required configuration error @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer do not wait indefinitely for native Computer Use readiness smoke tests before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed native-readiness-timeout error when a native Computer Use readiness smoke test exceeds its effective timeout @spec @mvp
- a native Computer Use readiness smoke-test timeout requests upstream cancellation and blocks prompt execution @spec @mvp
- a timed-out native readiness probe stores a terminal timed_out Readiness Result and releases its Control Lease only after the Codex adapter confirms that no upstream probe Turn remains active @spec @mvp
- when timed-out native readiness probe cancellation cannot be confirmed, Satelle records outcome_unknown diagnostics, keeps the Control Lease recovery_pending, and blocks conflicting Turn or probe admission until reconciliation succeeds @spec @mvp
- satelle does not allow prompt execution or remote-control flows on hosts that fail native Codex Computer Use readiness @spec @mvp
- satelle may keep a host that lacks native Codex Computer Use only for diagnostics, installation, and repair flows @spec @mvp
- satelle host capability checks are OS-aware for Windows, Linux, and macOS instead of assuming one platform's Codex or Computer Use behavior applies to every platform @spec @mvp
- satelle treats cross-platform host support as successful configuration, diagnostics, and capability reporting, not as a guarantee that native Codex Computer Use is available on every operating system @spec @mvp
- satelle Computer Use readiness checks verify standalone Codex installation, authentication, native Computer Use availability, required OS permissions, app-server or remote-control startup, and a harmless observable Computer Use action @spec @mvp
- satelle Computer Use readiness checks return structured pass/fail reasons for each checked prerequisite @spec @mvp
- satelle treats configured model and provider values as requested intent rather than proof that the provider supports native Computer Use @spec @mvp
- satelle proves selected model-provider Computer Use compatibility with a host-side provider smoke test before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests run through the same remote Codex control plane and native Computer Use path that prompt execution will use @spec @mvp
- satelle blocks prompt execution with a typed unsupported-provider-computer-use error when the selected provider or model cannot pass the Computer Use smoke test @spec @mvp
- satelle can use cached provider smoke test results only when the cache key exactly matches the target host, provider, model, Codex version, native Computer Use runtime version, and relevant provider configuration fingerprint @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests create a fresh random nonce and probe session on the remote Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests use a Satelle Provider Probe Surface served by the Host Daemon over a loopback or local-only endpoint on the remote host @spec @mvp
- each Provider Probe Surface binds only to loopback @spec @mvp
- each Provider Probe Surface uses a fresh unguessable capability value valid for exactly one probe attempt @spec @mvp
- a Provider Probe Surface accepts only the expected nonce and expected action result @spec @mvp
- a Provider Probe Surface exposes no user files, cookies, credentials, Session data, Host metadata, or unrelated network proxy behavior @spec @mvp
- provider probe completion closes the listener and invalidates its capability immediately @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests do not depend on external websites, real user accounts, signed-in browser profiles, browser extensions, user files, payment pages, security settings pages, or destructive desktop actions @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests ask Codex native Computer Use to read the probe nonce, perform a harmless visible action, and submit the expected result through the probe surface @spec @mvp
- satelle Host Daemon verifies provider smoke test success from probe surface callbacks or daemon-observed state instead of trusting the model's final message text @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests may use a browser as the probe target only when native Computer Use is operating that browser as an approved desktop target rather than relying solely on the Codex Browser plugin @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests distinguish selected provider or model failure from native Computer Use readiness failures such as missing OS permissions, app approval prompts, locked desktop state, or inability to open the probe target @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests report readiness blockers or manual-action-required when the probe cannot run because native Computer Use cannot access the probe target @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests time out, close or retire the probe surface, and clean up probe session state after completion or failure @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests use a 120 second timeout by default @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test timeout values are configurable per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle timeouts.provider_smoke_test configuration values are human duration strings with explicit units such as "120s" or "2m" @implemented @mvp
- satelle rejects bare integer timeouts.provider_smoke_test configuration values with a typed duration-unit-required configuration error @implemented @mvp
- satelle run and steer do not wait indefinitely for provider smoke tests before prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle reports a typed provider-smoke-test-timeout error when a provider smoke test exceeds its effective timeout @spec @mvp
- a provider smoke-test timeout requests upstream cancellation and blocks prompt execution @spec @mvp
- a timed-out provider probe stores a terminal timed_out Readiness Result and releases its Control Lease only after the Codex adapter confirms that no upstream probe Turn remains active @spec @mvp
- when timed-out provider probe cancellation cannot be confirmed, Satelle records outcome_unknown diagnostics, keeps the Control Lease recovery_pending, and blocks conflicting Turn or probe admission until reconciliation succeeds @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke tests store normalized pass/fail metadata and typed failure reasons but do not store screenshots, full transcripts, or desktop recordings by default @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke test cache misses during prompt execution trigger a live provider smoke test when the selected provider requires experimental provider Computer Use and the user has opted into that experimental mode @spec @mvp
- satelle live provider smoke test failures block prompt execution and store the normalized failure result in the Host Daemon cache @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke test cache hits, live refreshes, and failures are distinguishable in preflight, doctor, and JSON output @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test cache successful results are trusted for 24 hours by default when the cache key still exactly matches the target host, provider, model, Codex version, native Computer Use runtime version, and relevant provider configuration fingerprint @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test cache failed results are trusted for 10 minutes by default when the cache key still exactly matches the target host, provider, model, Codex version, native Computer Use runtime version, and relevant provider configuration fingerprint @spec @mvp
- satelle treats expired provider smoke-test cache entries as cache misses for prompt execution @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test cache time-to-live values are configurable per host or profile @spec @mvp
- satelle preflight and JSON output identify when provider Computer Use compatibility came from cache and include the cached result age or expiry metadata @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test refresh during run or steer ignores matching cached pass and fail entries and replaces them with the new live smoke-test result @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test refresh during run or steer still blocks prompt execution when the live smoke test fails @spec @mvp
- satelle provider smoke-test refresh during run or steer is distinct from doctor provider refresh because run and steer refresh validate immediately before a real prompt turn while doctor refresh validates without starting prompt execution @spec @mvp

## computer-use
- satelle prefers native Codex Computer Use installed on the remote host over custom screenshot and input automation @spec @mvp
- satelle detects when native Codex Computer Use is unavailable on a configured remote host and reports the missing capability to the user @spec @mvp
- satelle offers assisted installation for missing Codex or native Codex Computer Use prerequisites but requires explicit user confirmation before running remote install commands @spec @mvp
- satelle run, steer, and status do not install Codex, Computer Use plugins, OS permissions, or app approvals as side effects @implemented @mvp
- satelle doctor reports missing Codex runtime, Computer Use plugin, OS permissions, app approvals, authentication, unsupported operating system, and unsupported region as separate readiness blockers when those blockers can be detected @spec @mvp
- satelle provides an explicit host setup or repair command for guided Codex and native Computer Use prerequisite setup on supported hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle setup in an interactive terminal is an applying onboarding flow by default instead of a preview-only command @spec @mvp
- satelle setup presents planned remote install, update, and configuration actions before mutating the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup and repair ask for one final cliclack confirmation after presenting the planned remote mutations and before running install, update, service, or configuration actions @spec @mvp
- satelle interactive setup and repair treat the user's earlier setup selections as configuration input rather than final consent to mutate the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair skip the final interactive mutation confirmation when --yes is present @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair do not ask for a final mutation confirmation when the resolved action plan contains no remote mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair treat a user choosing No at the final mutation confirmation as a clean cancelled no-op rather than an error @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair exit 0 after a user chooses No at the final mutation confirmation because the command completed without applying changes @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair do not start the remote mutation executor after a user chooses No at the final mutation confirmation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair human output reports No changes applied. after a user chooses No at the final mutation confirmation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair JSON output reports status cancelled, changed false, applied_actions as an empty list, and cancellation_reason user_declined_confirmation after a user chooses No at the final mutation confirmation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair treat Ctrl-C or an interrupted cliclack prompt as an interrupt distinct from a user choosing No at the final mutation confirmation @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair exit 130 for Ctrl-C or an interrupted cliclack prompt when the platform reports an interrupt signal to the process @spec @mvp
- satelle setup may install or update the standalone Codex runtime and Satelle host binary when the target operating system and transport support the required actions @spec @mvp
- satelle repair may update the standalone Codex runtime or Satelle host binary only when live probes show the installed component is missing, corrupted, unsupported, below the required minimum version, incompatible with the required control-plane protocol, or blocking native Computer Use readiness @spec @mvp
- satelle repair does not perform opportunistic upgrades to the latest Codex runtime or Satelle host binary when the installed components are compatible and current readiness checks can pass @spec @mvp
- satelle repair action plans identify the current version, target version, compatibility reason, and source of the version requirement before proposing a Codex runtime or Satelle host binary upgrade @spec @mvp
- satelle repair upgrade actions follow the same plan presentation, final confirmation, --dry-run, --yes, --no-input --yes, setup action ledger, and partial-failure rules as other setup and repair mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle repair reports manual-action-required when a required compatibility or readiness upgrade cannot be automated safely on the target operating system or transport @spec @mvp
- satelle ordinary non-repair upgrades are explicit setup or host maintenance actions instead of side effects of repair @spec @mvp
- satelle repair may recommend satelle host update as a follow-up when a newer compatible component is available but not required for current readiness or control-plane compatibility @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair execute remote mutations as an ordered idempotent action plan with stable action identifiers @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair record each started, completed, failed, and skipped setup action in a host-side setup action ledger before reporting final status @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair stop executing remaining remote mutations after the first failed required setup action @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair do not automatically roll back previously completed install, update, service, or configuration actions after a later setup action fails @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair may clean up temporary artifacts created solely by the failed action when cleanup is local to that action and does not undo previously completed setup actions @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair preserve partial setup state after a failed action so a later repair command can inspect and continue from the recorded host state @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair report a typed setup-partially-applied error when at least one remote mutation completed before a later required setup action failed @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair use the remote execution failure exit-code class for setup-partially-applied because the command attempted remote mutation and did not reach the requested final state @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair human partial-failure output states the failed action, the completed actions, the skipped actions, the preserved remote state, and the next repair command @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair JSON partial-failure output includes status partial_failure, changed true, completed_actions, failed_action, skipped_actions, preserved_state, and recovery_command fields @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair report a typed setup-action-failed error instead of setup-partially-applied when a required setup action fails before any remote mutation completes @spec @mvp
- satelle setup supports --dry-run to preview planned setup actions without mutating the selected host @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup supports --no-input for automation and fails with a typed input-required error when required interactive choices or confirmations are missing @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup in non-interactive mode does not run remote install, update, service, or configuration mutations unless an explicit non-interactive consent option is provided @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair use --yes as the exact explicit consent option for accepting ordinary setup mutations without an interactive confirmation prompt @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair do not use a separate apply subcommand or --apply flag in MVP because interactive setup is already the normal applying onboarding flow @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair in non-interactive mode require --no-input --yes before running remote install, update, service, or configuration mutations @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --yes and repair --yes do not synthesize missing setup choices; required values that cannot be inferred still produce a typed input-required error when prompts are disabled @spec @mvp
- satelle --yes does not bypass manual-action-required blockers, unsupported platform constraints, operating-system privacy prompts, administrator authentication, security prompts, app approvals, or native Computer Use readiness failures @spec @mvp
- satelle accepts --yes only for commands whose specification explicitly defines it as noninteractive consent after presenting a mutation or sensitive-output plan @spec @mvp
- satelle never treats --yes by itself as prompt-execution approval, YOLO enablement, provider-secret consent, raw-diagnostic consent, recording consent, or desktop-snapshot consent @spec @mvp
- satelle setup --dry-run and repair --dry-run never mutate the remote host even when --yes is present @spec @mvp
- satelle setup and repair help text describes --yes as accepting ordinary setup mutations, not as YOLO mode or prompt-execution auto-approval @implemented @mvp
- satelle repair follows the same interactive, dry-run, no-input, and non-interactive consent rules as setup @spec @mvp
- satelle setup reports manual-action-required when Codex app settings, OS privacy permissions, app approvals, administrator authentication, security prompts, or unsupported platform constraints cannot be automated safely @spec @mvp
- satelle setup default success means required binaries, authentication, service configuration, selected desktop session metadata, and detectable native Computer Use permissions appear configured for the target host @spec @mvp
- satelle setup does not run the live native Computer Use readiness smoke test by default @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup does not move the pointer, type, capture screenshots, open a probe surface, or ask Codex native Computer Use to operate the desktop as part of ordinary onboarding @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup invalidates affected native Computer Use readiness cache entries when it installs, updates, repairs, or reconfigures Codex runtime, native Computer Use components, OS permission state, app approval state, desktop binding, desktop session preference, or Host Daemon service configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle setup without --verify does not create a successful native Computer Use readiness cache entry because detectable prerequisite checks are not proof of the action path @spec @mvp
- satelle setup human output and JSON output report native Computer Use readiness as not_verified when no live readiness smoke test was run @implemented @mvp
- satelle setup output recommends satelle doctor --scope computer-use --refresh for explicit readiness verification without starting prompt execution @implemented @mvp
- satelle refuses prompt execution on hosts that still fail native Computer Use readiness after setup or repair @spec @mvp

## transport
- satelle treats Tailscale as an optional first-class private connectivity option for reaching configured remote hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle does not require Tailscale for core remote host configuration or execution flows @spec @mvp
- satelle supports connectivity paths that are not exclusive to Tailscale @spec @mvp
- satelle does not assume Tailscale SSH is available on Windows hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle host configuration is transport-agnostic and represents remote host capabilities independently from the connectivity method used to reach the host @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP includes first-class optional Tailscale support rather than treating Tailscale as a post-MVP recipe @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale support includes host reachability checks, tailnet address resolution guidance, and transport diagnostics for Tailscale-backed hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle models Tailscale as an optional network provider for SSH and direct Host Daemon transports @spec @mvp
- satelle host configuration may include a small Tailscale-specific block when the host selects Tailscale as its network provider @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale-specific configuration stays scoped to Tailscale-backed hosts instead of adding Tailscale fields to every host shape @spec @mvp
- satelle detects the local tailscale CLI and Tailscale login or daemon status when diagnosing Tailscale-backed hosts @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale diagnostics can report partial results without the tailscale CLI by validating configuration shape and explaining which live checks were skipped @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale diagnostics provide full live reachability and status checks only when the tailscale CLI or equivalent local status source is available @spec @mvp
- satelle reads Tailscale status data when available to validate configured tailnet host visibility and suggest Tailscale DNS or IP addresses @spec @mvp
- satelle validates Tailscale-backed host reachability with Tailscale-aware diagnostics when available @spec @mvp
- satelle does not automatically run tailscale up, edit tailnet ACLs, or call the Tailscale admin API in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP includes an explicit Tailscale Serve setup helper for exposing a remote Host Daemon to the user's tailnet when a host uses Tailscale-backed direct transport @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale Serve setup runs against the remote host's Tailscale daemon because the exposed service is the remote Host Daemon, not the local CLI @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale Serve setup is never run automatically by run, steer, status, or doctor commands @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale Serve setup separates preview from apply so users can inspect the planned tailscale serve change before Satelle mutates remote Tailscale configuration @spec @mvp
- satelle Tailscale Serve setup preserves unrelated existing Tailscale Serve configuration instead of resetting or overwriting the remote node's full Serve state @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP does not configure Tailscale Funnel or public internet exposure as a normal setup path @spec @mvp
- satelle warns when a configuration attempts to use Tailscale Funnel or public exposure for desktop-control access @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP supports SSH transport for bootstrap, file upload, remote command execution, and tunneled access to the on-demand Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle MVP supports direct HTTPS and WSS transport for already reachable or persistently installed Host Daemons @spec @mvp
- satelle models Tailscale as optional reachability and address resolution for supported transports rather than as a separate execution model @spec @mvp
- satelle treats direct authenticated HTTPS and WSS access to the Host Daemon as the preferred runtime transport when the daemon is already reachable @spec @mvp
- satelle treats system OpenSSH as the default SSH backend for bootstrap and repair because it preserves user SSH configuration, agents, hardware keys, jump hosts, known hosts, and Tailscale SSH behavior @spec @mvp
- satelle SSH bootstrap does not assume a POSIX shell on the remote host and uses OS-aware command execution, quoting, path, and file-copy behavior for Windows, Linux, and macOS @spec @mvp
- satelle never disables OpenSSH Host-key verification automatically @spec @mvp
- satelle never accepts a changed SSH Host key automatically @spec @mvp
- first-use SSH Host-key acceptance requires normal OpenSSH interactive confirmation or preconfigured known-host state @spec @mvp
- noninteractive SSH bootstrap fails with a typed ssh-host-key-verification-required error when trust cannot be established without prompting @spec @mvp
- project-level configuration cannot supply raw OpenSSH options, ProxyCommand values, identity paths, or executable overrides @spec @mvp
- satelle constructs OpenSSH argv values without invoking a local shell @spec @mvp
- remote prompts, bearer tokens, provider secrets, and raw configuration are never embedded in SSH command strings @spec @mvp
- SSH bootstrap tunnels bind only to Controller loopback by default @spec @mvp
- Host Daemon API authentication remains required inside an SSH tunnel @spec @mvp
- uploaded Host Daemon binaries are verified against release integrity metadata before remote execution @spec @mvp
- uploaded binaries are staged under generated names and atomically promoted only after verification @spec @mvp
- remote bootstrap stdout used as a machine protocol is size-bounded and separated from diagnostic stderr @spec @mvp
- satelle supports direct transport for hosts where SSH bootstrap is unavailable but a Host Daemon is already installed and reachable @spec @mvp

# research

## native-computer-use
- satelle Windows readiness diagnostics inspect the current supported Codex Computer Use app policy without hard-coding a version-independent configuration path @spec @mvp
- satelle supports the current Windows Codex app policy in $CODEX_HOME/config.toml under computer_use.windows with always_allowed_app_ids @spec @mvp
- satelle treats older $CODEX_HOME/computer-use/config.toml allow-list entries as upstream migration input and does not depend on the removed denied-list schema @spec @mvp
- satelle capability probes, not a remembered documentation path, determine whether a Codex release exposes the required native Computer Use app policy and approval behavior @spec @mvp
- satelle does not treat native Codex Computer Use sensitive-action prompts as a complete Satelle policy guarantee unless Codex exposes a stable capability or event contract for those prompts @spec @mvp

## model-providers
- satelle defaults model and provider selection to the configured Codex model and provider on the remote host @spec @mvp
- satelle supports explicit per-run model and provider overrides when the remote host can validate the requested combination @spec @mvp
- satelle project-level model and provider defaults are treated as shared intent and must resolve through user-level or host-owned provider bindings before execution @spec @mvp
- satelle does not write provider credentials or project-defined provider endpoint data into the remote Codex configuration as a side effect of resolving project model defaults @spec @mvp
- satelle requires an explicit experimental provider Computer Use option before attempting native Computer Use with a non-OpenAI provider @spec @mvp
- satelle experimental non-OpenAI provider Computer Use opt-in must come from a CLI flag or user-level configuration rather than project-level configuration @implemented @mvp
- satelle supports non-OpenAI provider Computer Use only as an explicit experimental mode guarded by warning text and a live remote smoke test @spec @mvp
- satelle caches non-OpenAI provider Computer Use smoke test results by host, provider, model, Codex version, and native Computer Use runtime version @spec @mvp
- satelle can refresh a cached non-OpenAI provider Computer Use smoke test result on demand @spec @mvp
- satelle reports providers that pass normal Codex text turns but fail the Computer Use smoke test as unsupported for native Computer Use on that host @spec @mvp
- satelle treats text-only or Chat-Completions-only providers as incompatible with native visual Computer Use unless a configured proxy supplies the required Responses-compatible visual/tool semantics @spec @mvp
- satelle does not allow a non-OpenAI provider smoke test cache miss to start prompt execution without first running a live smoke test during preflight or failing with an experimental-provider-not-validated error when the live test cannot be run @spec @mvp

# docs
- satelle MVP public documentation uses Fumadocs as the documentation site framework @spec @mvp
- satelle repository README states project status, supported platforms, implemented release surface, security model, development commands, and the shortest successful-use example @spec @mvp
- satelle public repository includes the license file matching the workspace package metadata before preview publication @spec @mvp
- satelle public repository includes a security policy describing vulnerability reporting and sensitive diagnostic handling before preview publication @spec @mvp
- satelle ships a Satelle Agent Skill Bundle as embedded SKILL.md content for AI agents that need to set up, operate, or recover Satelle @spec @mvp
- satelle Agent Skill Bundle contains separate setup, use, recover, and router skills instead of one sprawling skill covering every Satelle workflow @spec @mvp
- satelle embedded skills are Satelle-owned product guidance and not a general-purpose user skill registry, plugin marketplace, or arbitrary skill execution system @spec @mvp
- satelle exposes satelle skills list, satelle skills get <name>, and satelle skills path <name> so AI clients can discover or install bundled Satelle skills without scraping documentation pages @spec @mvp
- satelle bundled setup skill guides AI agents through safe noninteractive setup planning, secret-source descriptor handling, consent boundaries, and readiness verification @spec @mvp
- satelle bundled use skill guides AI agents through run, steer, status, logs, stop, event modes, output formats, and session continuation rules @spec @mvp
- satelle bundled recover skill guides AI agents through doctor, config check, logs, setup repair, and host update without guessing at remote state @spec @mvp
- satelle later extends the bundled recover skill with support bundle escalation when the matching CLI release supports diagnostic bundles @spec @later
- satelle bundled router skill names the setup, use, and recover skills and routes agents to the smallest skill that covers the current Satelle task @spec @mvp
- satelle bundled skills are versioned with the Satelle CLI release and document the CLI behavior for that same release instead of floating independently from the binary @spec @mvp
- satelle skills list and satelle skills get report the Agent Skill Bundle release version @spec @mvp
- satelle release validation proves embedded Agent Skill Bundle bytes match the release source copies byte for byte @spec @mvp
- satelle release validation smoke-tests every bundled skill command example against the matching release binary @spec @mvp
- satelle bundled skills do not include user secrets, host-specific configuration, prompts, session transcripts, screenshots, or generated diagnostic artifacts @spec @mvp
- satelle Fumadocs setup is not a prerequisite for the first Rust CLI and Host Daemon skeleton implementation @spec @mvp
- satelle Fumadocs setup happens after the first Rust CLI and Host Daemon skeleton establishes stable top-level commands, configuration surfaces, and setup flow names @spec @mvp
- satelle Fumadocs setup happens before public MVP release hardening so documentation, CLI help output, and .facts can be reviewed together before publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle first public MVP release requires a Fumadocs documentation site covering installation, setup onboarding, run, steer, status, logs, doctor, configuration, provider authentication, Trusted Profiles, transports, Tailscale support, YOLO mode, diagnostics, and security boundaries @spec @mvp
- satelle Fumadocs documentation follows the Diataxis structure with tutorials, how-to guides, reference pages, and explanation pages instead of a single flat README-style manual @spec @mvp
- satelle .facts remains the product specification source of truth, and Fumadocs pages are user-facing documentation derived from .facts, CLI help output, and implemented behavior @spec @mvp
- satelle Fumadocs build dependencies are documentation and release-time dependencies only and are not runtime dependencies for the Rust CLI, Host Daemon, or remote host artifacts @spec @mvp
- satelle documentation CI rejects broken internal links, missing local assets, and command examples that do not parse against the matching release binary @spec @mvp
- satelle versioned documentation identifies the Satelle release whose CLI, API, schemas, and bundled skills it describes @spec @mvp
- satelle generated command and schema reference is derived from the release binary or public domain types instead of manually duplicating field lists @spec @mvp

# release
- satelle uses Tegami as the preferred changelog, versioning, and publishing workflow once release automation is introduced @spec @mvp
- satelle public MVP release requires a documented security and legal language review for remote desktop control behavior, YOLO mode language, diagnostic export boundaries, provider credential handling, and user-consent wording before public publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle Tegami setup uses the Cargo plugin for Rust workspace package discovery, version bumps, and dependency range updates without enabling crates.io publishing for the MVP public release @spec @mvp
- satelle treats Tegami as release tooling and does not make Node.js or Tegami part of the runtime dependency chain for the Rust CLI or Host Daemon @spec @mvp
- satelle may configure Tegami before the first public MVP release so changelog, versioning, and publish orchestration behavior can be validated early without making Tegami a runtime dependency @spec @mvp
- satelle does not rely on Tegami for production publishing until a repo-local release dry run verifies Tegami's Node.js 24 requirement, Cargo plugin behavior, Rust workspace package discovery, changelog generation, version bump output, dependency range updates, and compatibility with Satelle GitHub release and npm-registry publishing artifacts @spec @mvp
- satelle first MVP public release uses Tegami for changelog, versioning, and publishing orchestration only if the release dry run passes and the generated changes are reviewed before publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle first MVP public release falls back to the documented manual release runbook when Tegami validation fails, while keeping Tegami as the preferred release workflow after the blocker is fixed @spec @mvp
- satelle Tegami-driven MVP release workflow builds Satelle release artifacts outside Tegami or through an explicit Tegami hook because Tegami publishes package contents and does not replace Rust binary build, signing, checksum, or artifact-attestation steps @spec @mvp
- satelle Tegami-driven MVP release workflow does not publish crates.io packages unless a later release fact explicitly enables crates.io publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle Tegami validation records the checked Tegami version, Node.js version, Cargo plugin behavior, generated files, and skipped publish targets before production publishing is allowed @spec @mvp
- satelle first MVP public release publishes GitHub release assets and npm-registry packages but does not publish a crates.io crate @spec @mvp
- satelle release workflow may run cargo package or cargo publish --dry-run to validate future crates.io readiness without uploading a crate to crates.io @spec @mvp
- satelle does not publish a placeholder crates.io package only to reserve the satelle crate name @spec @mvp
- satelle later crates.io publishing provides a binary-only cargo install satelle surface and does not promise a stable public Rust library API initially @spec @later
- Satelle internal Rust workspace crates remain unpublished when the binary-only crates.io package is introduced @spec @later
- satelle crates.io publishing requires documented Cargo SemVer commitments, package owner policy, package contents policy, and CI-only publish controls before it can become part of a public release @spec @later
- satelle crates.io package versions, when introduced, use the same Satelle release version as GitHub release assets and npm-registry packages @spec @later
- satelle crates.io publication remains a later release milestone rather than an MVP release blocker @spec @later
- satelle ordinary public release flow starts with a release pull request before any public package or binary publishing occurs @spec @mvp
- satelle release pull request updates version metadata, Tegami changelog output, package lockfiles, generated package manifests, and release configuration needed for the target version @spec @mvp
- satelle release pull request verification builds and validates release candidate artifacts without publishing public npm packages or final GitHub release assets @spec @mvp
- satelle public publish workflow is triggered by pushing a protected version tag matching vX.Y.Z after the release pull request has merged to the default branch @spec @mvp
- satelle public publish workflow does not run from release pull request merge alone @spec @mvp
- satelle public publish workflow verifies that the version tag, committed version metadata, Tegami changelog output, npm package metadata, native artifact metadata, and integrity metadata all describe the same version before publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle release version tags are annotated Git tags instead of lightweight Git tags @spec @mvp
- satelle release version tags are signed with a GitHub-verifiable GPG, SSH, or S/MIME signing identity controlled by an authorized releaser @spec @mvp
- satelle repository uses an active GitHub tag ruleset for release tags matching v* to restrict tag creation, updates, deletion, and force pushes to authorized releasers or approved release automation @spec @mvp
- satelle public publish workflow verifies the triggering release tag is annotated, signed, GitHub-verifiable, matches vX.Y.Z, and points at the default-branch commit produced by the merged release pull request before publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle public publish workflow rejects lightweight, unsigned, unverified, moved, deleted, or wrong-target release tags with a typed release-tag-not-trusted error @spec @mvp
- satelle authorized releasers may create and push signed release tags from local developer machines after the release pull request has merged because tag creation is a release trigger, not public artifact publishing @spec @mvp
- satelle signed release tags and GitHub tag rulesets complement npm provenance, GitHub artifact attestations, and immutable release assets instead of replacing them @spec @mvp
- satelle workflow_dispatch release runs are limited to dry-run, diagnostics, or non-publishing recovery tasks in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle workflow_dispatch release runs do not publish public npm packages or final GitHub release assets in MVP @spec @mvp
- satelle release archives use the canonical name satelle-v<version>-<target>.tar.gz on Unix targets and satelle-v<version>-<target>.zip on Windows targets @spec @mvp
- satelle release workflow publishes SHA-256 digests for every release archive in a canonical SHA256SUMS manifest @spec @mvp
- every Satelle release archive contains exactly one executable at its root, named satelle on Unix and satelle.exe on Windows @spec @contract @mvp
- release validation extracts every archive and verifies executable name, root layout, executable mode where applicable, reported version, target identity, and digest before publication @spec @release-gate @verification @mvp
- release validation checks the archive target against its expected matrix entry through archive naming plus binary format, architecture, and libc-family inspection where applicable instead of trusting archive naming alone @spec @release-gate @verification @mvp
- satelle release validation compares every npm native package binary digest with the corresponding GitHub release archive binary digest @spec @mvp
- satelle initial npm publication publishes platform-native packages before the scoped top-level package and publishes the unscoped forwarding package last @spec @mvp
- the public GitHub release remains draft until every required npm package is registry-visible and passes clean-install smoke tests @spec @mvp
- a partial npm publication failure stops later package publication and records which immutable versions already exist plus an idempotent recovery procedure @spec @mvp
- release recovery never moves the signed version tag or republishes different bytes under an already published package version @spec @mvp
- the release-candidate offline JSON smoke command is satelle paths --json and must emit schema_version satelle.paths.v1 before target-specific online smoke tests run @release-gate @verification @mvp @spec
- release-candidate validation installs, executes the --version contract, runs satelle paths --json, upgrades, and uninstalls Satelle on every Controller target @spec @verification @mvp

# verification

## pull-request
- label: Rust workspace formatting passes
  command: cargo fmt --all -- --check
  tags: [implemented, ci, mvp]
- label: Rust workspace linting passes with warnings denied
  command: cargo clippy --workspace --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings
  tags: [implemented, ci, mvp]
- label: Rust workspace tests pass
  command: cargo test --workspace --all-targets --all-features
  tags: [implemented, ci, mvp]
- label: No CI-tagged fact is manual
  command: test -z "$(facts list --tags ci --manual --light | sed -n '/^-/p')"
  tags: [implemented, ci, mvp]
- label: Rust workspace release build passes with warnings denied
  command: RUSTFLAGS="-D warnings" cargo build --workspace --release --locked
  tags: [ci, mvp, implemented]

## contract-suites
- the ci tag is reserved for command-bearing facts, while manual conformance and release-gate requirements use the verification tag until an executable mapping exists @spec @mvp
- every versioned JSON and NDJSON surface has contract tests for schema_version, required fields, enum tokens, stdout, stderr, and exit status @spec @verification @mvp
- parser failures and semantic validation failures share the same human and JSON error conformance suite @spec @verification @mvp
- direct and SSH-tunneled Host Daemon transports pass one shared API and Session conformance suite @spec @verification @mvp
- concurrent admission tests prove that one Control Lease cannot create two active Turns across processes @spec @verification @mvp
- stop and completion race tests prove that exactly one immutable terminal Turn state wins @spec @verification @mvp
- Host Daemon restart tests prove recovery_pending reconciliation before replacement Turn admission @spec @verification @mvp
- setup, repair, Host update, self-update remotes, and doctor fix have no-mutation dry-run tests @spec @verification @mvp
- later storage migration and config repair have no-mutation dry-run tests @spec @verification @later
- a canary secret and canary prompt are absent from every normal log, error, event, setup ledger, status result, and public API response @spec @verification @mvp
- later diagnostic bundle and Raw Diagnostic Export redaction tests remove canary secrets from every artifact category covered by the declared redaction policy @spec @verification @later
- project configuration trust tests prove a checkout cannot replace a concrete Host Binding, redirect an endpoint, select an unauthorized binding, or activate consent and YOLO policy @spec @verification @mvp
- each declared Controller target has release-candidate build, install, upgrade, smoke, and uninstall coverage @spec @verification @mvp
- each declared Computer Use Host Platform has end-to-end setup, readiness, run, status, steer, stop, reconnect, and recovery coverage @spec @verification @mvp
- bundled skill commands and documentation command examples parse against the same release binary @spec @verification @mvp
